/** Etymology data for lemma IDs in chunk 9 */
export const etymologyChunk9: Record<number, string> = {
  "4312": "يَتَخَبَّطُ and related words stem from the root خ-ب-ط, with the root verb خَبَطَ meaning \"he struck,\" \"he walked aimlessly,\" or \"he acted foolishly.\" خَبَّطَ means \"he struck repeatedly\" or \"he caused confusion or disorder.\" يَتَخَبَّطُ means \"he struggles wildly in confusion or disorder,\" \"he moves erratically,\" or \"he is in reckless instability.\" The root conveys themes of chaotic movement, instability, and lack of control, often linked to affliction or turmoil. Reckless, aimless actions mirror deeper disorder—whether physical, mental, or moral—where deviation from sound judgment leads to confusion and imbalance, illustrating the destructive impact of straying from clarity and upright conduct.",
  "4313": "يَتَخَطَّفَكُمُ and related words stem from the root خ-ط-ف, with the root verb خَطِفَ meaning \"he snatched\" or \"he took away swiftly.\" خَطَّفَ means \"he snatched repeatedly or intensively,\" and تَخَطَّفَ means \"they repeatedly snatch from one another\" or \"they were repeatedly snatched away and dispersed.\" يَتَخَطَّفَكُمُ means \"he/it repeatedly snatches you away and disperses you,\" often referring to being attacked, abducted, or driven from one's land. The root conveys suddenness, swiftness, and abrupt action, often with force and unpredictability. The connection highlights the recurring and forceful nature of being taken or scattered, emphasizing vulnerability, instability, and the loss of security.",
  "4314": "يَتَخَلَّفُوا and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ف, with the root verb خَلَفَ meaning \"he came after\" or \"he succeeded.\" The root conveys succession, substitution, and contrast, where one follows another or remains in place of something else. يَتَخَلَّفُوا means \"they lag behind\" or \"they stay back,\" emphasizing inaction, hesitation, or failure to advance when required. This reflects the consequences of neglecting responsibilities, whether due to reluctance, weakness, or deliberate avoidance, highlighting the contrast between those who move forward and those who fall behind.",
  "4315": "يَتَخَيَّرُونَ and related words stem from the root خ-ي-ر, with the root verb خَارَ meaning \"he chose or preferred\" or \"he sought what was best or most beneficial.\" The root revolves around goodness, preference, and choice, conveying the act of selecting what is most beneficial or superior. يَتَخَيَّرُونَ means \"they choose carefully\" or \"they select,\" emphasizing a deliberate and thoughtful selection process. The connection to the root highlights the importance of discernment and wisdom in making choices, ensuring that what is chosen aligns with benefit, excellence, and purpose.",
  "4316": "يَتَدَبَّرُونَ and related words stem from the root د-ب-ر, with the root verb دَبَرَ meaning \"it came after or followed\" or \"he turned his back or went away.\" تَدَبَّرَ means \"he reflected upon\" or \"he considered deeply,\" while يَتَدَبَّرُونَ means \"they reflect,\" emphasizing ongoing and personal engagement with deeper meanings. The root revolves around sequence, planning, and consequence, conveying the idea of examining what follows, understanding outcomes, and thoughtful deliberation. The connection highlights how true reflection involves looking beyond the present, considering consequences, and understanding matters with foresight and depth.",
  "4317": "يَتَرَاجَعَا and related words stem from the root ر-ج-ع, with the root verb رَجَعَ meaning \"he returned\" or \"he went back.\" يَتَرَاجَعَا means \"they return to one another\" or \"they reconsider.\" The connection lies in the reciprocal action of returning or reverting among parties, reflecting the root's emphasis on mutual reversal. This term conveys themes of dialogue, mutual understanding, and the reassessment of decisions or relationships.",
  "4318": "يَتَرَدَّدُ and related words stem from the root ر-د-د, with the root verb رَدَّ meaning \"he returned,\" \"he repelled,\" or \"he rejected.\" يَتَرَدَّدُ means \"he hesitates,\" \"he wavers,\" or \"he frequents.\" The connection lies in the repeated action of going back and forth, embodying the root's essence of returning. It reflects indecision or continual movement between options, highlighting the human tendency to hesitate and the importance of resolve.",
  "4319": "يَتَرَقَّبُ and related words stem from the root ر-ق-ب, with the root verb رَقَبَ meaning \"he watched\" or \"he observed.\" يَتَرَقَّبُ means \"he watches\" or \"he awaits expectantly.\" The connection lies in the ongoing action of vigilant observation, embodying the root's emphasis on watchfulness. This term reflects the continuous state of anticipation, highlighting the importance of being prepared and attentive.",
  "4320": "يَتَسَاءَلُونَ and related words stem from the root س-أ-ل, with the root verb سَأَلَ meaning \"he asked.\" يَتَسَاءَلُونَ means \"they ask one another\" or \"they inquire among themselves.\" The connection lies in mutual questioning and discussion, embodying the root's concept of asking. يَتَسَاءَلُونَ reflects the human tendency to seek understanding through dialogue and the sharing of ideas.",
  "4321": "يَتَسَلَّلُ and related words stem from the root س-ل-ل, with the root verb سَلَّ meaning \"he drew out,\" \"he extracted,\" or \"he removed gently.\" يَتَسَلَّلُ means \"he slips away,\" \"he sneaks away,\" or \"he withdraws stealthily.\" The connection lies in the subtle act of extracting oneself from a situation, reflecting the root's concept of gentle removal. It emphasizes the stealth and discretion involved in leaving unnoticed, highlighting themes of secrecy, avoidance, or retreat.",
  "4322": "يَتَسَنَّهْ and related words stem from the root س-ن-ه, with the root verb سَنِهَ meaning \"it changed with time\" or \"it aged.\" يَتَسَنَّهْ means \"it becomes old\" or \"it decays.\" The connection reflects the process of aging or deterioration over time. It emphasizes the transient nature of worldly things and the inevitable change that comes with the passage of time.",
  "4323": "يَتَضَرَّعُ and related words stem from the root ض-ر-ع, with the root verb ضَرَعَ meaning \"he was humble\" or \"he supplicated.\" يَتَضَرَّعُ means \"he supplicates\" or \"he humbles himself,\" indicating ongoing action. The connection lies in the continuous practice of humility and earnest prayer, directly relating to the root's focus on submissiveness. This term highlights the importance of persistent devotion and reliance on Allah's (ﷻ) mercy.",
  "4324": "يَتَعَارَفُونَ and related words stem from the root ع-ر-ف, with the root verb عَرَفَ meaning \"he knew,\" \"he recognized,\" or \"he perceived.\" يَتَعَارَفُونَ means \"they mutually recognize each other,\" \"they become acquainted,\" or \"they get to know one another.\" The nuance here is the reciprocal action of gaining knowledge or recognition, emphasizing social interaction and mutual understanding. This reflects the root's concept of knowledge and recognition, extended to the establishment of relationships and the building of communities through mutual acquaintance.",
  "4325": "يَتَعَدَّىٰ and related words stem from the root ع-د-و, with the root verb عَدَا meaning \"he transgressed\" or \"he acted aggressively.\" يَتَعَدَّىٰ means \"he transgresses\" or \"he exceeds limits.\" The connection lies in the ongoing action of overstepping boundaries, directly relating to the root's emphasis on transgression. This term serves as a reminder to be vigilant against continuous wrongful actions, emphasizing the importance of self-restraint and adherence to moral guidelines.",
  "4326": "يَتَعَلَّمُونَ and related words stem from the root ع-ل-م, with the root verb عَلِمَ meaning \"he knew,\" \"he became aware,\" or \"he understood,\" and عَلَّمَ meaning \"he taught\" or \"he caused to know.\" يَتَعَلَّمُونَ means \"they learn\" or \"they are learning,\" emphasizing an active and ongoing effort to acquire knowledge. The connection lies in the root's focus on awareness, understanding, and the dissemination of knowledge, as well as the personal growth that results from learning. This reflects a dynamic process of intellectual and spiritual development, rooted in the continuous pursuit of understanding and self-improvement.",
  "4327": "يَتَغَامَزُونَ and related words stem from the root غ-م-ز, with the root verb غَمَزَ meaning \"he winked,\" \"signaled with his eyes,\" or \"gestured secretly.\" يَتَغَامَزُونَ means \"they wink at each other\" or \"exchange secret signals.\" This form reflects reciprocal action between parties. The connection lies in the mutual and covert communication implied by the root, emphasizing subtle, often deceptive interactions. It highlights behaviors characterized by secrecy or mockery, emphasizing themes of insincerity or hidden intentions.",
  "4328": "يَتَغَيَّرْ and related words stem from the root غ-ي-ر, with the root verb غَارَ meaning \"he brought provision,\" \"he benefited,\" \"he bestowed something good,\" \"he was jealous,\" or \"he was protective.\" The derived root verb غَيَّرَ adds the dimension of \"altering\" or \"changing something.\" يَتَغَيَّرْ specifically means \"he changes\" or \"he becomes altered,\" highlighting the internal process of transformation or modification within oneself. This form emphasizes a change that occurs inherently, reflecting themes of personal or internal shifts connected to the root's broader meanings of provision, protection, and change.",
  "4329": "يَتَفَجَّرُ and related words stem from the root ف-ج-ر, with the root verb فَجَرَ meaning \"it burst forth\" or \"it gushed out.\" يَتَفَجَّرُ means \"it bursts forth\" or \"it gushes out repeatedly.\" The connection lies in the reflexive or intensive nature of the action, highlighting continuous or abundant emergence. This term reflects the root's concept of splitting open, emphasizing a dynamic, ongoing process such as water continuously flowing from a spring or emotions surfacing repeatedly.",
  "4330": "يَتَفَضَّلَ and related words stem from the root ف-ض-ل, with the root verb فَضَلَ meaning \"he exceeded,\" \"he was superior,\" or \"he remained.\" يَتَفَضَّلَ means \"he seeks to take precedence,\" \"he claims superiority,\" or \"he shows favor.\" The root conveys themes of abundance, excellence, and surplus, often emphasizing a state of being above or beyond others. يَتَفَضَّلَ reflects the act of seeking distinction or asserting superiority, whether positively through generosity or, as in some contexts, negatively through self-exaltation. This term ties to the root’s essence of surpassing others, highlighting the interplay between favor and dominance in its application.",
  "4331": "يَتَفَقَّهُ and related words stem from the root ف-ق-ه, with the root verb فَقِهَ meaning \"he understood\" or \"he comprehended,\" implying precise and insightful understanding. يَتَفَقَّهُ means \"he seeks to understand deeply\" or \"he endeavors to gain profound knowledge,\" reflecting deliberate pursuit of comprehension. The root conveys themes of intellect, awareness, and grasping nuances, particularly in intricate knowledge. يَتَفَقَّهُ highlights striving for deeper understanding, moving beyond superficial knowledge to attain meaningful insight and clarity.",
  "4332": "يَتَفَكَّرُونَ and related words stem from the root ف-ك-ر, with the root verb فَكَرَ meaning \"he thought\" or \"he reflected.\" يَتَفَكَّرُونَ means \"they engage in deep contemplation\" or \"they reflect thoroughly.\" The connection emphasizes an ongoing, self-motivated process of deep thinking and reflection. This term encourages continuous contemplation to gain insight and understanding, often in the context of pondering the signs of Allah (ﷻ) and the wonders of creation.",
  "4333": "يَتَفَيَّأُ and related words stem from the root ف-ي-أ, with the root verb فَاءَ meaning \"he returned.\" تَفَيَّأَ means \"it inclined\" or \"it shifted,\" while يَتَفَيَّأُ means \"they incline\" or \"they shift.\" The root conveys a sense of returning, bending, or changing position, which aligns with the movement or inclination described by these derived forms. This highlights a continuous or recurring action of shifting or inclining, often symbolizing the natural or cyclical return to a balanced state.",
  "4334": "يَتَكَبَّرُونَ and related words stem from the root ك-ب-ر, with the root verb كَبُرَ meaning \"he became great.\" يَتَكَبَّرُونَ means \"they are arrogant\" or \"they exalt themselves.\" It signifies an ongoing action of prideful behavior, highlighting the root’s emphasis on magnitude but with a negative moral dimension. This form warns against the continuous elevation of oneself above others, highlighting the importance of humility and submission to Allah’s (ﷻ) true greatness.",
  "4335": "يَتَكَلَّمُونَ and related words stem from the root ك-ل-م, with the root verbs كَلَمَ, meaning \"he wounded,\" and كَـلَّمَ, meaning \"he spoke.\" يَتَكَلَّمُونَ means \"they speak\" or \"they are speaking,\" emphasizing active and ongoing communication. The connection reflects the root's dual themes of impactful expression and lasting influence, as spoken words can metaphorically \"wound\" or heal, revealing intentions and eliciting responses. This term highlights the dynamic power of language, where continuous speech engages, affects, and shapes the social and emotional fabric of interactions.",
  "4336": "يَتَلَاوَمُونَ and related words stem from the root ل-و-م, with the root verb لَامَ meaning \"he blamed,\" \"he reproached,\" or \"he censured.\" يَتَلَاوَمُونَ means \"they blame each other,\" \"they mutually reproach,\" or \"they exchange blame.\" The root conveys notions of disapproval, fault-finding, and criticism, often aimed at correcting or exposing wrongdoing. It highlights the reciprocal nature of blame, where individuals hold one another accountable. Beyond simple reproach, it reflects deeper dynamics of moral evaluation, regret, and assigning responsibility, emphasizing the tensions and struggles inherent in human relationships.",
  "4337": "يَتَلَطَّفْ and related words stem from the root ل-ط-ف, with the root verb لَطُفَ meaning \"he was subtle,\" \"delicate,\" or \"gracious.\" يَتَلَطَّفْ means \"he should be gentle,\" \"he should act with subtlety,\" or \"he should behave courteously.\" The connection lies in embodying gentleness and subtlety in behavior, reflecting the root's emphasis on delicate kindness and cautiousness. This term highlights the importance of acting with care and consideration, being mindful of others' feelings, and proceeding with wisdom and tact in delicate situations.",
  "4338": "يَتَمَاسَّا and related words stem from the root م-س-س, with the root verb مَسَّ meaning \"he touched.\" يَتَمَاسَّا means \"they touch each other\" or \"they come into contact.\" The root emphasizes the concept of contact, whether physical or metaphorical, and often conveys lightness or delicacy, highlighting how even brief interactions can create meaningful effects. The reciprocal nature of يَتَمَاسَّا reflects mutual engagement, illustrating not just the physical act of touching but the nuanced dynamics of interaction, where contact, no matter how slight, can leave a lasting impact or signify mutual influence.",
  "4339": "يَتَمَطَّىٰ and related words stem from the root م-ط-ط, with the root verb مَطَّ meaning \"he stretched,\" \"he extended,\" or \"he lengthened.\" يَتَمَطَّىٰ means \"he stretches himself\" or \"he swaggers arrogantly,\" highlighting the act of extending or posturing oneself in pride. The root conveys the concept of elongation or extension, which can apply to physical stretching, the prolonging of time or effort, or metaphorical exaggeration. The term يَتَمَطَّىٰ combines these dimensions, reflecting both the physical act of stretching and the metaphorical behavior of arrogance or ostentation, emphasizing the connection between physical extension and the human tendency to overreach or display excessive pride.",
  "4340": "يَتَمَنَّىٰ stems from the root م-ن-ي, with the root verb مَنَى meaning \"he wished\" or \"he desired.\" يَتَمَنَّىٰ means \"he wishes\" or \"he desires,\" reflecting the act of longing or aspiring for something, whether attainable or beyond reach. The root also encompasses meanings like \"to measure\" or \"to determine,\" connecting the idea of wishes to measured aspirations or predetermined goals. In classical usage, it can also imply \"to recite\" or \"to fabricate,\" linking wishes to verbal expression or even falsehood. This term captures the complexity of human desires and their expressions, rooted in both aspiration and articulation.",
  "4341": "يَتَنَافَسُ and related words stem from the root ن-ف-س, with the root verb نَفِسَ meaning \"it was precious\" or \"valuable.\" يَتَنَافَسُ means \"they compete\" or \"they vied with one another.\" The connection lies in striving earnestly for something precious, mirroring the eagerness to attain valuable objectives, directly relating to the root's emphasis on value and competition.",
  "4342": "يَتَنَاهَوْنَ and related words stem from the root ن-ه-ى, with the root verb نَهَى meaning \"he forbade\" or \"he prohibited.\" يَتَنَاهَوْنَ means \"they mutually forbid one another\" or \"they admonish each other.\" The term comes from a reciprocal form, emphasizing mutual action and shared responsibility in discouraging wrongdoing. The root conveys themes of prohibition, restraint, and moral guidance, reflecting the importance of collective accountability in upholding righteousness.",
  "4343": "يَتِرُ and related words stem from the root و-ت-ر, with the root verb وَتَرَ meaning \"he deprived,\" \"he diminished,\" or \"he caused loss.\" يَتِرُ means \"he deprives\" or \"he causes loss.\" The connection lies in the act of taking away or causing someone to be bereft of something, directly relating to the root's meaning. This term emphasizes the experience of loss or deprivation, highlighting the impact of being stripped of possessions or blessings.",
  "4344": "يَتِيمٌ and related words stem from the root ي-ت-م, with the root verb يَتِمَ meaning \"he became an orphan\" or \"he was bereaved.\" يَتِيمٌ means \"orphan,\" specifically a child who has lost a father. The root conveys broader concepts of loss, incompleteness, and vulnerability. The connection reflects the root’s emphasis on bereavement and the absence of support, highlighting the moral responsibility to care for those in such a vulnerable state.",
  "4345": "يَتِيهُونَ and related words stem from the root ت-ي-ه, with the root verb تَاهَ meaning \"he deviated,\" \"he lost the way,\" \"he wandered,\" or \"he behaved arrogantly.\" يَتِيهُونَ describes an ongoing state of aimless wandering, often marked by arrogance that hinders finding the right path. The root encompasses both physical and moral disorientation, where pride or heedlessness compounds one’s misguidance. يَتِيهُونَ reflects a condition of being directionless, estranged from clarity and purpose due to one’s own arrogance, choices or attitudes.",
  "4346": "يَتَّكِئُونَ and related words stem from the root و-ك-أ, with the root verb وَكَأَ meaning \"he leaned.\" يَتَّكِئُونَ means \"they recline\" or \"they lean upon.\" The broader root meanings include the act of seeking stability, resting for support, and relying on something firm or dependable. This connects directly to the root's emphasis on leaning or depending for physical or symbolic stability, reflecting a state of reliance and comfort.",
  "4347": "يَثْرِبُ was the name of the city that became known as Al-Madinah Al-Munawwarah (the Enlightened City), or Medina, during the time of the Prophet Muhammad (ﷺ). The name يَثْرِبُ stems from the root ث-ر-ب, with the root verb ثَرَبَ meaning \"he blamed or reproached for an offense\" or \"acted corruptly, creating disorder.\" This reflects the city’s former state of strife and corruption before the Prophet Muhammad’s (ﷺ) migration. The transition from يَثْرِبُ to Medina symbolizes the city’s transformation from a place of disorder and blame to one of unity, justice, and harmony, as the Prophet’s (ﷺ) presence brought faith and brotherhood to the community.",
  "4348": "يَثْنُونَ and related words stem from the root ث-ن-ي, with the root verb ثَنَىٰ meaning \"he folded,\" \"he doubled,\" or \"he bent.\" يَثْنُونَ means \"they fold\" or \"they bend,\" reflecting the act of physically or metaphorically bending or turning. The root conveys concepts of curving, folding, or redirecting, often symbolizing a change in posture, attitude, or direction. This term highlights deliberate movement or adjustment, whether literal or figurative, such as turning away or altering focus.",
  "4349": "يَجُرُّ and related words stem from the root ج-ر-ر, with the root verb جَرَّ meaning \"he dragged\" or \"he pulled.\" يَجُرُّ means \"he drags\" or \"he pulls,\" directly depicting the act of moving something along by force or effort. The root conveys physical exertion and movement, emphasizing the connection between force and displacement. This word often illustrates the struggle or effort required to drag or pull objects.",
  "4350": "يَجْأَرُونَ and related words stem from the root ج-أ-ر, with the root verb جَأَرَ meaning \"he cried out\" or \"he supplicated loudly.\" يَجْأَرُونَ means \"they cry out\" or \"they implore earnestly,\" emphasizing the act of raising one’s voice in intense distress or urgent supplication. The root conveys themes of desperation, vulnerability, and seeking relief in moments of severe need or hardship. This term reflects the human instinct to call out loudly for help or mercy, especially in dire circumstances, symbolizing both physical and emotional expressions of need.",
  "4351": "يَجْمَحُونَ and related words stem from the root ج-م-ح, with the root verb جَمَحَ meaning \"he went at random or heedlessly, without consideration or aim, refusing to follow a guide to the right course.\" يَجْمَحُونَ means \"they go heedlessly\" or \"they act uncontrollably,\" highlighting actions driven by a lack of guidance or deliberate purpose. The connection emphasizes reckless behavior marked by unrestrained, aimless motion or action, reflecting the root’s central theme of heedlessness and disobedience.",
  "4352": "يَجْهَلُونَ and related words stem from the root ج-ه-ل, with the root verb جَهِلَ meaning \"he was ignorant.\" The root encompasses meanings of ignorance, acting foolishly, and lacking understanding or awareness. يَجْهَلُونَ means \"they are ignorant\" or \"they do not know,\" referring to an ongoing state of lacking knowledge or understanding. This term emphasizes the continuous journey of seeking knowledge and the dangers of complacency in ignorance, urging individuals to strive for enlightenment and awareness.",
  "4353": "يَحُضُّ and related words stem from the root ح-ض-ض, with the root verb حَضَّ meaning \"he urged,\" \"he incited,\" or \"he encouraged.\" يَحُضُّ means \"he urges\" or \"he incites,\" reflecting the ongoing act of motivating or influencing someone toward an action. While the root is neutral, its context determines whether it emphasizes positive encouragement, such as urging good deeds or generosity, or negative incitement, like neglecting responsibilities or harmful behavior. This dual nature highlights the significant impact of urging others, highlighting the moral responsibility to channel this influence toward fostering constructive and ethical outcomes.",
  "4354": "يَحُورَ and related words stem from the root ح-و-ر, with the root verb حَارَ meaning \"he returned or reverted.\" يَحُورَ means \"he returns\" or \"he will return.\" The root conveys themes of returning, reverting, and clarity, often emphasizing a transition back to an original state or place. This word reflects the certainty of return, whether in a physical, spiritual, or existential sense, highlighting the cyclical nature of existence and the inevitability of returning to one’s origin.",
  "4355": "يَحِضْنَ and related words stem from the root ح-ي-ض, with the root verb حَاضَ meaning \"she menstruated.\" يَحِضْنَ means \"they menstruated.\" This word also carries the meaning of \"it declined or turned away,\" indicating a shift or turning aside. The connection lies in the natural process of change during this time, where the woman moves through a temporary phase of separation from her usual state. This reflects an inherent cycle of transition and renewal, aligning with the root’s themes of movement, change, and a temporary turning aside before returning to her natural rhythm.",
  "4356": "يَحِيفَ and related words stem from the root ح-ي-ف, with the root verb حَافَ meaning \"he acted unjustly,\" he deviated from fairness,\" or \"he oppressed or acted tyrannically.\" يَحِيفَ means \"he acts unjustly\" or \"he deviates from justice.\" The root conveys themes of deviation, imbalance, and unfairness, emphasizing actions that disrupt equity and violate rights. The connection lies in the act of veering away from justice, whether through partiality, misuse of power, or deliberate harm.",
  "4357": "يَحْبِسُ and related words stem from the root ح-ب-س, with the root verb حَبَسَ meaning \"he restrained.\" يَحْبِسُ means \"he restrains,\" referring to the act of holding something or someone back, confining, or limiting movement or action. The root conveys meanings of restraining, confining, detaining, and holding back. The connection lies in the root’s focus on control, boundaries, and the deliberate act of setting limits for a specific purpose, whether for discipline, justice, or protection.",
  "4358": "يَحْتَسِبُ and related words stem from the root ح-س-ب, with the root verb حَسِبَ meaning \"he reckoned\" or \"he calculated.\" اِحْتَسَبَ means \"he sought reward.\" يَحْتَسِبُ means \"he seeks reward [from Allah (ﷻ)]\" or \"he expects recompense.\" The connection lies in reckoning, calculation, and expectation, as a person considers deeds in relation to their ultimate reward. This root conveys themes of accountability, trust, and seeking divine recompense, emphasizing mindfulness and confidence in Allah’s (ﷻ) justice.",
  "4359": "يَحْذَرُ and related words stem from the root ح-ذ-ر, with the root verb حَذِرَ meaning \"he was cautious\" or \"he was vigilant.\" يَحْذَرُ means \"he is cautious\" or \"he is wary.\" The connection lies in actively exercising caution, embodying the root's emphasis on ongoing vigilance. It highlights the continual state of alertness required to navigate potential dangers and avoid pitfalls.",
  "4360": "يَحْزُنُ and related words stem from the root ح-ز-ن, with the root verb حَزِنَ meaning \"he was sad\" or \"he grieved.\" يَحْزُنُ means \"he grieves,\" \"he becomes sad,\" or \"it grieves,\" depending on the subject. The root broadly conveys themes of emotional weight, ongoing hardship, and inner struggle. The connection emphasizes the continuous experience of sadness or the impact of grief caused by an event or situation, directly relating to the root's focus on emotional heaviness. This term highlights how sorrow can linger and affect both individuals and their responses to external circumstances.",
  "4361": "يَحْطِمَ and related words stem from the root ح-ط-م, with the root verb حَطَمَ meaning \"he broke,\" \"he shattered,\" or \"he crushed.\" يَحْطِمَ means \"he or it breaks,\" \"he or it shatters,\" or \"he or it crushes,\" reflecting the ongoing or potential action of causing destruction. The root also conveys themes of fragmentation, decay, and ruin, often associated with breaking something into smaller, unusable pieces. This term highlights the forceful and irreversible nature of breaking or crushing, directly connecting to the root's essence of destruction and disintegration.",
  "4362": "يَحْمُومٌ and related words stem from the root ح-م-م, with the root verb حَمَّ meaning \"it became hot\" or \"he heated.\" يَحْمُومٌ means \"intensely black smoke\" or \"soot,\" emphasizing the residual effects of extreme heat. The root reflects themes of heat, intensity, and protection, often signifying barriers that shield or separate. The connection to يَحْمُومٌ lies in its role as a byproduct of burning, where black smoke not only signifies destruction and suffocation but also acts as a barrier, obscuring visibility and shielding what is beyond it. This duality captures both the consuming nature of fire and its isolating, protective effects.",
  "4363": "يَحْيَىٰ stems from the root ح-ي-ي, with the root verb حَيَّ meaning \"he lived\" or \"he became fresh or lively. يَحْيَىٰ is the name of Prophet John (ﷺ) and means \"he lives.\" The connection lies in his miraculous birth to parents of old age, with his mother previously barren, emphasizing Allah’s (ﷻ) power to grant life against all odds. His name reflects the divine act of bestowing life and the profound spiritual vitality he embodied, serving as a reminder of Allah’s (ﷻ) will and ability to create life in the most extraordinary circumstances.",
  "4364": "يَخْتَانُونَ and related words stem from the root خ-و-ن, with the root verb خَانَ meaning \"he betrayed.\" اخْتَانَ means \"he acted treacherously,\" while يَخْتَانُونَ means \"they betray\" or \"they act treacherously,\" indicating ongoing secretive wrongdoing or deliberate deceit. The root revolves around betrayal, dishonesty, unfaithfulness, and breach of trust, conveying a failure to uphold responsibility or violating expectations of loyalty. The connection highlights a deeper, more intentional form of betrayal, where treachery is not just an act but a persistent behavior, further intensifying the severity of deceit and its consequences.",
  "4365": "يَخْتَصُّ and related words stem from the root خ-ص-ص, with the root verb خَصَّ meaning \"it was special, distinct, or distinguished from others,\" and خَصَّصَ meaning \"he distinguished, or singled out.\" اِخْتَصَّ means \"he selected for himself\" or \"he chose exclusively,\" while يَخْتَصُّ means \"he specifies\" or \"he chooses exclusively.\" The connection emphasizes the act of singling out or granting exclusive favor or distinction. It reflects how Allah (ﷻ) selects certain individuals or bestows particular blessings according to His wisdom, highlighting His absolute authority in determining what is set apart or uniquely favored.",
  "4366": "يَخْدَعُونَ and related words stem from the root خ-د-ع, with the root verb خَدَعَ meaning \"he deceived.\" يَخْدَعُونَ means \"they deceive\" or \"they are deceiving.\" The root carries dimensions of ongoing deceit and pretense, emphasizing deliberate acts of misleading others. The connection lies in the continuous and active nature of deceitful behavior, highlighting the persistence and intent behind their actions, which aligns with the root’s focus on deliberate cunning and manipulation.",
  "4367": "يَخْذُلُ and related words stem from the root خ-ذ-ل, with the root verb خَذَلَ meaning \"he abandoned or deserted,\" or \"he failed or disappointed.\" يَخْذُلُ means \"he forsakes\" or \"he abandons.\" The connection lies in the act of withdrawing support at a critical moment, leaving someone without aid. This word reflects the root’s theme of desertion, emphasizing the failure to assist when help is expected, which can lead to weakness, loss, or betrayal.",
  "4368": "يَخْرُصُونَ and related words stem from the root خ-ر-ص, with the root verb خَرَصَ meaning \"he spoke by opinion or conjecture.\" يَخْرُصُونَ means \"they speculate\" or \"they lie.\" The root conveys the concepts of conjecture, estimation, and speaking without definite knowledge. It pertains to actions involving making assumptions or guesses, without firm evidence or certainty. The connection lies in the ongoing action of making uncertain statements, reflecting the root's emphasis on speculation and dishonesty. It highlights the unreliability of unfounded assertions.",
  "4369": "يَخْصِفَانِ and related words stem from the root خ-ص-ف, with the root verb خَصَفَ meaning \"he covered one piece with another\" or \"he sewed or patched together.\" يَخْصِفَانِ means \"they patch\" or \"they joined together.\" The connection lies in the act of covering by attaching pieces, reflecting the instinct to mend or conceal what is exposed. In the Qur'an, it describes how Adam and Eve (عَلَيْهِمَا ٱلصَّلَاةُ وَٱلسَّلَامُ) fastened leaves together to cover themselves, symbolizing the innate human response to seek covering and dignity.",
  "4370": "يَخْفَىٰ and related words stem from the root خ-ف-ي, with the root verb خَفِيَ meaning \"he or it was hidden or concealed\" or \"he or it became unapparent.\" يَخْفَىٰ means \"it is hidden\" or \"it becomes hidden,\" emphasizing the state of being obscured or concealed. The root reflects broader dimensions of invisibility, subtlety, and imperceptibility, encompassing both physical and metaphorical concealment. It relates to the unseen, the unknown, or what lies beyond immediate perception, whether truths, realities, or intentions. This connection highlights the idea that certain aspects of existence remain hidden, often unfolding or being revealed with time, emphasizing Allah's (ﷻ) wisdom.",
  "4371": "يَخْلُدْ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-د, with the root verb خَلَدَ meaning \"he remained\" or \"he lasted long.\" يَخْلُدْ means \"he remains\" or \"he abides eternally.\" The root conveys permanence, timelessness, and continuous existence. The connection emphasizes the ongoing nature of abiding indefinitely, reflecting the unending reality of the afterlife, where one’s final state is everlasting.",
  "4372": "يَدٌ and related words stem from the root ي-د-ي, primarily referring to the \"hand\" as a physical instrument of action, execution, and interaction. The root conveys broader concepts such as power, capability, agency, control, and assistance. يَدٌ extends beyond its physical sense to symbolize authority, influence, or support in abstract contexts. These meanings align with the hand's role in performing actions, representing human ability to act, exert power, and bring about change both physically and metaphorically.",
  "4373": "يَدُسُّ and related words stem from the root د-س-س, with the root verb دَسَّ meaning \"he concealed, hid, or buried\" or \"he inserted, placed, or put (something) secretly or stealthily.\" يَدُسُّ means \"he hides,\" \"he conceals,\" or \"he buries,\" reflecting the ongoing act of suppression or covering something from view. The root conveys secrecy, suppression, and hidden placement. Just as something concealed is deliberately kept out of sight, this word emphasizes an intentional effort to obscure, suppress, or discreetly place something where it will not be noticed or easily discovered.",
  "4374": "يَدُعُّ and related words stem from the root د-ع-ع, with the root verb دَعَّ meaning \"he pushed back forcefully\" or \"he repelled.\" يَدُعُّ means \"he repels\" or \"he pushes away,\" highlighting an ongoing action of rejection or forceful expulsion. The root revolves around forceful actions, both physical (pushing, striking) and verbal (rebuking, scolding). Just as pushing something away removes it with force, this word conveys an act of harsh dismissal or rejection, emphasizing a strong and deliberate refusal to accept or allow something.",
  "4375": "يَدِينُونَ and related words stem from the root دَيَن, with the root verb دَانَ meaning \"he obeyed\" or \"he borrowed.\" يَدِينُونَ means \"they judge,\" \"they repay,\" or \"they obey,\" reflecting the themes of accountability and obligation. The root revolves around obedience, judgment, and indebtedness, encompassing faith, legal rulings, and financial obligations. The connection to obedience lies in the idea of being bound by duty, whether through religious devotion, legal responsibility, or moral obligation. Just as a debtor must repay what is owed, this word reflects submission to a higher authority, emphasizing the structured nature of justice, recompense, and adherence to obligations.",
  "4376": "يَدَّعُونَ and related words stem from the root د-ع-و, with the root verb دَعَا meaning \"he called or invited\" or \"he supplicated or prayed.\" يَدَّعُونَ means \"they call for,\" \"they request,\" or \"they summon,\" emphasizing an act of seeking, demanding, or invoking. The root revolves around calling, summoning, requesting, naming, and invoking, conveying the ideas of communication and appeal. Just as a call seeks recognition or response, this word reflects an active pursuit, whether in making demands, requesting fulfillment, or calling for something with insistence.",
  "4377": "يَدْرَؤُونَ and related words stem from the root د-ر-أ, with the root verb دَرَأَ meaning \"he pushed away or repelled\" or \"he averted or warded off.\" يَدْرَؤُونَ means \"they avert\" or \"they repel,\" emphasizing the act of pushing away harm or preventing something undesirable. The root revolves around repelling, preventing, resisting, and contention, conveying both warding off harm and the emergence or creation of something. Just as repelling involves active resistance, this word reflects a deliberate effort to prevent or deflect danger, conflict, or adversity, highlighting the power of opposition and protection.",
  "4378": "يَدْمَغُ and related words stem from the root د-م-غ, with the root verb دَمَغَ meaning \"he struck on the head\" or \"he inflicted a fatal blow.\" يَدْمَغُ means \"he crushes\" or \"he smites,\" reflecting the act of delivering a decisive and forceful blow. The root revolves around striking decisively, destroying, refuting, or marking something permanently. It conveys forcefulness, whether in physical impact (a blow to the head) or intellectual impact (refuting an argument completely). Striking the head symbolizes the complete and conclusive defeat of deceit, illustrating the inevitable triumph of truth over falsehood.",
  "4379": "يَذَرَ and related words stem from the root و-ذ-ر, with the root verb وَذَرَ meaning \"he left,\" \"he abandoned,\" or \"he forsook.\" يَذَرَ means \"he leaves\" or \"he forsakes.\" The connection lies in the act of abandoning or neglecting something, directly reflecting the root's concept of leaving behind.",
  "4380": "يَرْتَعْ and related words stem from the root ر-ت-ع, with the root verb رَتَعَ meaning \"he grazed freely\" or \"he indulged.\" يَرْتَعْ means \"he may enjoy freely\" or \"let him graze.\" The connection lies in the act of enjoying abundance without restraint, reflecting the root's emphasis on unrestricted enjoyment. This term conveys a sense of ease and plentiful provision, often associated with pastoral scenes or metaphorically with carefree indulgence.",
  "4381": "يَرْتَقُوا and related words stem from the root ر-ق-ي, with the root verb رَقِيَ meaning \"he ascended,\" \"he climbed,\" or \"he elevated.\" يَرْتَقُوا means \"they ascend\" or \"they climb,\" reflecting the act of moving upward. The root also conveys themes of progression, elevation, and advancement. This connection highlights the broader concept of striving for higher states, whether physically, spiritually, or emotionally.",
  "4382": "يَرْجُوا and related words stem from the root ر-ج-و, with the root verb رَجَا meaning \"he hoped\" or \"he expected.\" يَرْجُوا means \"he hopes\" or \"he expects.\" The connection is direct, expressing the act of hoping, reflecting the root's emphasis on desire and anticipation. This term embodies the human emotion of hope, highlighting reliance on future possibilities and faith.",
  "4383": "يَرْشُدُ and related words stem from the root ر-ش-د, with the root verb رَشَدَ meaning \"he was rightly guided\" or \"he was sensible.\" يَرْشُدُ means \"he is rightly guided\" or \"he acts sensibly.\" The connection reflects the ongoing state of being on the correct path, embodying the root's essence of guidance. It highlights the continuous process of seeking and maintaining right guidance in life.",
  "4384": "يَرْغَبُ and related words stem from the root ر-غ-ب, with the root verb رَغِبَ meaning \"he desired\" or \"he wished for.\" يَرْغَبُ means \"he desires\" or \"he wishes for.\" The connection lies in the ongoing action of desiring or inclining towards something, embodying the root's emphasis on continuous yearning. This term reflects the persistent nature of human desires and aspirations, influencing behavior and decisions.",
  "4385": "يَرْقُبُ and related words stem from the root ر-ق-ب, with the root verb رَقَبَ meaning \"he watched\" or \"he observed.\" يَرْقُبُ means \"he observes\" or \"he watches.\" The connection is direct, embodying the ongoing act of watching or guarding, reflecting the root's fundamental meaning. This term emphasizes the importance of vigilance and awareness in various contexts, from personal conduct to divine oversight.",
  "4386": "يَرْكَعُ and related words stem from the root ر-ك-ع, with the root verb رَكَعَ meaning \"he bowed (in prayer).\" يَرْكَعُ means \"he bows\" or \"he is bowing,\" emphasizing the act of bowing during worship. The connection lies in performing the act of bowing, directly relating to the root's meaning. This term highlights the importance of humility and submission in religious practices.",
  "4387": "يَرْكُضُ and related words stem from the root ر-ك-ض, with the root verb رَكَضَ meaning \"he ran\" or \"he galloped.\" يَرْكُضُ means \"he runs\" or \"he is running,\" emphasizing swift movement. The connection lies in the action of rapid motion, directly relating to the root's meaning. In the Qur'an, it can depict fleeing or rushing, symbolizing urgency or the need to escape from danger.",
  "4388": "يَرْكُمُ and related words stem from the root ر-ك-م, with the root verb رَكَمَ meaning \"he heaped up\" or \"he piled.\" يَرْكُمُ means \"he heaps up\" or \"he accumulates.\" The connection lies in the action of gathering into a heap, directly relating to the root's meaning. It can symbolize the process of accumulation, whether of physical objects, deeds, or abstract concepts like knowledge.",
  "4389": "يَرْهَبُونَ and related words stem from the root ر-ه-ب, with the root verb رَهِبَ meaning \"he feared\" or \"he was in awe.\" يَرْهَبُونَ means \"they fear\" or \"they are in awe.\" The connection lies in the ongoing emotional state of fear or reverence, directly relating to the root's meaning. This term highlights the continuous nature of fear or respect, especially in a spiritual context.",
  "4390": "يَرْهَقُ and related words stem from the root ر-ه-ق, with the root verb رَهِقَ meaning \"he overtook\" or \"he oppressed.\" يَرْهَقُ means \"he oppresses\" or \"he overwhelms.\" The connection lies in the ongoing action of causing hardship or excess, directly relating to the root's meaning. In the Qur'an, it can depict being covered or overwhelmed by darkness or disgrace.",
  "4391": "يَزِرُونَ and related words stem from the root و-ز-ر, with the root verb وَزَرَ meaning \"he carried a burden.\" يَزِرُونَ means \"they carry\" or \"they will carry (a burden).\" The connection lies in the ongoing or future act of bearing responsibility, directly reflecting the root's concept of carrying weight. This term emphasizes the continuous nature of personal accountability and the enduring impact of one's choices.",
  "4392": "يَزِفُّ and related words stem from the root ز-ف-ف, with the root verb زَفَّ meaning \"he hastened\" or \"he moved swiftly.\" يَزِفُّ means \"he hastens\" or \"he rushes.\" The connection lies in the act of moving quickly or with urgency, reflecting the root's emphasis on speed and swift movement. It captures moments of rapid action, highlighting the urgency or eagerness in reaching a destination or accomplishing a task.",
  "4393": "يَزْنُونَ stems from the root ز-ن-ي, with the root verb زَنَى meaning \"he committed adultery\" or \"he fornicated.\" يَزْنُونَ means \"they commit adultery\" or \"they fornicate,\" indicating the ongoing or habitual nature of such actions. The root dimensions include notions of continuous deviation and the perpetuation of sin, highlighting the need for awareness, repentance, and a return to righteousness. This word serves as a caution against normalizing immoral behavior and the importance of seeking forgiveness.",
  "4394": "يَسُبُّ and related words stem from the root س-ب-ب, with the root verb سَبَّ meaning \"he insulted\" or \"he reviled.\" يَسُبُّ means \"he insults\" or \"he reviles.\" The connection lies in the act of speaking ill or cursing, embodying the root's negative connotation of causing harm through words. يَسُبُّ highlights the destructive power of speech and the importance of guarding one's tongue against harmful expressions.",
  "4395": "يَسُومُونَ and related words stem from the root س-و-م, with the root verb سَامَ meaning \"he inflicted,\" \"he imposed,\" or \"he pastured.\" يَسُومُونَ means \"they inflict,\" \"they impose,\" or \"they pasture.\" The connection lies in the concept of driving or leading, whether it's livestock to pasture or imposing hardship upon others, reflecting the root's emphasis on action and movement. In the Qur'an, this term is used to describe tyrants who inflict severe punishment or hardship on people, symbolizing oppression.",
  "4396": "يَسِيرٌ and related words stem from the root ي-س-ر, with the root verb يَسَرَ meaning \"it became easy.\" يَسِيرٌ means \"easy,\" \"small,\" or \"trivial,\" describing something simple, manageable, or insignificant in effort or weight. The root conveys broader concepts of ease, simplicity, lightness, and accessibility, focusing on minimizing difficulty and burden. The connection lies in the root’s emphasis on the absence of hardship, highlighting ease and simplicity in both physical and metaphorical aspects.",
  "4397": "يَسَّرَ and related words stem from the root ي-س-ر, with the root verb يَسَرَ meaning \"it became easy.\" يَسَّرَ means \"he made easy\" or \"he facilitated,\" reflecting the active effort to create ease or smoothness for others. The root encompasses broader concepts of ease, facilitation, accessibility, and the removal of difficulty, emphasizing actions that simplify or lighten burdens. The connection lies in embodying the root’s focus on removing obstacles and promoting simplicity.",
  "4398": "يَسَّمَّعُونَ and related words stem from the root س-م-ع, with the root verb سَمِعَ meaning \"he heard\" or \"he listened.\" يَسَّمَّعُونَ means \"they try to overhear\" or \"they eavesdrop.\" The doubled letters indicate an intensified or repetitive action. The connection suggests not just listening, but actively attempting to hear what is not meant to be heard, highlighting themes of secrecy, intrusion, or seeking hidden knowledge.",
  "4399": "يَسْأَمُ and related words stem from the root س-أ-م, with the root verb سَئِمَ meaning \"he became weary\" or \"he became bored.\" يَسْأَمُ means \"he becomes weary\" or \"he tires.\" The connection lies in the feeling of fatigue or dissatisfaction, embodying the root's concept of weariness. يَسْأَمُ highlights the importance of perseverance and the challenges of maintaining enthusiasm over time.",
  "4400": "يَسْبَحُ and related words stem from the root س-ب-ح, with the root verb سَبَحَ meaning \"he swam\" or \"he moved swiftly.\" يَسْبَحُ means \"he swims\" or \"he moves swiftly.\" The connection lies in the ongoing action of moving smoothly, embodying the root's concept of fluid motion. يَسْبَحُ reflects the natural order and rhythm present in creation, where everything moves according to divine decree.",
  "4401": "يَسْبِتُ and related words stem from the root س-ب-ت, with the root verb سَبَتَ meaning \"he rested\" or \"he ceased.\" يَسْبِتُ means \"he rests\" or \"he ceases.\" The connection lies in the act of stopping work or activity, embodying the root's concept of rest. يَسْبِتُ underscores the importance of balancing effort with rest for overall well-being.",
  "4402": "يَسْتَأْخِرُونَ and related words stem from the root أ-خ-ر, with the root verb أَخَّرَ meaning \"he delayed\" or \"he postponed,\" and اسْتَأْخَرَ meaning \"he sought to delay\" or \"he stayed behind.\" يَسْتَأْخِرُونَ means \"they seek to delay\" or \"they try to postpone,\" reflecting the attempt to defer or postpone something. This embodies the root's concept of delay or deferral. In the Qur'an, it is often used to highlight the inevitability of Allah's (ﷻ) decree, emphasizing that when the appointed time comes, no one can \"advance\" or \"delay\" it, highlighting the futility of trying to alter predetermined events.",
  "4403": "يَسْتَبْدِلْ and related words stem from the root ب-د-ل, with the root verb بَدَلَ meaning \"he exchanged\" or \"he replaced.\" The derived form اسْتَبْدَلَ means \"he sought a substitute\" or \"he replaced,\" adding the nuance of actively seeking a replacement. يَسْتَبْدِلْ translates as \"he seeks to replace\" or \"he replaces,\" emphasizing a deliberate intent to find an alternative. The root conveys both substitution and the motivation to alter, improve, or exchange, often reflecting a purposeful pursuit of change due to dissatisfaction or a desire for renewal.",
  "4404": "يَسْتَبْشِرُونَ and related words stem from the root ب-ش-ر, with the root verb بَشِرَ meaning \"he rejoiced\" or \"he was cheerful.\" يَسْتَبْشِرُونَ means \"they rejoice\" or \"they are delighted upon receiving good news,\" highlighting a collective experience of joy and hope. The root conveys themes of happiness, relief, and reassurance, and يَسْتَبْشِرُونَ reflects how such news uplifts communities, fostering unity and shared optimism. Unlike يُبَشِّرُونَ (they bring good news), يَسْتَبْشِرُونَ focuses on the recipients’ joyful response, celebrating the good news together with gratitude and hope.",
  "4405": "يَسْتَثْنُونَ and related words stem from the root ث-ن-ي, with the root verb ثَنَىٰ meaning \"he folded,\" \"he doubled,\" or \"he bent.\" يَسْتَثْنُونَ means \"they excluded\" or \"they made an exception,\" directly tied to the root’s sense of bending or diverting. This conveys the idea of setting something aside or apart, much like bending or folding a part of a whole. The term reflects deliberate differentiation or exclusion, emphasizing intention in separating or distinguishing one part from the rest.",
  "4406": "يَسْتَحْسِرُونَ and related words stem from the root ح-س-ر, with the root verb حَسَرَ meaning \"he was tired or fatigued.\" اِسْتَحْسَرَ means \"he became extremely exhausted or too weary to continue.\" يَسْتَحْسِرُونَ translates as \"they become so fatigued that they are unable to continue.\" The connection lies in progressive depletion, directly reflecting the root’s emphasis on weariness. This root theme encompasses both physical and emotional exhaustion, often resulting from continuous effort, prolonged hardship, or overwhelming strain that leads to a state of complete fatigue and cessation.",
  "4407": "يَسْتَحْيِي and related words stem from the root ح-ي-ي, with the root verb حَيِيَ meaning \"he was shy\" or \"he felt modesty,\" and حَيَّ meaning \"he lived\" or \"he became fresh or lively.\" يَسْتَحْيِي means \"he is shy,\" \"he refrains out of modesty,\" or \"he avoids due to a sense of shame or embarrassment.\" In older classical Arabic usage, it can also mean \"to spare a life\" or \"to let live,\" though in the context of captivity rather than as a positive act of mercy. The connection lies in how shyness and modesty lead one to restraint and avoidance, while the extended meaning reflects a different kind of restraint—holding someone back from death yet not granting them true freedom.",
  "4408": "يَسْتَخْفُونَ and related words stem from the root خ-ف-ي, with the root verb خَفِيَ meaning \"he or it was hidden or concealed\" or \"he or it became unapparent.\" اِسْتَخْفَى means \"he sought to hide himself,\" and يَسْتَخْفُونَ means \"they seek to hide\" or \"they hide themselves.\" The connection emphasizes the continuous action of attempting to conceal oneself or something, reflecting the inclination to avoid exposure.",
  "4409": "يَسْتَسْخِرُونَ and related words stem from the root س-خ-ر, with the root verb سَخِرَ meaning \"he mocked.\" يَسْتَسْخِرُونَ means \"they burst into laughter\" or \"they mock excessively.\" The term conveys an intensified act of ridicule, reflecting deliberate and excessive scorn. The root’s concept emphasizes negative behavior, highlighting the harm caused by persistent and exaggerated mockery.",
  "4410": "يَسْتَصْرِخُ and related words stem from the root ص-ر-خ, with the root verb صَرَخَ meaning \"he cried out.\" يَسْتَصْرِخُ means \"he calls out for help\" or \"he appeals desperately.\" The connection lies in seeking assistance through a loud or urgent plea, emphasizing the intensity of the need for help. This term conveys the idea of a desperate cry or call for aid, often in a moment of distress or emergency.",
  "4411": "يَسْتَعْتِبُوا and related words stem from the root ع-ت-ب, with the root verb عَتَبَ meaning \"he blamed\" or \"he reproached.\" اِسْتَعْتَبَ means \"he sought to please\" or \"he sought reconciliation.\" يَسْتَعْتِبُوا means \"they seek to please\" or \"they seek reconciliation.\" The connection involves actively seeking to remove blame, reflecting the root's concept of moving toward satisfaction through efforts to appease or make amends.",
  "4412": "يَسْتَعْفِفْ and related words stem from the root ع-ف-ف, with the root verb عَفَّ meaning \"he was chaste.\" يَسْتَعْفِفُ means \"he seeks to be chaste\" or \"he restrains himself.\" The connection lies in the active pursuit of self-restraint and purity, reflecting the root's emphasis on chastity. This term highlights the effort to maintain moral integrity by avoiding temptations and practicing self-discipline.",
  "4413": "يَسْتَفِزُّ and related words stem from the root ف-ز-ز, with the root verb فَزَّ meaning \"he moved quickly,\" \"he shook,\" or \"he disturbed.\" اِسْتَفَزَّ means \"he provoked,\" \"he incited,\" or \"he agitated.\" يَسْتَفِزُّ means \"he provokes\" or \"he incites.\" The connection lies in causing movement or disturbance, reflecting the root's concept of shaking. This term emphasizes the act of agitating others, highlighting the implications of provoking unrest.",
  "4414": "يَسْتَفْتُونَ and related words stem from the root ف-ت-ي, with the root verb فَتِيَ meaning \"he became a youth\" or \"he was youthful and strong,\" extending to \"he provided an answer\" or \"gave a legal decision.\" يَسْتَفْتُونَ means \"they seek a legal opinion\" or \"they ask for a fatwa.\" The connection lies in seeking wisdom and guidance, much like a youth seeks knowledge to grow. This term reflects the root's emphasis on acquiring understanding and clarity, highlighting the proactive pursuit of answers to navigate complex matters.",
  "4415": "يَسْتَقْدِمُونَ and related words also stem from the root ق-د-م, with the root verb قَدُمَ meaning \"he was ancient\" or \"he preceded.\" يَسْتَقْدِمُونَ means \"they seek to advance,\" \"they attempt to proceed,\" or \"they strive to move forward.\" This term focuses on the ongoing and active effort to progress or lead, reflecting the root’s emphasis on striving for precedence. It captures the continuous nature of pursuing advancement, whether in a physical, intellectual, or metaphorical sense. The root highlights perseverance and the pursuit of forward movement, symbolizing ambition and the drive to overcome stagnation and achieve progress.",
  "4416": "يَسْتَنْقِذُونَ and related words stem from the root ن-ق-ذ, with the root verb نَقَذَ meaning \"he saved\" or \"he delivered,\" and the derived verb اسْتَنْقَذَ meaning \"he sought to rescue\" or \"he tried to save.\" يَسْتَنْقِذُونَ means \"they seek to rescue,\" \"they try to save,\" or \"they attempt to recover,\" emphasizing an active and intentional effort to deliver someone or something from harm or loss. The connection lies in the purposeful action of striving to save or reclaim, directly reflecting the root’s core meaning of deliverance.",
  "4417": "يَسْتَنْكِحَ and related words stem from the root ن-ك-ح, with the root verb نَكَحَ meaning \"he married,\" and the derived verb اسْتَنْكَحَ meaning \"he sought to marry.\" يَسْتَنْكِحَ means \"he seeks to marry.\" The connection lies in the pursuit of entering into marriage, directly relating to the root's meaning. It highlights the intention and effort to establish a marital relationship.",
  "4418": "يَسْتَنْبِئُونَ and related words stem from the root ن-ب-أ, with the root verb نَبَأَ meaning \"he informed,\" \"he announced,\" or \"he brought news.\" يَسْتَنْبِئُونَ means \"they seek to be informed\" or \"they inquire.\" The root also conveys meanings of delivering significant or important information, often tied to communication or revelation. This connection emphasizes the act of seeking clarification or knowledge about matters of importance. The term highlights human curiosity and the pursuit of understanding, reflecting the broader themes of inquiry and the dissemination of news, particularly regarding essential or noteworthy matters.",
  "4419": "يَسْتَنْبِطُونَ and related words stem from the root ن-ب-ط, with the root verb نَبَطَ meaning \"it gushed forth\" or \"it sprang up.\" يَسْتَنْبِطُونَ means \"they deduce\" or \"they extract hidden meanings.\" The connection lies in the metaphor of drawing water from deep within the earth, representing the act of extracting deep knowledge or understanding from sources. This emphasizes the process of reasoning and interpretation, especially in legal or scholarly contexts, highlighting the value of insight and discernment.",
  "4420": "يَسْتَوْفُونَ and related words stem from the root و-ف-ى, with the root verb وَفَىٰ meaning \"he fulfilled\" or \"he completed.\" يَسْتَوْفُونَ means \"they seek to obtain in full\" or \"they exact fully,\" often emphasizing a deliberate effort to ensure nothing is left incomplete. The connection lies in the pursuit of completeness or fulfillment, reflecting the root's focus on totality and perfection. This term can carry both positive and negative connotations, as it may represent the fair and just attainment of one's due or the excessive and selfish demand for one's share.",
  "4421": "يَسْرِ and related words stem from the root س-ر-ى, with the root verb سَرَى meaning \"he traveled by night\" or \"he moved during the night.\" يَسْرِ means \"it passes,\" \"it journeys,\" or \"it departs,\" typically referring to the movement or transition of something, such as the night. The connection lies in the concept of gradual motion, reflecting the root’s focus on purposeful and often serene travel. In the Qur'an, يَسْرِ evokes imagery of the night receding or transitioning toward dawn, symbolizing the passage of time and the inevitability of change. This term highlights the divine orchestration of natural phenomena, serving as a reminder of Allah’s (ﷻ) wisdom and power.",
  "4422": "يَسْطُونَ and related words stem from the root س-ط-و, with the root verb سَطَا meaning \"he attacked,\" \"he assaulted,\" or \"he overpowered.\" يَسْطُونَ means \"they attack,\" \"they overpower,\" or \"they seize by force.\" The connection lies in the forceful exertion of power or dominance over others, reflecting the root's emphasis on sudden aggression and overwhelming strength. It highlights actions characterized by might and often associated with tyranny or oppression.",
  "4423": "يَسْطُرُونَ and related words stem from the root س-ط-ر, with the root verb سَطَرَ meaning \"he wrote,\" \"he lined,\" or \"he set in order.\" يَسْطُرُونَ means \"they write,\" \"they inscribe,\" or \"they arrange.\" The connection lies in the ongoing action of writing or arranging text, reflecting the root's emphasis on inscribing and organizing words. This term highlights the active process of documentation.",
  "4424": "يَسْفِكُ and related words stem from the root س-ف-ك, with the root verb سَفَكَ meaning \"he shed\" or \"he spilled,\" particularly referring to blood. يَسْفِكُ means \"he sheds\" or \"he spills (blood),\" describing the act of causing blood to flow. The root also conveys the idea of pouring, scattering, or causing liquid to spread, emphasizing the uncontrolled and forceful nature of spilling. While the term is often used in the context of bloodshed, it can extend to the broader imagery of loss, waste, or destruction caused by such acts. This highlights the gravity of shedding blood, highlighting the sanctity of life and the moral imperative to avoid violence, chaos, and actions that lead to harm or ruin.",
  "4425": "يَسْلُبُ and related words stem from the root س-ل-ب, with the root verb سَلَبَ meaning \"he took away,\" \"he robbed,\" or \"he stripped.\" يَسْلُبُ means \"he robs,\" \"he plunders,\" or \"he takes away.\" The connection lies in the act of stripping away or removing something from someone, directly reflecting the root's core meaning. It emphasizes the forceful deprivation of possessions or rights, highlighting themes of injustice or loss, and serves as a moral warning against such actions.",
  "4426": "يَشَّقَّقُ and related words stem from the root ش-ق-ق, with the root verb شَقَّ meaning \"he split\" or \"he cleft.\" يَشَّقَّقُ means \"it splits open,\" \"it cracks,\" or \"it fissures.\" The connection lies in the root's emphasis on splitting or breaking apart, and this intensified form reflects an action happening extensively or repeatedly. يَشَّقَّقُ vividly describes something undergoing fragmentation or cracking, such as the earth splitting due to drought or pressure, highlighting the dynamic process of division inherent in the root.",
  "4427": "يَشْعُرُ and related words stem from the root ش-ع-ر, with the root verb شَعَرَ meaning \"he perceived\" or \"he became aware.\" يَشْعُرُ means \"he perceives\" or \"he feels.\" The connection lies in the ongoing process of perception and awareness. It reflects the root's emphasis on consciousness and understanding in one's experiences and interactions.",
  "4428": "يَشْفَعُ and related words stem from the root ش-ف-ع, with the root verb شَفَعَ meaning \"he interceded\" or \"he paired.\" يَشْفَعُ means \"he intercedes.\" The connection lies in the ongoing action of advocating or pleading on behalf of another, embodying the root's concept of joining in support.",
  "4429": "يَشْفِ and related words stem from the root ش-ف-ي, with the root verb شَفَا meaning \"he healed\" or \"he cured.\" يَشْفِ means \"he heals.\" The connection lies in seeking or affirming healing, reflecting the root's concept of restoration. It often appears in supplications, expressing hope and reliance on Allah's (ﷻ) power to heal.",
  "4430": "يَشْوِي and related words stem from the root ش-و-ي, with the root verb شَوَىٰ meaning \"he roasted.\" يَشْوِي means \"he roasts\" or \"he grills.\" The connection lies in the ongoing action of exposing something to heat. In the Qur'an, it describes the severity of Hellfire, emphasizing the extreme punishment and the consuming nature of the fire. This reflects the root's concept of intense exposure leading to transformation or destruction.",
  "4431": "يَصُمْ and related words stem from the root ص-و-م, with the root verb صَامَ meaning \"he fasted\" or \"he abstained.\" يَصُمْ means \"he fasts\" or \"he will fast,\" indicating an ongoing or future action of fasting. The connection lies in the continual or intended practice of abstaining for spiritual purposes. This term highlights the act of fasting as a recurring element of worship, reflecting the root's emphasis on ongoing self-restraint and devotion.",
  "4432": "يَصِفُونَ and related words stem from the root و-ص-ف, with the root verb وَصَفَ meaning \"he described,\" \"he characterized,\" or \"he assigned qualities to.\" يَصِفُونَ means \"they describe\" or \"they attribute,\" emphasizing the continuous act of assigning attributes or qualities to something. The root encompasses themes of articulation, precision, and clarity, reflecting the deliberate effort to convey or assign characteristics accurately. However, when used to ascribe false attributes, it reflects a misuse of precision, driven by ignorance or the fulfillment of one’s own desires.",
  "4433": "يَصِلُونَ and related words stem from the root و-ص-ل, with the root verb وَصَلَ meaning \"he connected\" or \"he joined.\" يَصِلُونَ means \"they connect,\" \"they join,\" or \"they reach.\" The connection to the root involves the ongoing action of establishing or maintaining connections. In Islamic teachings, it often refers to upholding family ties or relationships, emphasizing the virtue of maintaining bonds of kinship and community.",
  "4434": "يَصَّدَّعُونَ and related words stem from the root ص-د-ع, with the root verb صَدَعَ meaning \"to split apart\" or \"to crack.\" The derived form تَصَدَّعَ means \"it split\" or \"it cracked,\" emphasizing fragmentation. يَصَّدَّعُونَ means \"they split apart\" or \"they are dividing,\" reflecting an ongoing or repeated process of separation. The connection lies in the root’s focus on continuous division or disintegration, symbolizing a state of fragmentation. This term represents not just a single instance but an ongoing process of breaking apart, whether physically, socially, or metaphorically, highlighting the gradual loss of unity or cohesion.",
  "4435": "يَصَّعَّدُ and related words stem from the root ص-ع-د, with the root verb صَعِدَ meaning \"he ascended.\" تَصَعَّدَ means \"he climbed with difficulty,\" and يَصَّعَّدُ means \"he climbs arduously\" or \"he struggles upward.\" The connection lies in the strenuous effort required to ascend, highlighting the challenges and hardships involved in reaching a higher position. This term emphasizes the physical or metaphorical difficulty of upward movement, symbolizing perseverance and effort in overcoming obstacles.",
  "4436": "يَصْدُرُ and related words stem from the root ص-د-ر, with the root verb صَدَرَ meaning \"he came forth,\" \"he proceeded,\" or \"he returned.\" يَصْدُرُ means \"he comes forth\" or \"he departs.\" The connection lies in the root's concept of moving away from a source or starting point. It can refer to people departing from a gathering or proceeding on a journey. ",
  "4437": "يَصْرِمُونَ and related words stem from the root ص-ر-م, with the root verb صَرَمَ meaning \"he cut off\" or \"he harvested.\" يَصْرِمُونَ means \"they harvest\" or \"they cut off.\" The connection lies in the act of severing crops from their source, symbolizing the process of reaping or detaching something from its origin. This term conveys the idea of taking what has grown or developed, typically in the context of gathering the results of effort or time.",
  "4438": "يَصْطَرِخُونَ and related words stem from the root ص-ر-خ, with the root verb صَرَخَ meaning \"he cried out.\" يَصْطَرِخُونَ means \"they cry out intensely\" or \"they wail.\" The connection lies in an intensified form of crying out, indicating extreme anguish or desperation. This term emphasizes a loud, continuous outcry, often arising from overwhelming distress or suffering. It reflects the intensity and urgency of the plea or wail.",
  "4439": "يَصْعَدُ and related words stem from the root ص-ع-د, with the root verb صَعِدَ meaning \"he ascended.\" يَصْعَدُ means \"he ascends\" or \"he rises.\" The connection lies in the action of moving upward, symbolizing progress, elevation, or the act of going to a higher position, whether physically or metaphorically. This term conveys the idea of upward movement, reflecting a rise in status, place, or state.",
  "4440": "يَصْفَحُوا and related words stem from the root ص-ف-ح, with the root verb صَفَحَ meaning \"he forgave\" or \"he overlooked.\" يَصْفَحُوا means \"they forgive\" or \"they overlook.\" The connection lies in the ongoing action of pardoning or letting go of resentment. In the Qur'an, it promotes continuous forgiveness as a virtue, mirroring Allah's (ﷻ) attribute of being Oft-Forgiving.",
  "4441": "يَصْلَىٰ and related words stem from the root ص-ل-ي, with the root verb صَلِيَ meaning \"he burned.\" يَصْلَىٰ means \"he will burn\" or \"he will be exposed to fire.\" The connection lies in the act of being subjected to intense heat, particularly in a metaphorical sense of punishment or suffering. This term emphasizes the severity of the experience, highlighting the physical or spiritual consequences of actions. ",
  "4442": "يَضُرَّ and related words stem from the root ض-ر-ر, with the root verb ضَرَّ meaning \"he harmed\" or \"he injured.\" يَضُرَّ means \"that he may harm\" or \"lest he harms,\" indicating a potential or feared action of causing harm. The connection lies in the root's focus on the act of harming, emphasizing caution against engaging in actions that could injure others. This term serves as a warning to prevent harm before it occurs.",
  "4443": "يَطِيرُ and related words stem from the root ط-ي-ر, with the root verb طَارَ meaning \"he or it flew.\" يَطِيرُ means \"it flies.\" The connection is direct, capturing the action of flying inherent in the root. This verb emphasizes continuous or habitual flight, symbolizing freedom, aspiration, and the ability to rise above earthly constraints.",
  "4444": "يَطَّوَّفَ and related words stem from the root ط-و-ف, with the root verb طَافَ meaning \"he went around\" or \"he circled.\" يَطَّوَّفَ means \"he goes around repeatedly\" or \"he performs circumambulation.\" This form emphasizes the action of circling as a deliberate and repeated act. The connection to the root highlights the ongoing nature of the movement. In Islamic rituals, it specifically refers to performing Tawaf around the Kaaba, symbolizing devotion and submission to Allah (ﷻ).",
  "4445": "يَطْلُبُ and related words stem from the root ط-ل-ب, with the root verb طَلَبَ meaning \"he sought\" or \"he requested.\" يَطْلُبُ means \"he seeks\" or \"he requests,\" highlighting the ongoing action of pursuit. The connection lies in actively striving for something, directly reflecting the root's concept of seeking. This term underscores continuous effort and aspiration in the quest to achieve or obtain.",
  "4446": "يَطْمَعُ and related words stem from the root ط-م-ع, with the root verb طَمِعَ meaning \"he desired eagerly.\" يَطْمَعُ means \"he desires\" or \"he hopes,\" indicating ongoing aspiration. The connection lies in actively longing or hoping for something, directly reflecting the root's concept of desire. This term can convey positive hope or negative greed, emphasizing human inclination towards aspiration and the need for balance.",
  "4447": "يَطْمِثْ and related words stem from the root ط-م-ث, with the root verb طَمَثَ meaning \"he had intimate relations.\" يَطْمِثْ means \"he touches intimately\" or \"he has relations.\" The connection lies in the act of physical intimacy, directly reflecting the root's concept of a transformative touch, symbolizing closeness and the exchange of physical intimacy.",
  "4448": "يَطْهُرُ and related words stem from the root ط-ه-ر, with the root verb طَهُرَ meaning \"he became pure\" or \"he was cleansed.\" يَطْهُرُ means \"he purifies\" or \"he becomes pure.\" The connection lies in the act of purifying or cleansing, reflecting the root's emphasis on purification and removal of impurity. It signifies both physical and spiritual cleanliness, highlighting the importance of purity in both a ritual and spiritual sense.",
  "4449": "يَعُوقُ and related words stem from the root ع-و-ق, with the root verb عَاقَ meaning \"he hindered,\" \"impeded,\" or \"obstructed.\" يَعُوقُ is the name of an idol worshipped by the people of Prophet Noah (ﷺ), representing a false deity that diverted people from the worship of Allah (ﷻ). Ya'uq was originally a righteous man, but he was later venerated as an idol through the whispers of Satan. The connection lies in the idol's role as an obstruction to true faith, embodying the root's concept of hindrance. يَعُوقُ symbolizes the barriers that prevent individuals from following the right path, highlighting the dangers of idolatry and the importance of steadfast monotheism.",
  "4450": "يَعْبَأُ and related words stem from the root ع-ب-أ, with the root verb عَبَأَ meaning \"he cared\" or \"he regarded.\" يَعْبَأُ means \"he cares\" or \"he gives importance.\" The connection is direct, reflecting the root's concept of paying attention or considering something significant. This term emphasizes the value or concern one has for a matter, highlighting themes of importance and regard.",
  "4451": "يَعْتَذِرُ and related words stem from the root ع-ذ-ر, with the root verb عَذَرَ meaning \"he excused\" or \"he pardoned.\" يَعْتَذِرُ means \"he apologizes\" or \"he seeks to excuse himself.\" It indicates the action of seeking forgiveness or presenting an excuse for oneself, directly linked to the root's emphasis on excusing and pardoning. This highlights the personal responsibility in acknowledging one's faults and the proactive step of seeking forgiveness, highlighting the moral value of humility and repentance.",
  "4452": "يَعْدُونَ and related words stem from the root ع-د-و, with the root verb عَدَا meaning \"he ran swiftly,\" \"he transgressed,\" or \"he acted aggressively.\" يَعْدُونَ means \"they run,\" \"they transgress,\" or \"they exceed limits.\" The connection lies in the action of swift movement or overstepping boundaries, directly relating to the root's emphasis on speed and transgression. This term highlights the dynamic nature of actions that can lead one away from the path of righteousness, emphasizing the need for self-control and guidance.",
  "4453": "يَعْرُجُ and related words stem from the root ع-ر-ج, with the root verb عَرَجَ meaning \"he ascended,\" \"he went up,\" or \"he climbed.\" يَعْرُجُ means \"he ascends\" or \"he is ascending.\" The action denotes the process of moving upward, directly connected to the root's concept of ascent. In a spiritual context, it may refer to prayers or deeds ascending to Allah (ﷻ), emphasizing the importance of righteous actions and the spiritual elevation of the soul.",
  "4454": "يَعْرِشُونَ and related words stem from the root ع-ر-ش, with the root verb عَرَشَ meaning \"he built,\" \"he constructed,\" or \"he erected.\" يَعْرِشُونَ means \"they build\" or \"they erect trellises,\" specifically referring to constructing supports or structures, such as trellises for vines or plants. The connection lies in the act of providing support and creating frameworks, reflecting the root's emphasis on building and structuring for growth and stability. This term highlights the importance of creating foundational support for development, both in a literal and metaphorical sense.",
  "4455": "يَعْزُبُ and related words stem from the root ع-ز-ب, with the root verb عَزَبَ meaning \"he was absent,\" \"he was distant,\" or \"he escaped notice.\" يَعْزُبُ means \"he goes unnoticed,\" \"he remains hidden,\" or \"he is distant.\" The connection lies in the idea of being beyond perception or awareness, emphasizing the root's concept of absence or remoteness. This reflects situations where something is concealed or escapes attention, highlighting the limitations of human perception compared to Divine knowledge.",
  "4456": "يَعْشُ and related words stem from the root ع-ش-و, with the root verb عَشَا meaning \"he became night-blind\" or \"his sight weakened in the dark.\" يَعْشُ means \"he becomes blinded\" or \"he cannot see.\" The connection lies in the loss of vision or clarity, reflecting the root's emphasis on darkness and obscurity. This term metaphorically highlights the inability to perceive guidance or truth, akin to being enveloped in darkness.",
  "4457": "يَعْصِرُونَ and related words stem from the root ع-ص-ر, with the root verb عَصَرَ meaning \"he squeezed\" or \"he pressed.\" يَعْصِرُونَ means \"they press\" or \"they extract.\" The connection emphasizes the action of squeezing or extracting, whether it be juice from fruit or oil from seeds. This term highlights the process of obtaining valuable substances through pressing.",
  "4458": "يَعْصِمُ and related words stem from the root ع-ص-م, with the root verb عَصَمَ meaning \"he protected\" or \"he held firmly.\" يَعْصِمُ means \"he protects\" or \"he preserves.\" The connection lies in the ongoing action of safeguarding or preventing harm, reflecting the root's emphasis on protection and firmness. This term emphasizes the continuous effort to maintain safety or purity, whether physically, morally, or spiritually.",
  "4459": "يَعْقُوبُ stems from the root ع-ق-ب, with the root verb عَقَبَ meaning \"he followed closely,\" \"came after,\" or \"succeeded.\" يَعْقُوبُ is the name of Prophet Jacob (ﷺ), known for his perseverance and the continuation of the prophetic lineage. The connection lies in his role as a successor to his father Prophet Isaac (ﷺ) and grandfather Prophet Abraham (ﷺ), embodying the root's concept of succession and continuity. This lineage highlights his role in the continuity of Allah's (ﷻ) favor and the perseverance of faith.",
  "4460": "يَعْكُفُونَ and related words stem from the root ع-ك-ف, with the root verb عَكَفَ meaning \"he devoted himself\" or \"he remained attached.\" يَعْكُفُونَ means \"they devote themselves,\" \"they remain devoted,\" or \"they continue in devotion.\" The connection lies in the ongoing act of dedication, reflecting the root's emphasis on persistent attachment. This term emphasizes maintaining steadfast devotion, particularly in worship or adherence to a practice, highlighting continuous commitment.",
  "4461": "يَعْمَهُونَ and related words stem from the root ع-م-ه, with the root verb عَمِهَ meaning \"he was bewildered,\" \"he was perplexed,\" or \"he wandered aimlessly.\" يَعْمَهُونَ means \"they wander blindly\" or \"they are in confusion.\" The connection lies in the state of being lost or without clear direction, reflecting the root's emphasis on bewilderment. This term illustrates the condition of those who lack guidance, emphasizing the need for divine direction to find purpose and clarity in life.",
  "4462": "يَغُضُّوا and related words stem from the root غ-ض-ض, with the root verb غَضَّ meaning \"he lowered,\" \"he reduced,\" or \"he lessened.\" يَغُضُّوا means \"they lower\" or \"they restrain.\" The connection lies in the act of reducing or lowering, directly relating to the root's meaning. This term is often used in the Qur'an to instruct believers to lower their gaze or restrain their desires, emphasizing self-control and modesty.",
  "4463": "يَغُوثُ and related words stem from the root غ-و-ث, with the root verb غَاثَ meaning \"he helped\" or \"provided relief.\" يَغُوثُ is the name of an idol worshipped by people before Prophet Noah (ﷺ), falsely regarded as a source of aid. Yaghuth was originally a righteous man, but his memory was corrupted into idolatry through the whispers of Satan. The connection to the root lies in the people's misguided belief that the idol could offer relief, aligning with the root’s concept of seeking help. يَغُوثُ symbolizes misplaced reliance on false gods, highlighting the futility of turning to anything other than Allah (ﷻ) for true support and guidance.",
  "4464": "يَغُوصُونَ and related words stem from the root غ-و-ص, with the root verb غَاصَ meaning \"he dived,\" \"plunged,\" or \"immersed.\" يَغُوصُونَ means \"they dive\" or \"they plunge,\" emphasizing the act of submerging oneself deeply into something, whether physically, such as diving into water, or metaphorically, such as immersing into a task or pursuit. This reflects the root’s themes of depth and immersion, highlighting an active engagement with or exploration of what lies beneath the surface.",
  "4465": "يَغْتَبْ and related words stem from the root غ-ي-ب, with the root verb غَابَ meaning \"he was absent\" or \"he vanished.\" يَغْتَبْ meaning \"he backbites\" or \"he slanders in absence.\" The connection lies in exploiting someone's absence to speak ill of them, reflecting the root's concept of absence being misused for harm. This highlights the moral admonition against backbiting, emphasizing respect and integrity even when others are not present.",
  "4466": "يَغْلِي and related words stem from the root غ-ل-ي, with the root verb غَلَىٰ meaning \"it boiled,\" \"seethed,\" or \"bubbled up.\" يَغْلِي means \"it boils\" or \"it is boiling.\" This form describes the ongoing action of boiling. The connection lies in depicting the dynamic process of rising heat and agitation, reflecting the root's emphasis on intensity. It can also metaphorically illustrate emotions or tensions currently escalating, highlighting immediacy and potential volatility.",
  "4467": "يَفْتَرُونَ and related words stem from the root ف-ر-ي, with the root verb فَرَىٰ meaning \"he cut,\" \"he cleaved,\" or \"he fabricated.\" يَفْتَرُونَ means \"they fabricate,\" \"they forge,\" or \"they invent falsely.\" Broader root meanings emphasize the act of cutting or reshaping, likening fabricating lies to metaphorically slicing into the truth and distorting it into something false. The connection lies in the ongoing nature of crafting deception, reflecting how falsehoods are actively and intentionally shaped to mislead.",
  "4468": "يَفْتُرُونَ and related words stem from the root ف-ت-ر, with the root verb فَتَرَ meaning \"he slackened\" or \"he became inactive.\" يَفْتُرُونَ means \"they slacken\" or \"they become inactive,\" highlighting the act of reducing effort. The connection lies in the process of losing momentum, reflecting the root's concept of diminishing activity. It emphasizes the importance of perseverance and maintaining effort over time.",
  "4469": "يَفْرُطَ and related words stem from the root ف-ر-ط, with the root verb فَرَطَ meaning \"he went ahead,\" \"he neglected,\" or \"he exceeded bounds.\" يَفْرُطَ means \"he may neglect\" or \"he may exceed limits.\" The connection lies in the potential to overstep boundaries or be negligent, directly relating to the root's concept of surpassing proper limits.",
  "4470": "يَفْسَحُ and related words stem from the root ف-س-ح, with the root verb فَسَحَ meaning \"he made wide,\" \"he expanded,\" or \"he made room.\" يَفْسَحُ means \"He makes room\" or \"He expands.\" In the Qur'an, it refers to Allah (ﷻ) making room for those who accommodate others. The connection emphasizes reciprocity and generosity, highlighting that making space for others leads to divine expansion in return.",
  "4471": "يَفْقَهُ and related words stem from the root ف-ق-ه, with the root verb فَقِهَ meaning \"he understood\" or \"he comprehended.\" يَفْقَهُ means \"he understands\" or \"he comprehends,\" indicating an ongoing state of awareness or insight. The connection lies in the root's focus on understanding and perception, highlighting the process of gaining knowledge and making sense of information in the present moment.",
  "4472": "يَقِينٌ and related words stem from the root ي-ق-ن, with the root verb يَقِنَ meaning \"he was certain.\" يَقِينٌ means \"certainty\" or \"sure knowledge,\" representing a state of firm conviction and complete clarity. The root encompasses broader concepts of stability, clarity, and unwavering assurance, emphasizing knowledge that is free from doubt. The connection lies in embodying the root’s essence, highlighting an unshakable certainty in faith and understanding, rooted in clarity and steadfastness.",
  "4473": "يَقْبَلُ and related words stem from the root ق-ب-ل, with the root verb قَبِلَ meaning \"he took, received, or admitted willingly,\" or \"he accepted.\" يَقْبَلُ means \"he accepts\" or \"he receives.\" The connection is direct, representing the continuous action of willingly receiving or taking something. It emphasizes receptiveness, openness, and adaptability, illustrating the root’s central theme of willingly engaging with what is presented. The ongoing nature of يَقْبَلُ reflects a state of readiness to accept or embrace, reinforcing the root's broader concept of willing reception and alignment.",
  "4474": "يَقْتُرُوا and related words stem from the root ق-ت-ر, with the root verb قَتَرَ meaning \"he was stingy.\" يَقْتُرُوا means \"they are stingy\" or \"they withhold,\" signifying the ongoing action of miserliness. The root carries the theme of constriction or limitation, reflecting a withholding nature that restricts generosity or provision. يَقْتُرُوا embodies this concept by emphasizing continuous behavior marked by reluctance to give or share. This highlights the persistent nature of stinginess, illustrating the effect of such actions in limiting not only material resources but also broader opportunities for mutual benefit and social harmony.",
  "4475": "يَقْرَبُوا and related words stem from the root ق-ر-ب, with the root verb قَرُبَ meaning \"he was near\" or \"he approached.\" يَقْرَبُوا means \"they approach\" or \"they draw near,\" highlighting the continuous action of coming closer. Broader root meanings emphasize nearness, connection, and movement toward proximity, whether physical, relational, or spiritual. The connection lies in the dynamic process of reducing distance, reflecting deliberate or natural movement toward closeness, whether to a goal, a place, or a relationship.",
  "4476": "يَقْطِينٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ط-ن, with the root verb قَطَنَ meaning \"he resided.\" يَقْطِينٌ refers to plants that spread along the ground, such as gourds. The connection lies in the plant's rapid growth and its ability to provide shade, reflecting themes of shelter and mercy. In the Qur'an, يَقْطِينٌ is mentioned in the story of Prophet Jonah (ﷺ), where Allah (ﷻ) caused a plant to grow over him, offering comfort and protection after he was cast ashore. This symbolizes Allah's (ﷻ) care during times of vulnerability, aligning with the root's idea of providing cover or residence.",
  "4477": "يَقْنُتْ and related words stem from the root ق-ن-ت, with the root verb قَنَتَ meaning \"he was obedient\" or \"he stood in long prayer.\" يَقْنُتْ means \"he is obedient,\" \"he remains devout,\" or \"he stands in prolonged prayer.\" The root conveys themes of obedience, devotion, and steadfastness, emphasizing acts of worship performed with humility and consistency. يَقْنُتْ reflects the state of ongoing submission and dedication to Allah (ﷻ), highlighting the importance of persistence in worship and the profound connection between physical acts, such as standing in prayer, and spiritual submission. This term embodies the essence of maintaining faith and devotion as central elements of worship and life.",
  "4478": "يَكْفُلُ and related words stem from the root ك-ف-ل, with the root verb كَفَلَ meaning \"he took care of,\" \"he guaranteed,\" or \"he supported.\" يَكْفُلُ means \"he takes responsibility for\" or \"he takes care of.\" The connection lies in the ongoing action of providing support or guardianship, reflecting the root's concept of continuous care. This term emphasizes the importance of sustained responsibility and the role of ongoing support in nurturing and protecting others.",
  "4479": "يَكْلَؤُ and related words stem from the root ك-ل-أ, with the root verb كَلَأَ meaning \"he guarded,\" \"he protected,\" or \"he watched over.\" It also conveys \"to preserve\" or \"to oversee.\" يَكْلَؤُ means \"he guards\" or \"he watches over,\" emphasizing vigilant care and oversight. The connection lies in providing continuous safeguarding, directly relating to the root's concept of active protection. This term highlights guardianship rooted in diligence and concern, often symbolizing Allah's (ﷻ) protective care, ensuring well-being and safety, both physically and in a broader sense.",
  "4480": "يَلُونَكُمْ and related words stem from the root و-ل-ي, with the root verb وَلِيَ meaning \"he was near,\" \"he befriended,\" or \"he protected.\" يَلُونَكُمْ means \"they are near to you\" or \"they come after you.\" The connection again lies in proximity and succession, emphasizing relationships of adjacency and the importance of those who are immediately connected to or following after someone, whether in family, responsibility, or confrontation.",
  "4481": "يَلِتَ and related words stem from the root ل-ي-ت, with the root verb لَاتَ meaning \"he diminished,\" \"he decreased,\" or \"he lessened.\" يَلِتَ means \"he diminishes,\" \"he lessens,\" or \"he reduces.\" The connection lies in the act of reducing or detracting from something. This reflects themes of loss or deprivation, emphasizing the consequences of actions that lead to diminishment. In the Qur'an, it refers to the assurance that certain actions do not detract from rewards or that justice will not be diminished.",
  "4482": "يَلِجُ and related words stem from the root و-ل-ج, with the root verb وَلَجَ meaning \"he or it entered.\" يَلِجُ means \"he or it enters,\" emphasizing the act of moving into or passing through something. The root conveys broader concepts of passage, transition, and initiation, highlighting access to a space, state, or condition. The connection reflects the fundamental idea of crossing a boundary or threshold, symbolizing movement, transformation, or beginning.",
  "4483": "يَلْوُونَ and related words stem from the root و-ل-ي, with the root verb لَوَىٰ meaning \"he twisted,\" \"he bent,\" \"he turned aside,\" \"he turned something away,\" \"he made something difficult,\" \"he concealed,\" or \"he waited.\" يَلْوُونَ means \"they turn\" or \"they twist,\" reflecting deliberate deviation or distortion. The root's meanings—twisting, bending, and waiting—connect through the idea of \"not following a direct path.\" Just as twisting or bending moves away from a straight line, waiting suggests a deliberate delay, a deviation from immediate action. These notions extend to acts of diversion or avoidance in speech, behavior, or judgment, reflecting movement away from clarity or truth.",
  "4484": "يَلْتَفِتْ and related words stem from the root ل-ف-ت, with the root verb لَفَتَ meaning \"he turned,\" \"he diverted,\" or \"he caused to turn away.\" يَلْتَفِتْ means \"he turns\" or \"he looks back.\" The root conveys the act of turning one’s body, gaze, or attention, emphasizing a change in direction or focus. This term highlights the deliberate action of redirecting oneself, whether physically by turning back or mentally by diverting attention. The connection reflects the importance of intentionality in actions and the risks of looking back or hesitating, symbolizing a break in momentum or determination when forward focus is required.",
  "4485": "يَلْحَقُوا and related words also derive from the root ل-ح-ق, with the root verb لَحِقَ carrying the meanings of \"he overtook,\" \"he reached,\" or \"he caught up.\" يَلْحَقُوا specifically means \"they overtake\" or \"they join,\" reflecting an ongoing action tied to the root’s emphasis on pursuit and effort. This term highlights the dynamic process of striving to catch up, reach, or align with something or someone, showcasing the root’s focus on bridging gaps and achieving connection. It encapsulates both the action of striving and the resultant alignment, tying the derived form to the root's foundational sense of connection and unification.",
  "4486": "يَلْعَبْ and related words stem from the root ل-ع-ب, with the root verb لَعِبَ meaning \"he played,\" \"he jested,\" or \"he engaged in amusement.\" يَلْعَبْ translates as \"he plays,\" describing the act of engaging in playful or leisure activities. The root emphasizes the notion of amusement or entertainment, highlighting actions characterized by a lack of gravity or serious intent.",
  "4487": "يَلْفِظُ and related words stem from the root ل-ف-ظ, with the root verb لَفَظَ meaning \"he expelled,\" \"he ejected,\" \"he uttered,\" or \"he pronounced.\" The root encompasses physically expelling something, such as spitting or vomiting, as well as metaphorically expelling words or expressions. يَلْفِظُ translates as \"he utters,\" \"he speaks,\" or \"he expels,\" emphasizing the act of bringing forth words or substances from the mouth. The connection lies in the deliberate action of ejecting something from within, reflecting the root's focus on expression, articulation, and outward projection. This duality links physical expulsion with the articulation of thoughts or words.",
  "4488": "يَلْمِزُونَ and related words stem from the root ل-م-ز, with the root verb لَمَزَ meaning \"he criticized\" or \"he found fault with.\" يَلْمِزُونَ means \"they criticize\" or \"they find fault,\" indicating an ongoing action of fault-finding or defamation. This term refers to individuals who habitually engage in criticizing or defaming others, whether through direct confrontation or behind their backs. It highlights the detrimental impact of such behavior on social harmony and personal relationships, emphasizing the importance of refraining from actions that sow discord and undermine trust within the community.",
  "4489": "يَلْهَثْ and related words stem from the root ل-ه-ث, with the root verb لَهَثَ meaning \"he panted,\" \"he gasped,\" or \"he breathed heavily.\" يَلْهَثْ means \"he pants,\" \"he gasps,\" or \"he continues to pant.\" The connection lies in the act of panting or breathing rapidly, reflecting the root's emphasis on labored breathing, often due to thirst, exhaustion, or exertion. This term paints a vivid picture of relentless desire or unfulfilled longing, as in the Qur'anic analogy of those who reject guidance being like a dog that pants whether chased away or left alone, emphasizing the insatiable nature of their desires.",
  "4490": "يَمُوجُ and related words stem from the root م-و-ج, with the root verb مَاجَ meaning \"it surged\" or \"it moved turbulently.\" يَمُوجُ means \"he/it surges\" or \"he/it moves turbulently.\" The connection emphasizes ongoing agitation or unrest, often symbolizing chaos or tumultuous events, reminding believers of the trials they may face.",
  "4491": "يَمِيزُ and related words stem from the root م-ي-ز, with the root verb مَازَ meaning \"he separated\" or \"he distinguished.\" يَمِيزُ translates to \"he distinguishes\" or \"he separates,\" reflecting the act of setting things apart based on clear criteria. The root encompasses themes of separation, discernment, and defining boundaries, symbolizing the purposeful act of differentiating truth from falsehood and purity from corruption. ",
  "4492": "يَمِيلُونَ and related words stem from the root م-ي-ل, with the root verb مَالَ meaning \"he inclined,\" \"he leaned,\" or \"he bent.\" يَمِيلُونَ means \"they incline,\" \"they lean,\" \"they deviate,\" or \"they attack,\" depending on the context. It captures actions of moving towards or away from something, often metaphorically indicating deviation, bias, or aggression.",
  "4493": "يَمِينٌ and related words stem from the root ي-م-ن, with the root verb يُمِنَ meaning \"he was prosperous\" or \"he was fortunate.\" يَمِينٌ means \"right hand\" or \"oath,\" referring to the right hand as a symbol of strength, trustworthiness, and authority, as well as the act of making a solemn promise. The root conveys broader concepts of goodness, blessings, and favor. The connection lies in the right hand's association with reliability and honor, reflecting the root's emphasis on prosperity and integrity through steadfastness and commitment.",
  "4494": "يَمْتَرُونَ and related words stem from the root م-ر-ي, with the root verb مَارَىٰ meaning \"he disputed,\" and امْتَرَىٰ meaning \"he doubted.\" يَمْتَرُونَ means \"they doubt,\" \"they are skeptical,\" or \"they dispute.\" The word reflects a persistent and ongoing state of questioning or contention, consistent with the root’s focus on doubt and disputation. يَمْتَرُونَ highlights both the internal struggle of skepticism and the external manifestation of this doubt through argument or debate.",
  "4495": "يَمْحَقُ and related words stem from the root م-ح-ق, with the root verb مَحَقَ meaning \"he blotted out,\" \"he wiped away,\" or \"he caused something to diminish until it vanished.\" يَمْحَقُ means \"he eradicates\" or \"he annihilates,\" emphasizing the gradual and total removal of something. The connection lies in the root's essence of obliteration or reduction to nothingness, often reflecting the idea of divine retribution or correction through the nullification of what is corrupt or undesired. It highlights the power to eliminate completely, leaving no trace of what once existed.",
  "4496": "يَمْهَدُونَ and related words stem from the root م-ه-د, with the root verb مَهَدَ meaning \"he spread out\" or \"he prepared.\" يَمْهَدُونَ means \"they prepare\" or \"they make smooth,\" reflecting ongoing effort in facilitating or readying something. The connection emphasizes ongoing action in facilitating or readying something. It highlights continuous, deliberate action to create ease, improve conditions, or lay groundwork for stability and progress. It emphasizes the human role in maintaining and enhancing environments, whether physical or spiritual.",
  "4497": "يَنَالُ stems from the root ن-ي-ل, with the root verb نَالَ meaning \"he attained,\" \"he acquired,\" or \"he reached.\" يَنَالُ translates to \"he obtains\" or \"he acquires,\" emphasizing the act of reaching or achieving something. The root also carries the meanings of \"granting\" or \"giving,\" highlighting not only the effort involved in acquisition but also the possibility of receiving something as a result of access or permission. This duality reflects themes of striving, opportunity, and reciprocity, illustrating that attainment often involves both effort and grace.",
  "4498": "يَنْبُوعٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ب-ع, with the root verb نَبَعَ meaning \"it sprang forth\" or \"it gushed forth.\" يَنْبُوعٌ means \"spring\" or \"fountain.\" The connection lies in representing a source of water flowing abundantly from the earth, aligning with the root's focus on gushing forth. This symbolizes sustenance, life, and the continuous provision from Allah (ﷻ), highlighting themes of abundance and renewal in creation.",
  "4499": "يَنْتَظِرُونَ and related words stem from the root ن-ظ-ر, with the root verb نَظَرَ meaning \"he looked,\" \"he observed,\" or \"he considered.\" يَنْتَظِرُونَ means \"they wait\" or \"they are waiting,\" emphasizing a state of anticipation or preparation for what is to come. The connection lies in the act of waiting with observant attention, reflecting the root's broader themes of careful observation, thoughtful consideration, and patience. This highlights the interplay between observation and expectation, showing how waiting often requires both attentiveness and readiness for change or action.",
  "4500": "يَنْسَخُ and related words stem from the root ن-س-خ, with the root verb نَسَخَ meaning \"he copied,\" \"he transcribed,\" or \"he abrogated.\" يَنْسَخُ means \"he copies,\" \"he transcribes,\" or \"he abrogates.\" This verb conveys the ongoing action of abrogating or replacing, directly relating to the root's concept. In the Qur'anic context, it often refers to Allah's (ﷻ) abrogation of previous verses or laws with new ones, highlighting His wisdom and the progression of guidance to suit changing circumstances. It emphasizes the importance of adhering to the current divine instructions.",
  "4501": "يَنْسِلُونَ and related words stem from the root ن-س-ل, with the root verb نَسَلَ meaning \"he hastened,\" \"he moved swiftly,\" or \"he reproduced.\" يَنْسِلُونَ means \"they hasten\" or \"they rush forth,\" illustrating swift and continuous movement. The root's broader meanings also include procreation and dispersal, highlighting the dynamic spread of life or beings. The connection lies in the imagery of rapid emergence or spreading, whether in physical motion or generational continuity. يَنْسِلُونَ reflects the urgency and energy inherent in life's movement, tying the swift action of rushing forth to the root's overarching theme of expansion and propagation.",
  "4502": "يَنْطِقُونَ and related words stem from the root ن-ط-ق, with the root verb نَطَقَ meaning \"he spoke\" or \"he uttered.\" يَنْطِقُونَ means \"they speak\" or \"they are is speaking.\" The connection lies in the ongoing action of speech, emphasizing the continual ability to articulate and express oneself. This reflects the root's focus on utterance and communication, highlighting the importance of using this faculty responsibly and truthfully.",
  "4503": "يَنْقَضَّ and related words stem from the root ق-ض-ض, with the root verb قَضَّ meaning \"he broke,\" \"he shattered,\" or \"he caused to fall apart.\" يَنْقَضَّ means \"it collapses,\" \"it crumbles,\" or \"it falls apart,\" emphasizing the sudden and forceful breaking or disintegration of something. The connection lies in the violent and complete nature of the collapse, often caused by structural weakness or external force. The root highlights themes of fragility, instability, and the inevitable consequence of weakness in foundations, whether physical or metaphorical. This term serves as a vivid reminder of how even the strongest structures or systems can crumble when their integrity is compromised.",
  "4504": "يَنْحِتُونَ and related words stem from the root ن-ح-ت, with the root verb نَحَتَ meaning \"he carved\" or \"he sculpted.\" يَنْحِتُونَ means \"they carve\" or \"they are carving.\" The connection lies in the act of shaping or fashioning something by cutting away material, highlighting themes of creation, craftsmanship, and manipulation. This can symbolize human creativity but also serves as a caution against idolatry, reflecting on the misuse of skills in creating objects of worship.",
  "4505": "يَنْعٌ and related words stem from the root ي-ن-ع, with the root verb يَنَعَ meaning \"it ripened.\" يَنْعٌ means \"ripeness\" or \"maturity.\" The connection lies in the culmination of growth and development, reflecting the root's emphasis on reaching perfection and readiness.",
  "4506": "يَنْعِقُ and related words stem from the root ن-ع-ق, with the root verb نَعَقَ meaning \"he shouted,\" \"he cried out,\" or \"he called.\" The root also conveys meanings tied to loud, echoing cries, such as a shepherd's call to sheep or the caw of a raven. يَنْعِقُ means \"he calls out\" or \"he cries aloud,\" often implying repetitive, hollow sounds. In the Qur'anic context, it metaphorically describes those who preach without understanding, likened to noise heard without comprehension. This emphasizes the distinction between sound and meaning, highlighting the responsibility in both delivering and understanding communication.",
  "4507": "يَهُودُ and related words stem from the root ه-و-د, with the root verb هَادَ meaning \"he turned back\" or \"he repented.\" يَهُودُ refers to \"Jews,\" the followers of Judaism. The root emphasizes returning, reflecting the identity of a people repeatedly called to Allah (ﷻ) through repentance and obedience. It highlights their role as recipients of divine guidance through prophets sent to guide them back to the straight path. This term conveys themes of divine testing and the necessity of adhering to Allah’s (ﷻ) commands, offering profound lessons on the importance of steadfastness, accountability, and taking responsibility for one's actions.",
  "4508": "يَهِيجُ and related words stem from the root ه-ي-ج, with the root verb هَاجَ meaning \"he stirred,\" \"he provoked,\" or \"it dried up.\" يَهِيجُ means \"it becomes agitated,\" \"it stirs,\" or \"it dries up.\" The root conveys themes of movement, agitation, and transformation, reflecting changes in state or condition. In the Qur'an, it describes plants that flourish and then wither, symbolizing the transient nature of life and the inevitable decline of worldly matters. This connection emphasizes the cyclical nature of existence, highlighting the contrast between vitality and decay.",
  "4509": "يَهِيمُونَ and related words stem from the root ه-ي-م, with the root verb هَامَ meaning \"he wandered aimlessly\" or \"he became passionately in love.\" يَهِيمُونَ means \"they wander aimlessly\" or \"they are passionately in love,\" embodying the uncontrolled nature of their actions or feelings. The connection lies in the root's emphasis on unrestrained movement and intense emotion, whether physical or metaphorical. This term evokes a state of being consumed by desire or lost without direction, mirroring the way emotions or needs can drive individuals into aimless or relentless pursuits.",
  "4510": "يَهْبِطُ and related words stem from the root ه-ب-ط, with the root verb هَبَطَ meaning \"he descended,\" \"he came down,\" or \"he landed.\" يَهْبِطُ means \"he descends\" or \"he comes down,\" emphasizing the act of moving from a higher place to a lower one. The root conveys themes of descent, whether physical, such as coming down to a lower ground, or metaphorical, such as a change in state or condition. It reflects transitions that involve a shift in position or status, highlighting both literal movement and figurative changes, such as departing from a higher state to a lower one or adapting to a new environment.",
  "4511": "يَهْجَعُونَ and related words stem from the root ه-ج-ع, with the root verb هَجَعَ meaning \"he slept,\" particularly at night. يَهْجَعُونَ means \"they sleep\" or \"they are sleeping.\" The term هُجُوعٌ refers specifically to nocturnal sleep, often implying a light or brief slumber during the early part of the night. This root conveys themes of rest, tranquility, and the natural human inclination to seek repose after daily activities.",
  "4512": "يَوْمٌ and related words stem from the root ي-و-م, meaning \"day.\" It denotes a period from sunrise to sunset or a 24-hour cycle. The connection is direct, embodying the root's focus on time, cycles, and the progression of events, symbolizing the rhythm of life and creation.",
  "4513": "يُؤَاخِذُ and related words stem from the root أ-خ-ذ, with root verb verb أَخَذَ meaning \"he took.\" يُؤَاخِذُ means \"to take to account,\" referring to the act of reproaching or holding someone responsible. The connection lies in the act of taking someone to task or seizing upon their faults, directly reflecting the root's concept of taking. In the Qur'an, this word is often used in the context of delaying accountability and giving people the opportunity to repent and seek forgiveness, highlighting Allah’s (ﷻ) mercy, patience, and compassion.",
  "4514": "يُؤَدِّ and related words stem from the root أ-د-ى, with the root verb أَدَّىٰ meaning \"he fulfilled,\" \"he performed,\" \"he delivered,\" or \"he paid.\" يُؤَدِّ means \"he performs,\" \"he fulfills,\" \"he pays,\" or \"he discharges,\" but in a specific grammatical form that implies either a command or an action tied to a condition. The connection reflects the ongoing action of fulfilling a duty or obligation, emphasizing the need to carry it out properly. This form highlights the importance of responsibility and performing one's duty with care and diligence.",
  "4515": "يُؤْثَرُ and related words stem from the root أ-ث-ر, with the root verb أَثَرَ meaning \"he left a mark\" or \"he transmitted.\" يُؤْثَرُ is a passive form meaning \"it is transmitted.\" The connection lies in the transmission of knowledge, traditions, or stories that leave an enduring mark on collective memory, reflecting the root's concept of imprinting and tracking. يُؤْثَرُ emphasizes the importance of preserving and conveying wisdom from one generation to the next, highlighting the role of narratives in shaping moral values.",
  "4516": "يُؤْلُونَ and related words stem from the root أ-ل-و, with the root verb أَلَا meaning \"he fell short\" or \"he neglected to act,\" and آلَىٰ meaning \"he swore an oath.\" يُؤْلُونَ means \"they swear an oath,\" emphasizing the binding and serious nature of promises. This reflects a deep connection between the act of taking an oath and the moral obligation to uphold it, as failing to fulfill a promise is akin to falling short in one’s responsibility. The word conveys the weight of commitment and the restraint it imposes, highlighting the importance of accountability and the moral integrity required to honor one's word.",
  "4517": "يُبَتِّكُنَّ and related words stem from the root ب-ت-ك, with the root verb بَتَكَ meaning \"he cut\" or \"he severed.\" يُبَتِّكُنَّ translates as \"they cut\" or \"they mutilate,\" describing the act of cutting something completely, resulting in an irreversible separation. The connection lies in altering or disrupting something from its natural form, reflecting the root’s concept of severing or causing distortion. In the Qur'an, it refers to those who alter Allah's (ﷻ) creation in unnatural ways, highlighting the significance of preserving the intended harmony and integrity of Allah’s (ﷻ) creation.",
  "4518": "يُبَصَّرُونَ and related words stem from the root ب-ص-ر, with the root verb بَصُرَ meaning \"he saw\" or \"he was endowed with mental perception, belief, firm belief, knowledge, understanding, intelligence, or skill.\" يُبَصَّرُونَ is a passive form, meaning \"they will be made to see\" or \"they will be shown,\" indicating that clarity or awareness will be imposed upon them. This term emphasizes an unavoidable realization, where hidden truths are brought to light, compelling recognition and understanding regardless of prior ignorance or denial.",
  "4519": "يُبَطِّئَ and related words stem from the root ب-ط-أ, with the root verb بَطُؤَ meaning \"he delayed\" or \"he was slow,\" and بَطَّأَ meaning \"he caused to delay\" or \"he held back.\" يُبَطِّئَ means \"he causes to delay\" or \"he holds back,\" emphasizing intentional hesitation, particularly in situations demanding urgency or decisiveness. The root conveys themes of slowness, delay, and withholding, suggesting a deliberate choice to restrain or postpone action. يُبَطِّئَ reflects conscious hesitation, which may stem from caution, reluctance, or resistance, contrasting the need for timely response with the effects of delay, whether prudent or procrastinated.",
  "4520": "يُبِينُ and related words stem from the root ب-ي-ن, with the root verb بَانَ meaning \"it became separated, severed, disunited, or cut off,\" or \"it became apparent, manifest, evident, or clear\" or \"it became distinct,\" implying separation from others. يُبِينُ specifically refers to the act of making something clear or clarifying it, emphasizing the ongoing process of explanation to ensure understanding or distinction. The root ب-ي-ن encompasses broader meanings such as clarity, evidence, discernment, and differentiation. These related meanings highlight the importance of transparency, providing evidence, and the ability to distinguish things clearly.",
  "4521": "يُبْدِئُ and related words stem from the root ب-د-أ, with the root verb بَدَأَ meaning \"he began\" or \"he commenced.\" يُبْدِئُ means \"he begins\" and is linked to the act of initiating or bringing something into existence. The broader root concept encompasses the idea of a first-time occurrence or creation from nothing, highlighting not only the start of something new but also the unique power involved in original creation. In the Qur'an, يُبْدِئُ often alludes to Allah's (ﷻ) continuous creative power, bringing forth life and phenomena in ways that display divine wisdom and originality.",
  "4522": "يُبْدِلَ and related words stem from the root ب-د-ل, with the root verb بَدَلَ meaning \"he exchanged\" or \"he replaced.\" يُبْدِلَ means \"he replaces\" or \"he substitutes.\" The root conveys not only the idea of substitution but also a broader sense of transformation, where something is intentionally exchanged, altered, or replaced with something else. This reflects a purposeful act of change, whether to improve, adapt, or discard, and often implies a shift in state or condition. يُبْدِلَ thus emphasizes an active and deliberate replacement, aligning with the root’s themes of change and renewal.",
  "4523": "يُبْدِينَ and related words stem from the root ب-د-و, with the root verb بَدَا meaning \"he or it became apparent\" or \"he or it appeared.\" يُبْدِينَ means \"they reveal\" or \"they make apparent,\" referring to the action of bringing something into visibility or making it known. The root conveys themes of appearance, revelation, and making things visible. يُبْدِينَ emphasizes the act of disclosing or uncovering, often used in the Qur'an in the context of revealing specific matters, reflecting the root’s focus on clarity and awareness.",
  "4524": "يُبْطِلُ and related words stem from the root ب-ط-ل, with the root verb بَطَلَ meaning \"it was, or became, false, untrue, incorrect, fictitious, spurious, unfounded, or unsound.\" يُبْطِلُ means \"he or it invalidates,\" \"he or it nullifies,\" or \"he or it makes void,\" describing the act of rendering something ineffective or devoid of value. The root conveys themes of falsehood, invalidation, and futility, emphasizing the process of stripping away perceived worth or validity, exposing it as baseless or empty. This reflects the notion of uncovering deception or revealing the lack of substance in something seemingly significant.",
  "4525": "يُبْلِسُ and related words stem from the root ب-ل-س, with the root verb بَلَسَ meaning \"he was confused, and silenced by grief or misfortune,\" and أَبْلَسَ meaning \"he despaired.\" يُبْلِسُ describes being overwhelmed by grief and confusion, silenced by misfortune, and unable to find relief. This silence often leads to despair, either from failing to seek forgiveness or realizing it is too late. The root conveys profound emotional and spiritual defeat, as if severed from relief or guidance, engulfed by sorrow. Notably, the name إِبْلِيسُ derives from this root, signifying \"the one who despaired,\" highlighting his total loss of hope in Allah's (ﷻ) mercy.",
  "4526": "يُبْلِيَ and related words stem from the root ب-ل-و, with the root verb بَلَا meaning \"he tried, proved, or tested,\" referring to testing in a general sense to reveal the nature of someone or something. يُبْلِيَ refers to the ongoing action of testing or subjecting someone to trials, examining their character, faith, or patience. The root also includes the meaning of \"smelting,\" which involves purifying metal through intense heat. This root meaning deepens the concept of يُبْلِيَ, as it implies that these ongoing tests refine and reveal a person’s true essence, much like smelting purifies metal to expose its purity.",
  "4527": "ثُبُورٌ and related words stem from the root ث-ب-ر, with the root verb ثَبَرَ meaning \"he confined, restrained, withheld, hindered, or prevented,\" or \"he expelled,\" or \"he destroyed.\" This root conveys overarching themes of severance, prevention, and irreversible harm. In its extended usage, ثُبُورٌ refers to \"destruction\" or \"perdition,\" encapsulating a state of devastating ruin. The connection to the root lies in the sense of hindering existence or severing continuity, where destruction is the ultimate act of breaking. This term portrays profound despair and invoking destruction upon oneself, often out of overwhelming regret or suffering, emphasizing the finality of ruin in physical and emotional realms.",
  "4528": "يُجَاوِرُونَ and related words stem from the root ج-و-ر, with the root verb جَاوَرَ meaning \"he became a neighbor.\" The root encompasses meanings of proximity, association, and residing in close quarters. يُجَاوِرُونَ means \"they remain as neighbors\" or \"they dwell near,\" reflecting close companionship or association. This term highlights the significant influence of one’s environment and companions, emphasizing the importance of maintaining positive and meaningful relationships.",
  "4529": "يُجَنَّبُ and related words stem from the root ج-ن-ب, with the root verb جَنَبَ meaning \"he placed at a distance, sent away, or turned aside.\" The root broadly conveys meanings of avoiding, distancing, or being on the side of something, often implying separation or protection. يُجَنَّبُ means \"he is kept away from\" or \"he is averted,\" signifying being caused to avoid something, often through divine protection or guidance. This reflects the notion of Allah’s (ﷻ) mercy and care in shielding one from harm or misguidance, emphasizing His role in safeguarding His servants from what may lead to detriment.",
  "4530": "يُجِيرُ and related words stem from the root ج-و-ر, with the root verb جَارَ meaning \"he declined or deviated from the right course\" and جاوَرَ meaning \"he became a neighbor.\" أَجَارَ means \"he protected\" or \"he granted refuge,\" and يُجِيرُ means \"He gives protection\" or \"He grants refuge,\" emphasizing the act of providing safety and sanctuary. The root conveys meanings of deviating, granting refuge, and seeking protection. In the context of true protection, only Allah (ﷻ) possesses the absolute power to grant it, encompassing unmatched mercy and the ability to safeguard His creation. This highlights Allah (ﷻ) as the ultimate source of sanctuary, providing protection beyond any creation.",
  "4531": "يُجْبَىٰ and related words stem from the root ج-ب-ي, with the root verb جَبَىٰ meaning \"he collected\" or \"he appropriated a thing exclusively to himself.\" يُجْبَىٰ is a passive form meaning \"it is collected\" or \"it is gathered.\" This expression highlights the action of bringing components together, focusing on the systematic assembly of parts into a whole. The root conveys themes of accumulation and assembly, emphasizing the process where various elements are unified or compiled. This broader concept highlights the organized nature of collection, whether it pertains to physical items, data, or other forms of resources, reflecting a cohesive gathering of disparate parts.",
  "4532": "يُحَادُّونَ and related words stem from the root ح-د-د, with the root verb حَدَّ meaning \"he sharpened\" or \"he prevented, impeded, withheld, or restrained.\" يُحَادُّونَ means \"they oppose\" or \"they show enmity.\" The connection lies in setting oneself against another by creating a boundary, reflecting the root’s concept of restriction and separation. Just as something sharp defines limits, opposition establishes division, preventing reconciliation. This word signifies active defiance, where enmity reinforces barriers, making the conflict firm and decisive.",
  "4533": "يُحَافِظُونَ and related words stem from the root ح-ف-ظ, with the root verb حَفِظَ meaning \"he guarded,\" \"he protected,\" or \"he preserved.\" حَافَظَ adds an element of mutuality or intensity, meaning \"he guarded carefully,\" \"he observed,\" or \"he maintained diligently.\" يُحَافِظُونَ means \"they carefully guard,\" \"they maintain,\" or \"they observe,\" reflecting the ongoing action of diligently safeguarding or upholding something. The root conveys themes of vigilant care, meticulous attention, and protection, emphasizing sustained effort.",
  "4534": "يُحَاوِرُ and related words stem from the root ح-و-ر, with the root verb حَارَ meaning \"he returned or reverted.\" يُحَاوِرُ means \"he converses\" or \"he engages in dialogue,\" emphasizing a dynamic exchange of ideas through reciprocal interaction. The root conveys themes of returning, purification, and clarity. Dialogue itself reflects the idea of \"returning,\" as responses move back and forth between participants, shaping and refining understanding. This term also extends to discussions involving contention, disputes, or boasting, showing how conversation—like the root’s themes of motion and change—can shift perspectives, challenge ideas, and lead to clarity.",
  "4535": "يُحَذِّرُ and related words stem from the root ح-ذ-ر, with the root verb حَذِرَ meaning \"he was cautious\" or \"he was vigilant.\" يُحَذِّرُ means \"he warns\" or \"he cautions.\" The connection lies in causing others to be cautious, reflecting the root's emphasis on alertness. It highlights the act of warning someone about potential dangers to help them avoid harm, emphasizing the importance of guidance and protection.",
  "4536": "يُحَرِّفُونَ and related words stem from the root ح-ر-ف, with the root verb حَرَفَ meaning \"he altered\" or \"he distorted.\" يُحَرِّفُونَ means \"they alter\" or \"they distort.\" The connection lies in actively changing or twisting something from its original form, reflecting the root's sense of deviation. It emphasizes the act of misrepresenting or modifying content, often deceptively.",
  "4537": "يُحَكِّمُونَ and related words stem from the root ح-ك-م, with the root verb حَكَمَ meaning \"he judged\" or \"he governed.\" يُحَكِّمُونَ means \"they seek judgment\" or \"they appeal to a judge,\" reflecting the act of turning to an authority for decision-making or dispute resolution. The root also conveys the ideas of restraining, controlling, and ensuring firmness, highlighting how judgment is not merely about decision-making but also about upholding justice and preventing disorder. The connection lies in invoking governance to establish justice, emphasizing the root's focus on fairness, balance, and the application of wisdom to resolve matters decisively.",
  "4538": "يُحِقَّ and related words stem from the root ح-ق-ق, with the root verb حَقَّ meaning \"it was true,\" \"it became established,\" or \"it was necessitated.\" يُحِقَّ means \"He establishes\" or \"He makes true,\" signifying the active process of bringing truth into reality and fulfilling rights. The root conveys certainty, confirmation, and realization, highlighting how truth is not just a concept but something firmly upheld and executed. This term emphasizes the active role of making justice prevail and ensuring rightful matters come to pass.",
  "4539": "يُحْبَرُ and related words stem from the root ح-ب-ر, with the root verb حَبَرَ meaning \"he made [him] happy\" or \"he granted ease and plenty,\" extending to treating with honor. يُحْبَرُ is a passive form meaning \"he is delighted,\" referring to being adorned or filled with joy and happiness. The root conveys meanings of beautification, honor, and elevated joy, emphasizing how happiness is not merely an internal state but is reflected outwardly through blessings and distinction. This highlights that true delight comes from being granted ease, honor, and favor, reinforcing the idea that joy is both a gift and a sign of being elevated in status.",
  "4540": "يُحْدِثُ and related words stem from the root ح-د-ث, with the root verb حَدَثَ meaning \"it was new or recent,\" or \"it came into existence,\" or \"it happened.\" يُحْدِثُ means \"he brings about\" or \"he causes to happen.\" The connection lies in actively initiating events, embodying the root's concept of occurrences. It highlights the role of an agent in causing new happenings, emphasizing the capacity to effect change or introduce developments.",
  "4541": "يُحْفِكُمْ and related words stem from the root ح-ف-و, with the root verb حَفِيَ meaning \"he inquired earnestly,\" \"he showed much honor,\" or \"he was deeply attentive and concerned.\" The root conveys persistence, pressing inquiry, and care. يُحْفِكُمْ means \"he persists in questioning you\" or \"he urges you persistently.\" In this context, it emphasizes urgency and insistence, particularly in repeated questioning or persistent requests. This persistence can sometimes uncover reluctance or hidden emotions, revealing the tension between genuine concern and the pressure of insistence. The meaning highlights how constant inquiry influences relationships, balancing care with the potential strain of persistence.",
  "4542": "يُحْمَدُوا and related words stem from the root ح-م-د, with the root verb حَمِدَ meaning \"he praised\" or \"he thanked.\" يُحْمَدُوا is a passive form meaning \"they are praised.\" The connection lies in the state of receiving praise, reflecting continuous recognition for admirable qualities or actions. This term emphasizes the lasting nature of praise granted to those who embody virtue and excellence.",
  "4543": "يُخَادِعُونَ and related words stem from the root خ-د-ع, with the root verb خَدَعَ meaning \"he deceived.\" يُخَادِعُونَ means \"they try to deceive\" or \"they seek to deceive,\" indicating a reciprocal or intensified action. The root encompasses themes of active attempts and cunning strategies, often involving mutual deception. The connection emphasizes the effort and engagement in a dynamic process of deception, reflecting the interplay of trickery between the deceiver and their target.",
  "4544": "يُخَالِفُونَ and related words stem from the root خ-ل-ف, with the root verb خَلَفَ meaning \"he came after\" or \"he succeeded.\" The root conveys succession, substitution, and contrast, where one follows another or deviates from what preceded. يُخَالِفُونَ means \"they oppose\" or \"they disobey,\" emphasizing actions that go against established norms, commands, or expectations. This reflects the act of divergence, whether in thought, behavior, or allegiance, highlighting the contrast between adherence and defiance, conformity and resistance.",
  "4545": "يُخَوِّفُ and related words stem from the root خ-و-ف, with the root verb خَوَّفَ meaning \"he frightened\" or \"he intimidated.\" يُخَوِّفُ means \"he causes fear\" or \"he intimidates,\" reflecting the act of deliberately instilling fear in another. The root conveys themes of heightened awareness, caution, and emotional responses to perceived danger. يُخَوِّفُ emphasizes fear as a tool that can serve as a warning or deterrent, encouraging reflection and vigilance. It highlights the dual nature of fear—either as a protective guide or as a means of control—depending on its intent and application.",
  "4546": "يُخَيَّلُ and related words stem from the root خ-ي-ل, with the root verb خَالَ meaning \"he imagined (something to be in a certain way)\" or \"he perceived (something) in his mind.\" The root revolves around imagination, perception, illusion, and grandeur, conveying both mental perception and physical presence. يُخَيَّلُ is a passive form meaning \"it is made to appear\" or \"it seems,\" referring to something perceived as real or true, whether through illusion, deception, or impression. The connection to the root highlights how perception can be shaped by external influences, reinforcing the idea that what appears real may sometimes be an illusion or a product of one's imagination.",
  "4547": "يُخْرِبُونَ and related words stem from the root خ-ر-ب, with the root verb خَرِبَ meaning \"it became in a state of ruin, uninhabited or deserted.\" يُخْرِبُونَ means \"they ruin\" or \"they destroy,\" emphasizing active efforts to bring about ruin or devastation. The root encompasses themes of desolation, decay, and abandonment, highlighting the process of something once functional or whole deteriorating into a state of uselessness. The connection highlights the deliberate nature of causing destruction, whether through neglect, violence, or intentional acts, reflecting the root's focus on both the result of ruin and the actions leading to it.",
  "4548": "يُخْسِرُونَ and related words stem from the root خ-س-ر, with the root verb خَسِرَ meaning \"he lost.\" يُخْسِرُونَ means \"they cause loss\" or \"they defraud.\" The root conveys themes of deprivation, failure, and ruin. This word emphasizes the act of actively making others incur loss, whether through dishonesty, exploitation, or unfair dealings. It reflects ongoing harmful actions that disadvantage others, reinforcing the root’s focus on deliberate deprivation and its consequences.",
  "4549": "يُدَافِعُ and related words stem from the root د-ف-ع, with the root verb دَفَعَ meaning \"he repelled or pushed away\" or \"he prevented or averted.\" دَافَعَ means \"he defended\" or \"he repelled,\" while يُدَافِعُ means \"he defends\" or \"he repels,\" emphasizing an ongoing action. The root conveys both physical movement (pushing, resisting) and figurative actions (defense, prevention, or warding off harm). Just as defending requires continuous effort to resist or push back threats, this word reflects an active and persistent struggle to protect, prevent harm, or maintain safety.",
  "4550": "يُدْحِضُوا and related words stem from the root د-ح-ض, with the root verb دَحَضَ meaning \"it slipped, slided, or became unstable\" or \"it became null, void, or baseless.\" أَدْحَضَ means \"he invalidated\" or \"he refuted,\" while يُدْحِضُوا means \"they invalidate\" or \"they refute,\" emphasizing the act of disproving or rendering something void. The root revolves around slipping, instability, refutation, and invalidation, conveying both physical unsteadiness and the conceptual weakening of an argument. Just as something that slips loses stability and collapses, this word reflects the act of making a claim or position unsustainable, showing its failure to withstand truth.",
  "4551": "يُدْهِنُونَ and related words stem from the root د-ه-ن, with the root verb دَهَنَ meaning \"he anointed\" or \"he oiled.\" يُدْهِنُونَ means \"they flatter\" or \"they compromise,\" emphasizing the act of softening or concealing the truth, akin to applying oil to smooth things over. The root revolves around oiliness or greasiness, both in a literal sense (relating to substances like oil or grease) and metaphorically (implying deceit or hypocrisy). Just as oil makes surfaces sleek and slippery, this word reflects speech or actions intended to pacify, appease, or manipulate by smoothing over matters rather than addressing them honestly.",
  "4552": "يُذَبِّحُونَ and related words stem from the root ذ-ب-ح, with the root verb ذَبَحَ meaning \"he slaughtered\" or \"he sacrificed.\" يُذَبِّحُونَ means \"they massacre\" or \"they slaughter extensively,\" indicating an intensified or repeated action. The connection emphasizes the severity and magnitude of the act, reflecting the root's focus on slaughter but with added intensity. It brings to mind historical accounts of oppression or mass killings, highlighting the consequences of unchecked tyranny and injustice.",
  "4553": "يُرَاءُونَ and related words stem from the root ر-أ-ي, with the root verb رَأَىٰ meaning \"he saw\" or \"he perceived.\" يُرَاءُونَ means \"they make themselves seen\" or \"they act to be seen by others,\" describing an ongoing effort to ensure visibility and attract attention. This form highlights deliberate actions aimed at being noticed, reflecting the root's emphasis on sight and observation. It conveys themes of hypocrisy, where deeds are performed for external approval rather than sincerity, emphasizing the focus on appearances rather than genuine intent.",
  "4554": "يُرْضُونَ and related words stem from the root ر-ض-و, with the root verb رَضِيَ meaning \"he was pleased,\" \"he approved,\" or \"he was satisfied.\" يُرْضُونَ means \"they please\" or \"they satisfy.\" The root conveys themes of contentment, approval, and mutual satisfaction. In context, it emphasizes collective actions or conditions that bring about shared satisfaction or approval, whether among people or between creation and the Creator. This highlights the importance of striving for harmony and actions that collectively align with what is pleasing to Allah (ﷻ), as ultimate contentment stems from His approval.",
  "4555": "يُرْضِعْ and related words stem from the root ر-ض-ع, with the root verb رَضَعَ meaning \"he suckled\" or \"he nursed.\" يُرْضِعْ means \"he/she breastfeeds\" or \"he/she nurses.\" The connection is in the ongoing action of providing nourishment, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on the act of nursing. This term underscores the continuous and essential process of nurturing through breastfeeding, highlighting the sustained care required during early development.",
  "4556": "يُرْهِقَ and related words stem from the root ر-ه-ق, with the root verb رَهِقَ meaning \"he overtook\" or \"he oppressed.\" يُرْهِقَ means \"he burdens\" or \"he causes oppression.\" The connection lies in actively imposing hardship or burden upon another, directly relating to the root's meaning. This form emphasizes causing someone else to experience oppression or difficulty.",
  "4557": "يُزْجِي and related words stem from the root ز-ج-و, with the verb زَجَا meaning \"he drove forward\" or \"he propelled.\" يُزْجِي means \"he drives\" or \"he propels,\" referring to the act of causing movement or progression. The root embodies the concept of advancing or pushing forward, which is directly reflected in يُزْجِي as it highlights an active, deliberate act of propulsion. This connection highlights the root's core idea of facilitating movement or guiding something along its course with intention and direction.",
  "4558": "يُزْلِقُونَ and related words stem from the root ز-ل-ق, with the root verb زَلَقَ meaning \"he slipped,\" \"he slid,\" or \"he lost footing.\" يُزْلِقُونَ means \"they cause to slip\" or \"they make (someone) falter,\" referring to the act of causing another to lose footing, whether physically or metaphorically. The root also encompasses meanings of causing instability, faltering, or inducing an error. The connection lies in creating indirect conditions that lead to instability or mistakes, symbolizing the act of leading someone astray, unsettling their position, or undermining their confidence.",
  "4559": "يُسَارِعُونَ and related words stem from the root س-ر-ع, with the root verb سَرُعَ meaning \"he was quick\" or \"he hastened.\" يُسَارِعُونَ means \"they hasten\" or \"they strive quickly,\" emphasizing urgency and eagerness in action. This form implies mutual participation or intensified effort, reflecting the root’s focus on speed and proactive behavior. In the Qur'an, يُسَارِعُونَ describes those hastening towards both disbelief and good deeds, highlighting the importance of striving eagerly for righteousness while avoiding haste in wrongdoing.",
  "4560": "يُسِيغُ and related words stem from the root س-و-غ, with the root verb ساغَ meaning \"it was easy to swallow.\" أَسَاغَ means \"he allowed (it) to be swallowed\" or \"he made (it) palatable.\" يُسِيغُ means \"he makes (it) easy to swallow\" or \"he causes (it) to go down smoothly.\" The connection lies in facilitating ease and smoothness, reflecting the root's focus on the effortless consumption or acceptance of something. It emphasizes the act of making an experience agreeable or acceptable.",
  "4561": "يُسْجَرُونَ and related words stem from the root س-ج-ر, with the root verb سَجَرَ meaning \"he kindled,\" \"he ignited,\" or \"he filled.\" يُسْجَرُونَ is a passive form meaning \"they will be filled with fire\" or \"they will be ignited.\" The term vividly describes both the state of being consumed by fire and the role of acting as fuel for it, intensifying the flames. The root’s dimensions extend to processes of filling, overflowing, and igniting, emphasizing total engulfment and intensification. The connection lies in the vivid imagery of something being entirely consumed or overwhelmed, reflecting the severity of the consequences associated with being \"filled\" in this way.",
  "4562": "يُسْجَنَ and related words stem from the root س-ج-ن, with the root verb سَجَنَ meaning \"he imprisoned\" or \"he detained.\" يُسْجَنَ is a passive form meaning \"he is imprisoned\" or \"he will be imprisoned,\" emphasizing an ongoing or future action of being confined. The term connects to the root’s themes of restriction and justice, highlighting potential or impending consequences tied to one’s actions.",
  "4563": "يُسْحَبُ and related words stem from the root س-ح-ب, with the root verb سَحَبَ meaning \"he drew\" or \"he pulled.\" يُسْحَبُ is a passive form meaning \"he is being dragged\" or \"he will be dragged.\" The connection lies in being pulled by another force, directly relating to the root's concept. This term often connotes compulsion or punishment.",
  "4564": "يُسْحِتُ and related words stem from the root س-ح-ت, with the root verb سَحَتَ meaning \"he annihilated\" or \"he consumed.\" يُسْحِتُ means \"he annihilates\" or \"he destroys utterly.\" The connection lies in causing complete destruction, directly relating to the root's concept. This term emphasizes the severity of obliteration.",
  "4565": "يُسْرٌ and related words stem from the root ي-س-ر, with the root verb يَسَرَ meaning \"it became easy.\" The root conveys broader concepts of ease, facilitation, simplicity, and removal of difficulty, focusing on making things accessible and manageable. يُسْرٌ means \"ease\" or \"comfort,\" representing a state free from hardship or obstruction. The connection lies in embodying the root’s core emphasis on simplicity and relief, reflecting Allah's (ﷻ) mercy and compassion in facilitating ease and lightening burdens in life.",
  "4566": "يُسْرَىٰ and related words stem from the root ي-س-ر, with the root verb يَسَرَ meaning \"it became easy.\" يُسْرَىٰ means \"easier\" or \"left side,\" but in the Qur'an, it often refers to \"the path of ease,\" symbolizing a way of life aligned with divine mercy and facilitation. The root conveys broader concepts of ease, simplicity, facilitation, and comfort, emphasizing actions or paths that remove difficulty and promote smoothness.  The connection lies in the root's focus on making things achievable and accessible, highlighting Allah’s (ﷻ) guidance toward simplicity, mercy, and the removal of hardship in navigating life's challenges.",
  "4567": "يُسْمِنُ and related words stem from the root س-م-ن, with the root verb سَمُنَ meaning \"he became fat\" or \"he was well-nourished.\" يُسْمِنُ means \"it nourishes\" or \"it fattens.\" The connection lies in the act of providing nourishment that leads to growth or increased vitality. It emphasizes the process of enrichment and strengthening, whether physically or metaphorically.",
  "4568": "يُشْعِرُ and related words stem from the root ش-ع-ر, with the root verb شَعَرَ meaning \"he perceived\" or \"he became aware.\" يُشْعِرُ means \"he makes (someone) perceive\" or \"he informs.\" The connection lies in causing others to become aware, aligning with the root's concept of perception. It highlights the act of imparting knowledge or awareness to others.",
  "4569": "يُصَدَّعُونَ and related words stem from the root ص-د-ع, with the root verb صَدَّعَ meaning \"he caused to split\" or \"he afflicted with headache.\" يُصَدَّعُونَ is a passive form meaning \"he is afflicted\" or \"he is caused to have a headache.\" The connection lies in the root's association with splitting, extended metaphorically to the splitting pain of a headache. In the Qur'an, it is used to describe the state of bliss in Paradise where inhabitants will not be afflicted by headaches or discomfort, highlighting the absence of any pain or distress.",
  "4570": "يُصَلَّبُوا and related words stem from the root ص-ل-ب, with the root verb صَلَبَ meaning \"he crucified.\" يُصَلَّبُوا is a passive form meaning \"they be crucified.\" The connection lies in being subjected to the act of crucifixion, reflecting the root's focus on hardness, affliction, and the extreme nature of this punishment. It also conveys the notion of being fixed or fastened, illustrating a state of enduring suffering. In the Qur'an, it is mentioned as part of the punishment for those who wage war against Allah (ﷻ) and His Messenger (ﷺ), signifying the severity of crimes that disrupt social order and security.",
  "4571": "يُصْحَبُونَ and related words stem from the root ص-ح-ب, with the root verb صَحِبَ meaning \"he accompanied\" or \"he befriended.\" يُصْحَبُونَ is the passive form, meaning \"they are accompanied\" or \"they are befriended.\" The connection lies in the root's concept of companionship, focusing on the experience of being the one who is accompanied. This highlights the reciprocal nature of relationships and the importance of surrounding oneself with righteous company, emphasizing the value of companionship and protection.",
  "4572": "يُصْدِرَ and related words stem from the root ص-د-ر, with the root verb صَدَرَ meaning \"he came forth.\" يُصْدِرَ means \"he drives out\" or \"he sends away.\" The connection lies in the action of causing something or someone to depart or move away. It emphasizes the role of making something leave or move from one place to another, particularly in the context of driving livestock or managing movement.",
  "4573": "يُصْهَرُ and related words stem from the root ص-ه-ر, with the root verb صَهَرَ meaning \"he melted\" or \"he smelted.\" يُصْهَرُ is a passive form meaning \"it is melted\" or \"they are being smelted,\" reflecting the process of being subjected to intense heat until substances liquefy or fuse. The connection lies in the transformation through heat, signifying a change of state or form, often associated with refining or purifying. This term conveys the idea of being melted or softened under pressure, symbolizing purification or intense transformation.",
  "4574": "يُضَارَّ and related words stem from the root ض-ر-ر, with the root verb ضَرَّ meaning \"he harmed\" or \"he injured.\" يُضَارَّ can be read as both active (\"he harms\") and passive (\"he is harmed\"), reflecting dual meanings. The connection lies in highlighting the root's concept of harm from both perspectives—inflicting and receiving injury. This term emphasizes the importance of avoiding harm in all forms, aligning with Allah's (ﷻ) commands and striving to please Him.",
  "4575": "يُضَاعِفُ and related words stem from the root ض-ع-ف, with the root verb ضَعُفَ meaning \"he became weak\" or \"he weakened.\" يُضَاعِفُ means \"he multiplies\" or \"he doubles.\" The connection lies in the action of increasing or amplifying something, particularly in contexts where insufficiency or smallness is transformed into abundance. This word often appears in reference to Allah's (ﷻ) mercy, where good deeds or efforts—though small—are multiplied many times over, far beyond their original measure. It reflects themes of divine generosity, reward, and the limitless potential for growth and compensation.",
  "4576": "يُضَاهِئُونَ and related words stem from the root ض-ه-أ, with the root verb ضَاهَأَ meaning \"he resembled\" or \"he imitated.\" يُضَاهِئُونَ means \"they resemble\" or \"they imitate closely.\" The connection lies in mimicking or matching something else, often implying rivalry or challenge. This term reflects an effort to imitate so closely that it seeks to surpass the original. It also serves as a cautionary note, especially in Islamic teachings, against imitating falsehood or misguidance. The idea of imitation here emphasizes the risks of blindly following beliefs or practices without understanding or truth.",
  "4577": "يُضَيِّقُونَ and related words stem from the root ض-ي-ف, with the root verb ضَافَ meaning \"he became a guest\" or \"he added.\" ضَيَّفَ means \"he entertained as a guest\" or \"he hosted.\" يُضَيِّقُونَ means \"they host\" or \"they entertain.\" The connection lies in the active role of bringing guests into one's home, directly reflecting the root's concept of addition and hospitality. This term emphasizes the act of hosting and the importance of generosity, fostering community and strengthening social bonds.",
  "4578": "يُطَاعُ and related words stem from the root ط-و-ع, with the root verb طَاعَ meaning \"he obeyed\" or \"he complied willingly.\" يُطَاعُ is a passive form meaning \"he is obeyed.\" It indicates that someone is being obeyed or followed by others. The connection to the root emphasizes the ongoing state of being the recipient of obedience. In a spiritual or authoritative context, it highlights the recognition and respect accorded to one who commands obedience.",
  "4579": "يُطَوَّقُونَ and related words stem from the root ط-و-ق, with the root verb طَاقَ meaning \"he was able to bear,\" or \"he could endure,\" and طَوَّقَ meaning \"he encircled\" or \"he burdened.\" يُطَوَّقُونَ is a passive form meaning \"they are encircled\" or \"they are burdened.\" This word conveys the idea of being surrounded or laden with something. The connection to the root emphasizes the state of being encompassed or bearing a burden. In moral contexts, it may refer to the consequences or responsibilities that envelop a person due to their actions.",
  "4580": "يُطِيقُونَ and related words stem from the root ط-و-ق, with the root verb طَاقَ meaning \"he was able to bear\" or \"he could endure.\" يُطِيقُونَ means \"they are able\" or \"they can endure.\" It denotes the capacity to handle or withstand something. The connection to the root highlights one's ability to encompass or bear burdens. In a spiritual sense, it highlights human limitations and the reliance on Allah's (ﷻ) mercy, reminding that obligations are assigned according to one's capacity.",
  "4581": "يُطْلِعَ and related words stem from the root ط-ل-ع, with the root verb طَلَعَ meaning \"he rose\" or \"he emerged.\" أَطْلَعَ means \"he informed\" or \"he revealed.\" يُطْلِعَ means \"he informs\" or \"he reveals,\" emphasizing the act of making something known. The connection lies in causing information to emerge, directly reflecting the root's concept of appearance. This term highlights the process of disclosure and enlightenment.",
  "4582": "يُعَظِّمْ and related words stem from the root ع-ظ-م, with the root verb عَظُمَ meaning \"he was great.\" يُعَظِّمُ means \"he magnifies,\" \"he exalts,\" or \"he honors.\" The connection lies in the act of elevating something or someone in status or esteem, reflecting the root's emphasis on greatness. This term highlights the actions of honoring, venerating, or considering something as significant and worthy of respect.",
  "4583": "يُعَقِّبْ and related words stem from the root ع-ق-ب, with the root verb عَقِبَ meaning \"he followed\" or \"he came after.\" يُعَقِّبْ is an intensified form meaning \"he follows up\" or \"he pursues continuously.\" This conveys the idea of repeated or deliberate following, whether physically, in actions, or in consequences. The root extends to themes of succession, continuity, and the cyclical nature of actions and their outcomes, emphasizing persistence and the interconnectedness of events or efforts.",
  "4584": "يُعَمَّرُ and related words stem from the root ع-م-ر, with the root verb عَمَرَ meaning \"he lived long,\" \"he inhabited,\" or \"he enriched.\" يُعَمَّرُ is a passive form meaning \"he is granted long life\" or \"he is made to live long.\" The connection is in receiving the gift of extended life, reflecting the root's emphasis on longevity as an opportunity to continue inhabiting and enriching the earth. It highlights the notion that long life is both a blessing and a responsibility to persist in good deeds and positive contributions.",
  "4585": "يُعْجِزُونَ and related words stem from the root ع-ج-ز, with the root verb عَجَزَ meaning \"he was weak,\" \"he failed,\" or \"he was unable.\" يُعْجِزُونَ means \"they seek to cause failure\" or \"they strive to incapacitate,\" emphasizing an active effort to render someone or something ineffective or unable to achieve success. The connection lies in the root's concept of weakness or inability, with this form focusing on the deliberate attempt to impose such a state on others, highlighting themes of obstruction and opposition.",
  "4586": "يُعْظِمْ and related words stem from the root ع-ظ-م, with the root verb عَظُمَ meaning \"he was great.\" يُعْظِمُ means \"he grants greatly\" or \"he makes great.\" The connection lies in the act of increasing in greatness or bestowing abundance, reflecting the root's emphasis on magnitude. This term signifies the action of causing something to become great or significant, often through generous bestowal or enhancement.",
  "4587": "يُغَاثُ and related words stem from the root غ-ي-ث, with the root verb غَاثَ meaning \"he aided\" or \"he relieved.\" يُغَاثُ is a passive form meaning \"he/they are helped\" or \"are given relief,\" emphasizing receiving aid. The connection lies in being the beneficiary of assistance, reflecting the root's concept of relief being granted, often in times of distress.",
  "4588": "يُغَادِرُ and related words stem from the root غ-د-ر, with the root verb غَدَرَ meaning \"he betrayed,\" \"he acted treacherously,\" or \"he abandoned.\" يُغَادِرُ means \"he departs,\" \"he leaves behind,\" or \"he forsakes.\" The connection lies in the act of leaving or abandoning, often with an implication of betrayal, reflecting the root's emphasis on treachery and desertion. This term highlights the actions of forsaking commitments or responsibilities, emphasizing the moral consequences of betrayal.",
  "4589": "يُغَيِّرُ and related words stem from the root غ-ي-ر, with the root verb غَارَ meaning \"he brought provision,\" \"he benefited,\" \"he bestowed something good,\" \"he was jealous,\" or \"he was protective.\" The derived root verb غَيَّرَ expands upon this with meanings of \"altering\" or \"changing something.\" يُغَيِّرُ means \"he changes\" or \"he alters,\" focusing on the act of actively causing change in something external. This reflects the root's association with intentionality, action, and influence, tying the concept of change to purposeful acts rooted in benefit or protection.",
  "4590": "يُفَتَّرُ and related words stem from the root ف-ت-ر, with the root verb فَتَرَ meaning \"he slackened\" or \"he became inactive.\" يُفَتَّرُ means \"it is lessened\" or \"it is slackened,\" emphasizing reduction by external means. The connection lies in something being diminished, reflecting the root's concept of slackening. It highlights how external factors can decrease intensity or vigor.",
  "4591": "يُفْتِي and related words stem from the root ف-ت-ي, with the root verb فَتِيَ meaning \"he became a youth\" or \"he was youthful and strong,\" also encompassing \"he provided an answer\" or \"gave a legal decision.\" يُفْتِي means \"he gives a legal opinion\" or \"he issues a fatwa.\" The connection lies in imparting wisdom and guidance, paralleling the clarity and vigor associated with youthfulness. This term embodies the root's focus on disseminating knowledge and resolving uncertainties, highlighting the role of one who provides authoritative guidance.",
  "4592": "يُقَلِّلُ and related words stem from the root ق-ل-ل, with the root verb قَلَّ meaning \"it was little\" or \"it decreased.\" قَلَّلَ means \"he reduced\" or \"he made something small.\" يُقَلِّلُ means \"he reduces\" or \"he diminishes.\" This reflects the root's concept of causing something to become less or smaller.",
  "4593": "يُقْصِرُونَ and related words stem from the root ق-ص-ر, with the root verb قَصَرَ meaning \"he confined,\" \"he shortened,\" or \"he limited.\" يُقْصِرُونَ means \"they refrain\" or \"they desist.\" The connection lies in the act of holding back or abstaining from certain actions, highlighting self-control and the conscious decision to avoid prohibited or harmful behaviors. This term highlights the importance of ethical conduct and the deliberate choice to limit oneself to what is permissible, promoting discipline and moral integrity.",
  "4594": "يُكَلِّفُ and related words stem from the root ك-ل-ف, with the root verbs كَلِفَ, meaning \"he was burdened\" or \"he was passionately attached,\" and كَـلَّفَ, meaning \"he imposed a burden\" or \"he tasked.\" يُكَلِّفُ means \"he burdens\" or \"he imposes a task upon,\" emphasizing the act of placing responsibility or obligation on someone. The connection lies in the weight of the duty assigned, directly relating to the root's concept of hardship and emotional investment. This term not only reflects the physical or practical burden but also hints at the deeper emotional commitment and involvement that can accompany such responsibilities, highlighting the comprehensive impact of obligation.",
  "4595": "يُلاقُوا and related words stem from the root ل-ق-ي, with the root verb لَقِيَ meaning \"he met,\" \"he encountered,\" or \"he found,\" describing the act of coming face to face with someone or something. يُلاقُوا means \"they meet,\" referring to the act of encountering or coming into direct contact. The root conveys themes of meeting, confronting, or finding, whether in physical, emotional, or metaphorical contexts. يُلاقُوا emphasizes the act of engagement or interaction, highlighting the significance of encounters, whether with people, challenges, or outcomes, reflecting the root's focus on direct and impactful engagements.",
  "4596": "يُلْحِدُونَ and related words stem from the root ل-ح-د, with the root verb لَحَدَ meaning \"he deviated,\" \"he turned aside,\" or \"he inclined away.\" يُلْحِدُ means \"he deviates\" or \"he falsely attributes,\" emphasizing deliberate actions of turning away from truth or correctness. This term highlights both the act of veering from the right path and misrepresenting or distorting truth, aligning with the root’s dimensions of inclining and deviation in both physical and metaphorical senses.",
  "4597": "يُمَسِّكُونَ and related words stem from the root م-س-ك, with the root verb مَسَكَ meaning \"he held,\" \"he grasped,\" or \"he seized.\" يُمَسِّكُونَ means \"they hold firmly\" or \"they adhere firmly,\" emphasizing the act of maintaining a strong grip or steadfast commitment. This reflects the root’s concept of securing or fastening, symbolizing determination and adherence. The term conveys themes of persistence and resolve, often applied metaphorically to describe firm adherence to principles or teachings, as seen in the context of holding firmly to the Book, highlighting a sense of unwavering commitment and devotion.",
  "4598": "يُمَنِّي stems from the root م-ن-ي, with the root verb مَنَى meaning \"to wish,\" \"to desire,\" or \"to hope.\" يُمَنِّي means \"he makes (someone) wish\" or \"he fills (someone) with false hopes.\" This form intensifies the action, indicating the act of instilling desires or aspirations in another, often without basis. The root also conveys meanings like \"to measure\" and \"to determine,\" reflecting the setting of expectations or goals. In the Qur'an, يُمَنِّي describes how false promises or deceptive hopes are instilled by Satan, leading individuals away from truth and righteousness. It highlights caution against being misled by baseless desires and emphasizes grounding hopes in reality and divine guidance.",
  "4599": "يُمِلُّ and related words stem from the root م-ل-ل, with the root verb مَلَّ meaning \"he repeated\" or \"he dictated.\" يُمِلُّ means \"he dictates,\" emphasizing the act of conveying words for writing with precision and clarity. The connection lies in the root's focus on repetition and deliberate transmission, ensuring accuracy and consistency in preserving knowledge. This term highlights the careful process of communication, emphasizing the importance of maintaining reliability and trustworthiness in recorded information.",
  "4600": "يُمْنَىٰ stems from the root م-ن-ي, with the root verb مَنَى meaning \"to decree,\" \"to ordain,\" or \"to destine.\" يُمْنَىٰ is the passive form, meaning \"is emitted\" or \"is destined,\" often referring to the emission of seminal fluid in creation. The root also conveys meanings like \"to measure\" and \"to set a fate,\" reflecting divine predestination. The term relates to مَنِيَّة, meaning \"death\" or \"fate,\" emphasizing the cyclical nature of life and Allah’s (ﷻ) meticulous decree. يُمْنَىٰ thus connects the physical act of creation with the profound concept of destiny and purpose in existence.",
  "4601": "يُنَازِعُنَّ and related words stem from the root ن-ز-ع, with the root verb نَزَعَ meaning \"he pulled out\" or \"he extracted.\" يُنَازِعُنَّ means \"they dispute\" or \"they contend,\" signifying an ongoing action of conflict or struggle. The root suggests pulling or forceful exertion, and this meaning extends metaphorically to disputes as a struggle to gain or remove something. The connection lies in the image of parties pulling in opposite directions, striving to prevail over one another. يُنَازِعُنَّ embodies the root's dynamic nature, reflecting contention as a mutual and forceful effort, emphasizing the tension and exertion in conflicts.",
  "4602": "يُنْزِفُونَ and related words stem from the root ن-ز-ف, with the root verb نَزَفَ meaning \"he bled,\" \"he was exhausted,\" or \"he became depleted.\" The root broadly conveys ideas of draining, exhaustion, and emptiness, whether physically, mentally, or emotionally. يُنْزِفُونَ means \"they are exhausted\" or \"they are drained,\" reflecting a state of impairment or depletion, whether from intoxication or exhaustion. The root emphasizes diminishing vitality or capacity. In the Qur'an, it describes a state free from depletion or intoxication, contrasting human weakness with divine grace. يُنْزِفُونَ highlights the fragility of loss or impairment while reflecting the perfection and stability of divine provision.",
  "4603": "يُنْظَرُونَ and related words stem from the root ن-ظ-ر, with the root verb نَظَرَ meaning \"he looked,\" \"he observed,\" or \"he considered.\" أَنْظَرَ means \"he gave respite\" or \"he delayed,\" signifying the act of granting time or postponing an outcome. يُنْظَرُونَ is a passive form meaning \"they are given respite\" or \"they are delayed,\" indicating being granted additional time. The connection lies in the idea of extending time for reflection, decision-making, or preparation, emphasizing the root’s themes of consideration, patience, and the deliberate use of time. This highlights the balance between mercy in granting delay and the responsibility it brings for thoughtful action.",
  "4604": "يُنْفَوْا and related words stem from the root ن-ف-ي, with the root verb نَفَى meaning \"he banished\" or \"he expelled.\" يُنْفَوْا is a passive form meaning \"they are banished\" or \"they are expelled.\" The connection lies in the act of being removed or excluded from a place or community, directly relating to the root's meaning. It reflects the state of exile and separation, emphasizing the consequences of certain actions.",
  "4605": "يُنْقَصُ and related words stem from the root ن-ق-ص, with the root verb نَقَصَ meaning \"he diminished,\" and the passive form يُنْقَصُ meaning \"it is diminished\" or \"it is decreased.\" The connection lies in the ongoing process of reduction or lessening, directly relating to the root's meaning. It reflects a state where something is currently being reduced or is decreasing.",
  "4606": "يُنْكِرُ and related words stem from the root ن-ك-ر, with the root verb نَكِرَ meaning \"he found strange\" or \"he disowned.\" The root embodies concepts of unfamiliarity and denial. يُنْكِرُ means \"he denies,\" \"he disapproves,\" or \"he rejects.\" It signifies the ongoing action of disapproving or rejecting something perceived as unfamiliar or objectionable. The connection lies in the active process of denial in response to strangeness, aligning with the root's emphasis on unfamiliarity leading to disapproval.",
  "4607": "يُنَشَّأُ and related words stem from the root ن-ش-أ, with the root verb نَشَأَ meaning \"he originated,\" \"he grew,\" or \"he came into being.\" يُنَشَّأُ is a passive form meaning \"they are brought up,\" \"they are reared,\" or \"they are caused to grow.\" The root conveys themes of development, origination, and progression, emphasizing the nurturing process that enables growth and maturity. This term highlights the act of fostering or facilitating growth, reflecting the root's focus on gradual formation and cultivation.",
  "4608": "يُنْغِضُونَ and related words stem from the root ن-غ-ض, with the root verb نَغَضَ meaning \"he shook\" or \"he moved,\" particularly referring to movements of the head, such as nodding or shaking. This root conveys meanings tied to slight, deliberate motions, often used to signify refusal or emotions. يُنْغِضُونَ means \"they shake\" or \"they nod,\" typically in an up-and-down motion. This term is contextually tied to mockery or derision, where such gestures express disbelief, rejection, or disdain. The broader root themes emphasize controlled movements that communicate unspoken sentiments, reflecting how actions mirror internal attitudes, particularly in moments of denial or scorn.",
  "4609": "يُهَيِّئُ and related words stem from the root ه-ي-أ, with the root verb هَآءَ meaning \"he was of good form or appearance,\" and هَيَّأَ meaning \"he prepared\" or \"he arranged.\" يُهَيِّئُ means \"he prepares,\" \"he arranges,\" or \"he facilitates,\" reflecting the active process of making ready or setting conditions. The root emphasizes themes of preparation, readiness, and deliberate action, highlighting the dynamic effort involved in achieving a specific goal. يُهَيِّئُ conveys the ongoing nature of organizing or enabling a state of readiness, symbolizing the interplay between effort and purpose. It reflects how facilitation and preparation are key to realizing potential and ensuring success.",
  "4610": "يُهْرَعُونَ and related words stem from the root ه-ر-ع, with the root verb هَرَعَ meaning \"he hastened,\" \"he hurried,\" or \"he was urged on.\" يُهْرَعُونَ is a passive form meaning \"they are being hurried\" or \"they are being rushed.\" This term connects to the root's concept by depicting someone compelled to move quickly, due to external forces. It reflects themes of urgency and compulsion inherent in the root, emphasizing a swift response to a pressing situation.",
  "4611": "يُوَاطِئُ and related words stem from the root و-ط-أ, with the root verb وَطَأَ meaning \"he trod,\" \"he walked upon,\" or \"he laid a foundation.\" From this, the derived verb وَاطَأَ means \"he agreed with,\" \"he conformed to,\" or \"he made something correspond to another.\" يُوَاطِئُ means \"he corresponds to,\" or \"he aligns with.\" The connection to the root involves the idea of establishing mutual conformity or agreement, akin to laying a foundation for alignment. It also reflects how alignment can be misused to manipulate truth or distort conformity to serve one's desires, emphasizing the importance of integrity in agreements and actions.",
  "4612": "يُوبِقُ and related words stem from the root و-ب-ق, with the root verb وَبَقَ meaning \"he perished,\" \"he was destroyed,\" or \"he was ruined.\" يُوبِقُ means \"He destroys\" or \"He causes to perish,\" reflecting the active role of bringing about destruction or ruin. The root also conveys themes of entrapment and overwhelming calamity, emphasizing the inescapable nature of destruction when it occurs. The connection lies in the inevitability of perishing due to overwhelming forces or circumstances. In the Qur'an, it highlights Allah’s (ﷻ) justice, where destruction is not arbitrary but a consequence of transgressions, serving as a powerful reminder of the repercussions of defying Allah’s (ﷻ) guidance.",
  "4613": "يُوثِقُ and related words stem from the root و-ث-ق, with the root verb وَثَقَ meaning \"he was firm\" or \"he trusted.\" يُوثِقُ means \"he binds,\" \"he secures,\" or \"he fastens firmly.\" The connection lies in the act of making something firm or secure, directly relating to the root's emphasis on firmness. This term emphasizes the action of securing or binding, whether physically or metaphorically, such as binding a promise or securing a trust.",
  "4614": "يُوزَعُونَ and related words stem from the root و-ز-ع, with the root verb وَزَعَ meaning \"he restrained\" or \"he controlled.\" يُوزَعُونَ means \"they are being restrained\" or \"they are being controlled.\" The connection lies in the state of being regulated or held back by an external force, reflecting the root's emphasis on order and discipline. In the Qur'an, it describes groups being kept in order, such as on the Day of Judgment, highlighting divine orchestration and the organization of creation.",
  "4615": "يُوسُفُ refers to Prophet Joseph (ﷺ) and is derived from the Hebrew root י-ס-פ, meaning \"He will add\" or \"God increases.\" This meaning is reflected in his life story, where early trials—betrayal, slavery, and imprisonment—seemed like losses but were actually tests of patience. Through perseverance and faith, Allah (ﷻ) ultimately \"added\" to his status, elevating him to a position of power and blessing. Prophet Joseph's (ﷺ) journey exemplifies how trials lead to growth and divine favor, perfectly aligning with the meaning of his name.",
  "4616": "يُوصِي and related words stem from the root و-ص-ي, with the root verb وَصَّى meaning \"he enjoined\" or \"he advised earnestly.\" يُوصِي means \"he enjoins,\" \"he advises,\" or \"he makes a will.\" The connection to the root involves the ongoing action of giving important instructions or making bequests. It reflects the responsibility of advising others or setting forth one's wishes regarding matters of significance.",
  "4617": "يُوفِضُونَ and related words stem from the root و-ف-ض, with the root verb وَفَضَ meaning \"he hastened\" or \"he rushed.\" يُوفِضُونَ means \"they hasten\" or \"they rush.\" The connection lies in the swift movement towards a goal, reflecting urgency or eagerness. This emphasizes the root's concept of rapid action, highlighting moments when promptness is essential.",
  "4618": "يُوقِعَ and related words stem from the root و-ق-ع, with the root verb وَقَعَ meaning \"he fell\" or \"it occurred.\" The verb أَوْقَعَ means \"he caused to fall\" or \"he inflicted,\" and يُوقِعَ means \"he causes (an event),\" \"he inflicts,\" or \"he instigates.\" The root conveys themes of falling, occurring, or happening, while its causative form emphasizes deliberate action to trigger or initiate an event. The connection lies in actively bringing about an occurrence or effect, whether through direct causation or intentional instigation.",
  "4619": "يُوقِنُونَ and related words stem from the root ي-ق-ن, with the root verb يَقِنَ meaning \"he was certain.\" يُوقِنُونَ means \"they are certain\" or \"they attain certainty,\" highlighting a state of continuous and firm belief. The root also conveys broader concepts of stability, clarity, and unwavering conviction, emphasizing a state free from doubt. The connection lies in the enduring nature of certainty, where clarity and stability in understanding lead to unwavering conviction, embodying the root’s focus on steadfastness and persistence in belief.",
  "4620": "يُولِجُ and related words stem from the root و-ل-ج, with the root verb وَلَجَ meaning \"he or it entered.\" يُولِجُ means \"He causes to enter,\" emphasizing an active, causative role. The root conveys themes of entry, transition, and passage, whether physical or metaphorical. يُولِجُ reflects the facilitation of transitions, symbolizing the seamless movement or integration of one thing into another, aligning with the broader concept of connecting and interweaving elements.",
  "4621": "يُونُسُ refers to Prophet Jonah (ﷺ), written as יוֹנָה in Hebrew, meaning \"dove.\" The dove is generally viewed as a symbol of peace, which mirrors Prophet Jonah's (ﷺ) repentance after being swallowed by a great fish. His supplication to Allah (ﷻ) led to his rescue, and upon his return, he found his people had also turned back to Allah (ﷻ), bringing peace and harmony. This story highlights Allah’s (ﷻ) mercy for those who repent and the peace that follows sincere faith and submission.",
  "4622": "The particle مَعَ is used to indicate accompaniment, association, or proximity, translating to \"with\" or \"among.\" It expresses being in the company of someone or something, whether physically or metaphorically. In the Qur'an, مَعَ is often used to convey Allah's (ﷻ) presence and support, as in \"Allah is with the patient.\" This emphasizes the notion that مَعَ not only signifies physical presence but also divine assistance, guidance, and protection, reminding believers of Allah's (ﷻ) closeness in times of trial or perseverance.",
  "4624": "آذَنَ and related words stem from the root أ-ذ-ن, with the root verb أَذِنَ meaning \"he listened\" or \"he permitted.\" آذَنَ means \"he announced,\" \"he informed,\" \"he proclaimed,\" or \"he gave permission.\" The connection lies in transitioning from receiving information through listening to actively conveying it to others, reflecting the root’s focus on communication and permission. While both verbs can mean \"to give permission,\" أَذِنَ emphasizes listening and granting consent internally, while آذَنَ focuses on publicly announcing or informing others.",
  "4625": "أَخْبَتُوا and related words stem from the root خ-ب-ت, with the root verb خَبَتَ meaning \"it (a fire) became extinguished,\" \"it subsided or became still,\" \"he became quiet or calm,\" or \"he was or became humble.\" أَخْبَتُوا means \"they humbled themselves,\" referring to the act of lowering oneself in humility before Allah (ﷻ). The connection lies in the idea of quieting and subduing the self—just as a fire dies down and becomes still, humility requires one to suppress arrogance and submit with sincerity, embodying a state of inner calm and reverence.",
  "4626": "أَذَلٌّ and related words stem from the root ذ-ل-ل, with the root verb ذَلَّ meaning \"he was lowly, humbled, or became submissive.\" أَذَلٌّ means \"most humiliated\" or \"more abject.\" The connection lies in intensifying the state of humility or submission indicated by the root, portraying a condition of extreme debasement or subjugation. ",
  "4627": "أَسْبَاطٌ and related words stem from the root س-ب-ط, which relates to spreading or extending. أَسْبَاطٌ means \"tribes,\" specifically referring to the tribes descended from the twelve sons of Prophet Jacob (ﷺ). The connection lies in the spreading out and multiplication of a family lineage, embodying the root's concept of extension. أَسْبَاطٌ signifies the growth of a community and the bonds that unite them.",
  "4628": "أَسْلَفَتْ and related words stem from the root س-ل-ف, with the root verb سَلَفَ meaning \"he preceded,\" \"he passed,\" or \"he went before.\" أَسْلَفَتْ means \"she sent forth,\" \"she did beforehand,\" or \"she has done in the past.\" The connection lies in the act of sending something ahead or performing deeds that precede one's current state, reflecting the root's concept of prior action. It emphasizes the impact of past actions on the present or future, highlighting the importance of being mindful of one's deeds and their lasting consequences.",
  "4629": "أَضَاءَ and related words stem from the root ض-و-أ, with the root verb ضَاءَ meaning \"he shone\" or \"he illuminated.\" أَضَاءَ means \"he illuminated\" or \"he lit up.\" The connection lies in the root's emphasis on light and illumination, symbolizing guidance and clarity. This term reflects the dispelling of darkness, both physically and metaphorically, signifying a transformative process that brings clarity, understanding, and enlightenment to a previously obscured or confused state. It conveys the idea of shedding light, whether on a physical object or in a deeper, spiritual sense.",
  "4630": "الْأَعْلَىٰ and related words stem from the root ع-ل-و, with the root verb عَلا meaning \"he rose\" or \"he ascended.\" الْأَعْلَىٰ means \"highest,\" \"superior,\" or \"exalted,\" denoting a state of ultimate elevation and prominence. It embodies the root's themes of height and superiority, signifying being above all others in status or rank. When referring to Allah (ﷻ), it means \"The Most High,\" emphasizing His absolute transcendence, perfection, and supreme authority over all creation. الْأَعْلَىٰ reflects Allah's (ﷻ) unparalleled greatness and complete freedom from any imperfection or limitation.",
  "4631": "أَغْرَىٰ and related words stem from the root غ-ر-و, with the root verb غَرَا meaning \"he adhered,\" \"he clung,\" or \"he stuck firmly.\" أَغْرَىٰ means \"he caused to cling,\" \"he incited,\" or \"he urged on,\" reflecting the act of instigating attachment or action. It conveys making someone fond of or attached to something, urging someone toward or against a particular action, or inciting enmity to cling between people. It can also mean setting someone in authority or dominion over others. The connection lies in the root’s emphasis on adherence and binding.",
  "4632": "أَكْثَرُوا and related words stem from the root ك-ث-ر, with the root verb كَثُرَ meaning \"it became numerous,\" \"it increased,\" or \"it multiplied.\" أَكْثَرُوا means \"they increased\" or \"they multiplied,\" emphasizing the collective or group action of causing growth in numbers or quantity. The connection to the root highlights the expansive and accumulative nature of abundance, where the focus is on the resulting magnitude produced by human or natural efforts.",
  "4633": "أَلْزَمَ and related words stem from the root ل-ز-م, with the root verb لَزِمَ meaning \"he adhered,\" \"he clinged,\" or \"he remained steadfast.\" أَلْزَمَ means \"he bound,\" \"he obligated,\" or \"he caused adherence.\" The connection lies in the act of compelling adherence or commitment, reflecting the root's emphasis on steadfastness and inevitability. This term signifies the act of binding someone to a duty, obligation, or path, highlighting the imposition of a commitment that must be upheld or adhered to firmly.",
  "4634": "أَلْهَىٰ and related words stem from the root ل-ه-و, with the root verb لَهَا meaning \"he was diverted,\" \"he was distracted,\" or \"he engaged in idle amusement.\" This root conveys concepts of diversion, amusement, and neglect resulting from distraction. أَلْهَىٰ means \"he diverted,\" \"he distracted,\" or \"he caused to neglect,\" emphasizing the act of inducing distraction in others. It is associated with circumstances where individuals are drawn away from essential duties by external influences such as wealth and worldly pursuits. It highlights how such attractions can overshadow meaningful pursuits and the remembrance of Allah (ﷻ), serving as a reminder to resist neglect caused by diversions.",
  "4635": "The particle أَم means \"or,\" used specifically to present exclusive choices, typically in questions where only one of the alternatives is expected to be true. It appears frequently in the Qur'an to invite deep reflection, urging the listener to consider and make a purposeful choice between clear options. أَم shares the root أ-م-م with the verb أَمَّ, meaning \"to direct one's course toward\" or \"to aim at.\" This root connection highlights the importance of intentional decision-making, as each choice presented by أَم calls for thoughtful reflection and a decisive commitment.",
  "4636": "أَمَةٌ and related words stem from the root أ-م-و, with the root verb آمَتْ meaning \"she became a slave.\" أَمَةٌ translates to \"female slave\" and refers to a woman in a state of servitude, contrasted with a free woman (حُرَّة). The root also implies closeness, submission, and purpose, suggesting a relationship of reliance and proximity to her master. In Islamic legal terminology, أَمَةٌ includes women taken into servitude through lineage or war. This term highlights both the specific societal role and the state of being entrusted to another’s authority.",
  "4637": "The particle أَمّا means \"as for\" and is used to introduce a specific topic or subject for emphasis. It sets the stage for detailed discussion, highlighting the significance of the subject introduced. أَمّا can introduce clauses that establish conditions or highlight contrasts. In conditional clauses, it signals that a specific condition will be discussed, while in contrastive clauses, it emphasizes the differences between two statements or situations. This helps clarify relationships and contrasts in the text, ensuring clear communication of the intended message.",
  "4638": "The particle أَنْ is commonly used in the Qur'an to connect ideas and clarify intentions or actions. It often introduces verbs that describe something intended, hoped for, or yet to happen. أَنْ can indicate purpose (\"so that\"), explanation (\"that\"), or consequence (\"in order to\"). It also plays a role in simplifying complex ideas by linking clauses smoothly, making it essential for expressing commands, supplications, and divine instructions. This small but powerful word helps convey deeper meanings and the unfolding of actions in Allah’s (ﷻ) plan.",
  "4639": "The pronoun \"أَنتَ\" is the singular masculine form of the second-person pronoun, meaning \"you,\" used to address a male directly. It is fundamental in personal communication, establishing a direct connection between the speaker and listener. أَنتَ emphasizes individual responsibility and engagement, making the communication more personal and specific.",
  "4640": "The pronoun \"أَنتُمْ\" is the plural form of the second-person masculine pronoun, meaning \"you all.\" It is used to address a group of males or a mixed-gender group. أَنْتُمْ conveys collective responsibility and action, emphasizing the communal aspects of communication. It reflects the importance of unity and shared purpose within a group.",
  "4641": "The pronoun \"أَنَا\" is the first-person singular pronoun, meaning \"I\" or \"I am.\" It is used by the speaker to refer to themselves. In the Qur'an, its usage emphasizes personal accountability and highlights the intimate relationship between the individual and Allah (ﷻ).",
  "4642": "The particle أَو translates to \"or\" and serves a broad purpose by presenting open or indefinite choices. أَو is used in both statements and questions to indicate a range of possibilities without expecting an exclusive answer. It can also provide explanations or expand on alternatives, encouraging the listener to consider various potential outcomes. In contrast to أَم, which suggests a decisive choice, this flexible \"or\" invites thoughtful consideration of different options, leaving room for multiple possibilities rather than a single conclusion.",
  "4643": "أَوَى and related words stem from the root أ-و-ي, and as the root verb, it means \"he took shelter\" or \"he sought refuge.\" This term denotes the act of seeking a place of rest, safety, or protection. The connection lies in the inclination toward a place of security, highlighting the human need for stability and comfort. The root also conveys ideas of dwelling, inclining, or being drawn to a place of solace, emphasizing the desire for a secure and stable refuge in times of need.",
  "4644": "أَوْقَدُوا and related words stem from the root و-ق-د, with the root verb وَقَدَ meaning \"it kindled\" or \"it ignited.\" أَوْقَدُوا means \"they kindled\" or \"they ignited.\" The connection lies in initiating a fire or starting something that spreads, reflecting the root's emphasis on ignition and illumination. This term can symbolize the beginning of inspiration or the spark of knowledge, as well as the onset of conflict, highlighting the profound effects that small beginnings can have.",
  "4645": "The particle أَيَّانَ means \"when\" and is used to ask about the timing of significant events with a sense of urgency or emphasis, often accompanied by skepticism or mockery. It shares the root أ-ي-ن with the verb آنَ, meaning \"its time came.\" This connection highlights أَيَّانَ as a question of timing or maturity. The verb آنَ signifies the culmination of an event, emphasizing the inevitability of time. Similarly, أَيَّانَ probes the exact moment something significant will occur.",
  "4646": "The conditional particle إِذَا means \"when\" or \"if,\" used to introduce future or hypothetical events. It sets up conditions, marks future occurrences, and emphasizes the certainty of these events. In the Qur'an, إِذَا conveys conditions, expectations, and certainties regarding future divine actions. It often precedes significant future occurrences, urging preparedness and awareness of what is to come.",
  "4647": "The particle إِذًا means \"then\" or \"in that case,\" and it is used to indicate a logical conclusion or result. In classical Arabic, it signals the consequence or outcome of a preceding statement or condition, emphasizing the reaction or result that follows a specific situation. Its usage enhances the logical flow of statements, making the relationship between actions and their outcomes clearer, particularly in conditional contexts.",
  "4648": "إِقامٌ and related words stem from the root ق-و-م, with the root verb قامَ meaning \"he stood\" or \"he rose.\" The root embodies concepts of standing upright, establishing, and maintaining. إِقامٌ means \"establishing\" or \"setting up.\" The connection lies in transforming the action of standing into firmly establishing something. It reflects the process of bringing something into a state of uprightness or stability, aligning with the root's core ideas of steadfastness and uprightness. In the context of prayer, إِقامُ الصَّلَاةِ signifies not just performing prayer, but maintaining it with discipline, consistency, and devotion, embodying spiritual steadfastness and aligning one’s life with principles of uprightness before Allah (ﷻ).",
  "4649": "The particle إِلّا serves as a conjunction meaning \"except\" or \"unless,\" commonly used to indicate exclusion or exception. It highlights what is excluded from a general statement and is often employed to create contrasts or opposites within a broader context. It can also specify exceptions to rules or conditions, and emphasize particular instances that deviate from general principles. Additionally, it plays a role in clarifying or explaining these exceptions.",
  "4650": "The compound particle إِمّا is formed from إِنْ (if) and مَا (what), and it means \"either...or\" or \"if...then.\" It is used to present two options or scenarios. For example, it can introduce a choice, such as \"either you throw, or I throw first,\" or outline two possible outcomes, like \"either success or failure.\" Additionally, إِمّا can mean \"if\" when followed by an instruction or order, e.g., \"and if you see them, then stay silent.\" As a conditional particle, it can also mean \"when,\" followed by the consequence of the condition, e.g., \"when I send you directions, whoever follows them will succeed.\"",
  "4651": "The conditional particle إِنْ means \"if.\" It introduces conditional clauses, setting the stage for cause-and-effect statements. The connection lies in its role in emphasizing choices and potential outcomes, highlighting the significance of free will and accountability in human actions. In the Qur'an, it often precedes scenarios that teach moral and ethical lessons based on conditions.",
  "4652": "The particle إِي means \"yes\" or \"indeed,\" used to strongly agree or assert something with confidence and certainty. It implies acknowledgment of truth, providing a clear answer to an inquirer or making a firm promise. إِي conveys certainty or emphasis, similar to saying \"absolutely\" or \"of course.\"",
  "4653": "اسْتَكَانُوا and related words stem from the root ك-ي-ن, with the root verb سَكَنَ meaning \"he was still\" or \"he resided.\" The root conveys notions of stillness, calmness, and remaining in place. اسْتَكَانُوا means \"they humbled themselves\" or \"they submitted.\" This form emphasizes adopting a state of stillness or calm as a sign of submission, often implying surrender or yielding in the face of greater power or adversity. The connection to the root lies in transitioning from motion or resistance to stillness and calm, reflecting a state of humility, reliance, and acknowledgment of a higher authority. This term embodies the intertwining of physical stillness with internal surrender and tranquility.",
  "4654": "اللَّهُمَّ and related words stem from the root أ-ل-ه, with the root verb أَلَهَ meaning \"he served,\" \"he worshipped,\" or \"he adored.\" اللَّهُمَّ is used to directly call upon Allah (ﷻ) in supplication, with the suffix \"مَّ\" intensifying the address, conveying deep earnestness and urgency. The root emphasizes worship, seeking refuge, and devotion, highlighting the act of turning to Allah (ﷻ) in need. When using اللَّهُمَّ, the worshiper invokes Allah (ﷻ) with all His perfect names and attributes, encompassing His majesty, mercy, and power. This reflects complete reliance on Allah (ﷻ) in all aspects of life and at all times.",
  "4655": "اِلْتَقَطَ and related words stem from the root ل-ق-ط, with the root verb لَقَطَ meaning \"he picked up,\" \"he gathered,\" or \"he collected.\" اِلْتَقَطَ means \"he picked up,\" \"he found,\" or \"he collected,\" often implying the discovery of something lost or discarded. The connection lies in the act of gathering or collecting with intent, reflecting the root's emphasis on careful selection or retrieval. This term highlights the mindful action of finding and taking hold of something, emphasizing attentiveness and perhaps the significance of the object found, as in the story of Prophet Joseph (ﷺ) being found by travelers.",
  "4656": "اِنْفَضُّوا and related words stem from the root ف-ض-ض, with the root verb فَضَّ meaning \"he broke up,\" \"he dispersed,\" or \"he scattered.\" اِنْفَضُّوا means \"they dispersed\" or \"they scattered.\" The connection lies in the act of a group breaking apart or dispersing, reflecting the root's emphasis on separation and scattering.",
  "4657": "بَاطِنٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ط-ن, with the root verb بَطَنَ meaning \"he or it was hidden, concealed, or inward.\" بَاطِنٌ means \"inner\" or \"hidden,\" referring to what is concealed or not outwardly visible, often contrasting with ظَاهِر (the apparent). ٱلْبَاطِنُ, one of Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect names, means \"The Hidden,\" signifying His knowledge and presence encompass both the unseen and the inner realities of all creation. The root conveys themes of concealment, inwardness, and depth, reminding us that Allah (ﷻ) knows our innermost thoughts and intentions. This inspires self-reflection and purification, as nothing remains hidden from Him.",
  "4658": "بَاقِينَ and related words stem from the root ب-ق-ي, with the root verb بَقِيَ meaning \"he remained,\" \"he endured,\" or \"he was left behind.\" بَاقِينَ describes \"those who remain\" or \"those who continue.\" ٱلْبَاقِي, one of Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect names, means \"The Everlasting\" or \"The Eternal,\" signifying His unchanging existence beyond time and creation. The root conveys themes of endurance, continuity, and constancy, emphasizing Allah’s (ﷻ) permanence as the ultimate, unaltered presence in contrast to the fleeting and transient nature of the world. This name serves as a reminder of reliance on Allah (ﷻ), who remains when all else fades.",
  "4659": "باقِيَةٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ق-ي, with the root verb بَقِيَ meaning \"he remained,\" \"he endured,\" or \"he stayed behind.\" باقِيَةٌ refers to \"something that remains,\" \"a remnant,\" or \"something that continues,\" emphasizing endurance or what is left as a lasting trace. The root conveys themes of continuity, resilience, and preservation, highlighting how remnants or enduring aspects serve as signs or reminders of significance, embodying the idea of persistence through time.",
  "4660": "بَعِيرٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ع-ر, with the root verb بَعَرَ meaning \"he evacuated the dung\" or \"he released waste.\" بَعِيرٌ refers to a camel, particularly in its role as a beast of burden. In the Qur'an, it is mentioned in the context of goods valued by a camel’s load, symbolizing provision and sustenance. The root conveys themes of release, burden, and utility, connecting the camel’s role in carrying loads and providing for livelihoods to its natural cycle of nourishing the earth, highlighting its essential place in sustaining life and commerce.",
  "4661": "The particle بَلْ is used to indicate a transition or correction, often translated as \"rather\" or \"nay.\" It negates what precedes it and affirms what follows, refining statements and guiding the listener toward a more precise understanding. In the Qur'an, بَلْ frequently corrects misconceptions or emphasizes deeper truths, drawing attention to the intended message.",
  "4662": "The affirmative particle بَلَى means \"yes indeed\" or \"certainly.\" It is used to strongly affirm a fact or truth, often following a negative or question. In the Qur'an, بَلَى is employed to confirm belief or acknowledge a reality after a statement of denial or doubt, reinforcing certainty and conviction in the message being conveyed. It serves to remove any ambiguity, emphasizing the truth with clarity and finality.",
  "4663": "بُدْنٌ and related words stem from the root ب-د-ن, with the root verb بَدُنَ meaning \"he became stout\" or \"he became heavy in body,\" often implying physical strength or robustness. بُدْنٌ refers specifically to sacrificial animals, especially large ones like camels, used in religious rituals. This term emphasizes animals of substantial physical presence, aligning with the root’s focus on strength, size, and corporeal form, which make these animals particularly suitable for offerings.",
  "4664": "تَابُوتُ and related words stem from the root ت-ب-ت, with the root verb تَابَ meaning \"he repented\" or \"he returned.\" تَابُوتُ means \"chest,\" specifically referring to the Sacred Chest given to the Children of Israel, renowned for its religious significance. The connection to the root lies in the notions of returning or preserving something precious. This chest symbolized a return to Allah's (ﷻ) guidance, containing important religious relics from the family of Prophet Moses (ﷺ) and Prophet Aaron (ﷺ). It served as a sign of divine assurance and a source of peace for the Children of Israel, representing both a physical vessel and a profound spiritual return to faith.",
  "4665": "تَبَرُّوا and related words stem from the root ب-ر-ر, with the root verb بَرَّ meaning \"he was devoted\" or \"he was kind.\" تَبَرُّوا translates as \"you act kindly\" or \"you show piety.\" This verb emphasizes the intentional act of displaying goodness, compassion, and devotion, often with a sense of fulfilling moral or social duties. This root conveys themes of consistent righteousness, loyalty, and faithfulness, particularly in relationships and obligations, suggesting that تَبَرُّوا reflects an active commitment to kindness and integrity in one's actions.",
  "4666": "تَحَاوُرٌ and related words stem from the root ح-و-ر, with the root verb حَارَ meaning \"he returned or reverted,\" or \"it fluctuated.\" حَاوَرَ means \"he conversed\" or \"he engaged in dialogue,\" and تَحَاوُرٌ refers to \"conversation\" or \"dialogue.\" The root conveys the ideas of reversion, alteration, and purification, often linked to cycles, change, or clarity. Dialogue itself embodies this process—ideas are exchanged, challenged, and refined, creating a dynamic interaction that leads to clarity and transformation in understanding.",
  "4667": "تَظَاهَرُوا and related words stem from the root ظ-ه-ر, with the root verb ظَهَرَ meaning \"he appeared\" or \"he became manifest.\" تَظَاهَرُوا means \"they supported each other\" or \"they collaborated.\" The connection lies in mutual backing, reflecting the root's concept of support (as the back supports the body). This term emphasizes cooperation and alliance, highlighting the strength found in unity.",
  "4668": "تَعْضُلُوا and related words stem from the root ع-ض-ل, with the root verb عَضَلَ meaning \"he hindered,\" \"he obstructed,\" or \"he prevented.\" تَعْضُلُوا means \"you hinder\" or \"you prevent.\" The connection lies in the act of imposing difficulties or obstacles, reflecting the root's emphasis on prevention and restriction. This term is often used in contexts where someone unjustly prevents another from exercising their rights, highlighting issues of oppression and injustice.",
  "4669": "تَقَوَّلَ and related words also stem from ق-و-ل, with the root verb قَالَ meaning \"he said\" or \"he spoke.\" تَقَوَّلَ means \"he fabricated\" or \"he falsely attributed words,\" emphasizing the deliberate act of creating or assigning false statements. It intensifies the root’s concept of speech to highlight falsehood, illustrating the potential misuse of words and the root’s capacity to embody both truth and deceit in verbal expression.",
  "4670": "تَمَنَّىٰ stems from the root م-ن-ي, with the root verb مَنَى meaning \"he wished\" or \"he desired.\" تَمَنَّىٰ means \"he wished,\" or \"he apired for,\" or \"he hoped,\" signifying an act of longing or yearning for something. The root also carries meanings like \"to measure\" and \"to determine,\" suggesting that desires are not arbitrary but are often tied to measured aspirations. In some contexts, it can also mean \"to recite\" or \"to fabricate,\" adding layers of articulation and creativity to the expression of one's hopes. This term reflects the human tendency to aspire and verbalize one's deepest desires.",
  "4671": "تُبْرِئُ and related words stem from the root ب-ر-أ, with the root verb بَرَأَ meaning \"he became free from\" or \"he disassociated from.\" تُبْرِئُ means \"you restore\" or \"you recover,\" specifically referring to the act of freeing someone from illness or harm. The connection to the root lies in the concept of purification and separation, where restoring health signifies a return to a state free from defects or suffering. This term highlights themes of renewal, compassion, and mercy, reflecting the alleviation of pain and the restoration of wholeness. It also connects to Allah's (ﷻ) beautiful name, الْبَارِئُ (\"the Maker\"), as a reminder that all recovery ultimately comes from Him, the One who grants health and well-being.",
  "4672": "The particle ثُمَّ means \"then\" or \"after that,\" indicating a sequence of events with a noticeable delay or pause between them. Unlike فَ, which suggests immediate succession of actions or events, ثُمَّ introduces a progression with a time lapse, emphasizing that one event follows another but not immediately. This distinction is important in understanding the flow of events in both daily speech and Qur'anic context, where the choice between ثُمَّ and فَ can reflect different levels of urgency, causality, or sequence in narrative or instruction.",
  "4673": "جَلَّىٰ and related words stem from the root ج-ل-و, with the root verb جَلَا meaning \"he removed, uncovered, or made clear,\" and \"it became manifest or clear.\" جَلَّىٰ means \"he unveiled\" or \"he made manifest,\" emphasizing a deliberate act of bringing something hidden or obscured into clarity and visibility. The root encompasses notions of uncovering, illuminating, and making apparent, often associated with transitions from concealment to brilliance. The connection lies in the intentional action of revealing, whether through intellectual insight, spiritual enlightenment, or physical unveiling, reflecting the root's central themes of clarity and revelation.",
  "4674": "جُنُبٌ and related words stem from the root ج-ن-ب, with the root verb جَنَبَ meaning \"he placed at a distance, sent away, or turned aside.\" جُنُبٌ refers to \"one in a state of impurity\" or \"needing total ablution,\" signifying a state that necessitates temporary separation from specific acts of worship until purification. The connection lies in the idea of being set apart or distanced due to a condition that requires cleansing, reflecting themes of separation and the process of returning to a state of readiness or purity.",
  "4675": "حَالَ and related words stem from the root ح-و-ل, and as the root verb, it means \"he or it changed or transformed,\" \"he or it moved or shifted,\" or \"he or it intervened or came between.\" The root conveys themes of transformation, transition, and intervention. The connection lies in the nature of change itself—whether as a shift in state, an alteration of circumstances, or an active interposition that disrupts or redirects events.",
  "4676": "The particle حَتَّى means \"until\" or \"up to,\" indicating the end point in time, space, or condition. It marks the limit or conclusion of an action, event, or state, often suggesting gradual progression toward that endpoint. حَتَّى is used in various contexts, such as specifying when something will stop, where something ends, or the result of an action. The term highlights the progression toward completion or cessation, emphasizing the finite nature of events. In the Qur'an, حَتَّى highlights the culmination of significant moments, emphasizing key changes or the fulfillment of divine plans.",
  "4677": "خَائِنِينَ and related words stem from the root خ-و-ن, with the root verb خَانَ meaning \"he betrayed.\" The root revolves around betrayal, dishonesty, unfaithfulness, and breach of trust, conveying a failure to uphold responsibility or acting deceitfully. خَائِنِينَ means \"traitors\" or \"ones who betray,\" referring to those who violate expectations of loyalty and trust. The connection to the root highlights the severity of betrayal, where deception undermines integrity, leading to broken commitments and lost trust.",
  "4678": "خَطْبٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ط-ب, with the root verb خَطَبَ meaning \"he delivered a speech\" or \"he addressed an assembly or congregation.\" خَطْبٌ means \"affair,\" \"matter,\" or \"issue,\" usually signifying something serious or significant. The root conveys themes of formal address and important discourse. The connection lies in how serious matters often require attention, discussion, or resolution, highlighting the weight and impact of significant events or concerns on individuals and communities.",
  "4679": "خَوَّلَ and related words stem from the root خ-و-ل, with the root verb خَوَّلَ meaning \"he ruled or governed\" or \"he managed or administered.\" The root revolves around bestowal, provision, stewardship, and privilege, conveying the idea of granting wealth, dependents, or responsibility as a favor or trust. خَوَّلَ means \"he conferred favor, granted, or bestowed a blessing or privilege,\" emphasizing the act of entrusting someone with resources, authority, or responsibility. The connection to the root highlights the theme of delegated care, where what is given is not merely a possession but a trust that carries duty and accountability.",
  "4680": "خُفْيَةً and related words stem from the root خ-ف-ي, with the root verb خَفِيَ meaning \"he or it was hidden or concealed\" or \"he or it became unapparent.\" خُفْيَةً means \"secretly\" or \"in secret,\" emphasizing actions done quietly, away from observation, or without drawing attention. The root reflects broader dimensions of concealment, subtlety, and discretion, encompassing both the physical act of hiding and the metaphorical sense of keeping intentions or actions private. It highlights themes of humility, sincerity, and caution, often associated with doing things for the sake of Allah (ﷻ) rather than for outward display.",
  "4681": "دَعْوَىٰ and related words stem from the root د-ع-و, with the root verb دَعَا meaning \"he called or invited\" or \"he supplicated or prayed.\" دَعْوَىٰ means \"supplication,\" \"cry,\" \"call,\" or \"plea,\" depending on the context, emphasizing an appeal or declaration. The root revolves around calling, summoning, requesting, naming, and invoking, conveying the ideas of communication and urging toward something. Just as a call is made to seek attention or support, this word reflects an expression of need, assertion, or appeal, whether in supplication, proclamation, or a legal claim.",
  "4682": "ذُلِّلَتْ and related words stem from the root ذ-ل-ل, with the root verb ذَلَّ meaning \"he was lowly, humbled, or became submissive.\" ذُلِّلَتْ means \"it was made easy,\" \"it was subdued,\" or \"it was humbled.\" This reflects the action of something being brought into a state of ease or submission without specifying the doer, directly connecting to the root's emphasis on being made tractable. This term underscores that challenges can be overcome when they are subdued or simplified, often alluding to divine intervention in easing difficulties.",
  "4683": "رابِعٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ب-ع, with the root verb رَبَعَ meaning \"he became four\" or \"it became quadruple.\" رابِعٌ means \"fourth.\"",
  "4684": "رَاغَ and related words stem from the root ر-و-غ, with the root verb رَاغَ meaning \"he moved stealthily,\" \"he slipped away,\" or \"he snuck away.\" This verb conveys the idea of subtlety and evasion, often implying a desire to avoid detection or to move quietly, either physically or metaphorically. The connection highlights the act of slipping away from something, evading notice or control, and often carries connotations of deliberate action to avoid responsibility or confrontation. This sense of stealthy movement reflects a deeper symbolism of avoiding unwanted situations or escaping from undesirable circumstances, emphasizing both physical and figurative elusiveness.",
  "4685": "رَبَطْنَا and related words stem from the root ر-ب-ط, with the root verb رَبَطَ meaning \"he tied\" or \"he bound.\" رَبَطْنَا means \"We made firm,\" or \"We strengthened,\" symbolizing the act of securing or strengthening something, such as faith, commitments, or relationships, emphasizing the importance of maintaining stability. It reflects the idea of fortifying oneself internally, particularly in times of difficulty, such as when Allah (ﷻ) strengthens the hearts of believers. The root suggests not just physical binding but also mental or spiritual resilience, highlighting the need for endurance and firmness in both belief and action.",
  "4686": "رَبْوَةٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ب-و, with the root verb رَبَا meaning \"it increased\" or \"it rose.\" رَبْوَةٌ means \"a high ground\" or \"an elevated land.\" The connection lies in elevation and prominence, reflecting the root's emphasis on rising. This term often signifies a place of refuge or vantage, symbolizing safety, clarity, and spiritual elevation, as seen in its Qur'anic use describing a protected dwelling.",
  "4687": "رَتِّلْ and related words stem from the root ر-ت-ل, with the root verb رَتَلَ meaning \"he arranged\" or \"he recited distinctly.\" رَتِّلْ means \"recite distinctly.\" The connection lies in commanding the act of careful, orderly recitation, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on clarity and arrangement. This term emphasizes the importance of deliberate articulation in conveying meaning and facilitating reflection upon sacred texts.",
  "4688": "رَدَّ and related words stem from the root ر-د-د and is the root verb meaning \"he returned,\" \"he repelled,\" or \"he rejected.\" This verb embodies the action of sending something back, refusing, or causing it to return to its origin. The connection lies in the root's fundamental concept of returning or rejecting, highlighting the importance of discernment and the consequences of acceptance or refusal in various contexts.",
  "4689": "رَضَاعَةٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ض-ع, with the root verb رَضَعَ meaning \"he suckled\" or \"he nursed from the breast.\" رَضَاعَةٌ means \"breastfeeding\" or \"nursing.\" The connection lies in the act of providing essential nourishment and care during infancy, directly relating to the root's emphasis on feeding and nurturing. This term embodies the intimate bond between mother and child, highlighting the importance of sustenance and growth that begins with breastfeeding, reflecting the root's core concept of nurturing life.",
  "4690": "رَيْحانٌ and related words stem from the root ر-و-ح, with the root verb رَاحَ meaning \"he found rest\" or \"he was comforted.\" رَيْحانٌ refers to \"sweet basil\" or \"fragrant plants\" and also conveys the meaning of \"bounty\" or \"blessing.\" The connection lies in the root’s focus on rest and comfort, as fragrance and blessings bring tranquility and ease. Just as the wind carries scents, the blessings or bounty spread naturally, bringing comfort and relief, mirroring the root verb’s connotation of peace and solace. The word reflects the spreading of goodness and divine favor.",
  "4691": "زَجْرَةٌ and related words stem from the root ز-ج-ر, with the verb زَجَرَ meaning \"he rebuked,\" \"he restrained,\" or \"he admonished.\" زَجْرَةٌ specifically refers to \"a blast\" or \"a single cry,\" often described as a powerful sound, such as the one signaling the Day of Resurrection. The root conveys force, authority, and decisive intervention, which is reflected in زَجْرَةٌ as a commanding and overwhelming sound that captures attention and prompts a response. This connection highlights the root’s emphasis on stern admonition and the power of a decisive act to correct or awaken.",
  "4692": "زَيْتُونٌ and related words stem from the root ز-ي-ت, relating to oil and its sources. زَيْتُونٌ means \"olive,\" referring to both the tree and its fruit. The connection lies in the olive being the source of oil, embodying the root's concept of producing something beneficial. زَيْتُونٌ symbolizes peace, blessings, and sustenance, and in the Qur'an, it is mentioned as a blessed tree, reflecting enlightenment and spiritual nourishment.",
  "4693": "سَافِلٌ and related words stem from the root س-ف-ل, with the root verb سَفَلَ meaning \"he was low\" or \"he was beneath.\" سَافِلٌ means \"low,\" \"base,\" or \"inferior.\" The connection lies in describing something or someone of low status or position, directly relating to the root's emphasis on lowness. This term can denote physical lowness or moral baseness, highlighting a state that is opposite of exalted or noble, and serves as a caution against degrading oneself through unethical actions.",
  "4694": "سَحَرٌ and related words stem from the root س-ح-ر, with the root verb سَحَرَ meaning \"he bewitched\" or \"he practiced magic.\" However, سَحَرٌ refers to \"the last part of the night,\" just before dawn. The connection between the root and the word lies in the mysterious and subtle nature of both magic and the pre-dawn hours. This time is considered spiritually significant in Islamic tradition, a moment for deep reflection and prayer, much like how magic captivates and draws one's attention to the unseen.",
  "4695": "سَلَمٌ and related words stem from the root س-ل-م, with the root verb سَلِمَ meaning \"he was safe,\" \"he was sound,\" or \"he was unharmed.\" سَلَمٌ means \"peace\" or, in some contexts, \"submitting.\" The connection lies in the harmonious state achieved through submission, reflecting the root's dimensions of safety, security, and well-being. It embodies the ideals of surrendering to higher principles to achieve inner and outer tranquility. This term emphasizes that true peace is found in yielding to Allah’s (ﷻ) guidance, fostering a state of balance and protection that transcends mere physical safety.",
  "4696": "سَوِيٌّ and related words stem from the root س-و-ي, with the root verb سَوَّىٰ meaning \"he made equal,\" \"he balanced,\" or \"he completed.\" سَوِيٌّ means \"sound,\" \"whole,\" \"balanced,\" or \"properly proportioned,\" describing someone or something in a perfect state of harmony. The root conveys themes of completeness, equilibrium, and proper proportion, extending to physical, mental, and moral aspects. سَوِيٌّ reflects the idea of being free from defect or imbalance, embodying perfection and congruity in all dimensions.",
  "4697": "The particle سَوْفَ is used to indicate the future tense, meaning \"will\" or \"shall.\" It signifies actions that will take place in the distant future, as opposed to سَ, which indicates the near future. While سَوْفَ does not specify an exact time frame, it implies a sense of delay or eventuality. In the Qur'an, سَوْفَ emphasizes the certainty of future events, such as rewards for the righteous or consequences for the transgressors, highlighting that everything will unfold according to Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect timing and decree. Its use serves as a reminder of Allah’s ultimate control over time, assuring believers of the fulfillment of His promises and warnings, even if they are not immediate.",
  "4698": "سُلَّمٌ and related words stem from the root س-ل-م, with the root verb سَلِمَ meaning \"he was safe,\" \"he was sound,\" or \"he was unharmed.\" سُلَّمٌ means \"ladder,\" \"staircase,\" or \"means of ascent.\" The connection lies in the idea of ascending safely and securely from one level to another, reflecting the root’s focus on sound progression. It symbolizes advancement and elevation—whether physically, spiritually, or intellectually—emphasizing the importance of secure and methodical steps toward growth and higher goals.",
  "4699": "سُوًى and related words stem from the root س-و-ي, with the root verb سَوَّىٰ meaning \"he made equal,\" \"he balanced,\" or \"he leveled.\" سُوًى means \"even,\" \"equal,\" or \"balanced,\" emphasizing a state of symmetry or uniformity. The root’s dimensions include balance, equality, and uniformity, often conveying impartiality or fairness. سُوًى reflects the root’s focus on creating harmony and equivalence, whether in physical spaces, relationships, or abstract concepts. In certain contexts, it can imply a shared or neutral state, highlighting the absence of imbalance or bias.",
  "4700": "سِقَايَةٌ and related words stem from the root س-ق-ي, with the root verb سَقَى meaning \"he gave to drink.\" سِقَايَةٌ means \"provision of water,\" \"watering-place,\" or \"drinking-vessel.\" The connection lies in facilitating the act of giving drink, directly relating to the root's emphasis on providing sustenance. This term refers to the responsibility of supplying water to pilgrims, or to the vessel used for drinking, indicating hospitality and service.",
  "4701": "شَفْعٌ and related words stem from the root ش-ف-ع, with the root verb شَفَعَ meaning \"he paired\" or \"he made even.\" شَفْعٌ means \"even number\" or \"pair.\" The connection lies in the root's concept of pairing or coupling, reflecting balance and completeness achieved through joining two elements.",
  "4702": "شَهْوَةٌ and related words stem from the root ش-ه-و, with the root verb شَهِيَ meaning \"he desired\" or \"he craved.\" شَهْوَةٌ means \"desire,\" \"lust,\" or \"appetite.\" The connection lies in the root's concept of intense longing. شَهْوَةٌ embodies the human inclination toward worldly pleasures and temptations. It highlights the powerful attraction of such desires and the importance of regulating them to maintain moral and spiritual integrity, as emphasized in the Qur'an.",
  "4703": "شَوَىٰ and related words stem from the root ش-و-ي, and as the root verb, it means \"he roasted\" or \"he grilled.\" This root conveys the idea of exposing something to heat, resulting in a transformation, often referring to the act of cooking or browning. In the context of نَزَّاعَةً لِلشَّوَىٰ, it also means \"the act of seeking to expose or turn something to a state of readiness\" or \"to seek the intense, fiery transformation,\" with the root symbolizing a process of refining or purification. The metaphorical implications of roasting or grilling suggest a transformative process, where what is raw is made fit for purpose or completion, often through challenge or hardship.",
  "4704": "صَرِيخٌ and related words stem from the root ص-ر-خ, with the root verb صَرَخَ meaning \"he cried out\" or \"he screamed.\" صَرِيخٌ means \"helper\" or \"responder to a cry for help.\" The connection lies in both the act of crying out and the one who responds, symbolizing someone who either calls for help in distress or comes to the aid of others in need. This term emphasizes the reciprocal nature of calling and responding, highlighting the role of assistance in times of crisis.",
  "4705": "الصَّمَدُ and related words stem from the root ص-م-د, with the root verb صَمَدَ meaning \"he betook himself\" or \"he was independent.\" الصَّمَدُ, one of Allah's (ﷻ) perfect names, means \"The Eternal,\" \"The Self-Sufficient,\" or \"The One upon whom all depend.\" The root emphasizes themes of steadfastness, independence, and self-sufficiency. This name highlights Allah's (ﷻ) perfection and freedom from need, emphasizing that all of creation is reliant upon Him for support, while He remains completely independent, eternal, and unchanging.",
  "4706": "طَرِيقٌ and related words stem from the root ط-ر-ق, with the root verb طَرَقَ meaning \"he trod\" or \"he beat a path.\" طَرِيقٌ means \"path,\" \"way,\" or \"road.\" The connection lies in the act of treading upon a place repeatedly, creating a path, directly relating to the root's emphasis on forming a way through frequent passage. This term represents a route formed by continual use, symbolizing the journey or course one takes in life. It highlights ideas of guidance and direction, emphasizing the paths we choose.",
  "4707": "طَعِمُوا and related words stem from the root ط-ع-م, with the root verb طَعِمَ meaning \"he tasted\" or \"he ate.\" طَعِمُوا means \"they ate\" or \"they consumed.\" The connection lies in the collective act of eating, directly relating to the root's emphasis on taste and nourishment. This term reflects communal aspects of eating, highlighting shared meals and the bonds formed through communal sustenance.",
  "4708": "طَلَبٌ and related words stem from the root ط-ل-ب, with the root verb طَلَبَ meaning \"he sought\" or \"he requested.\" طَلَبٌ means \"seeking,\" \"request,\" or \"pursuit,\" emphasizing the act of searching or striving for something. The connection lies in the endeavor to attain an objective, directly reflecting the root's concept of seeking. This term highlights the importance of initiative and effort in achieving one's aims.",
  "4709": "طَلْعٌ and related words stem from the root ط-ل-ع, with the root verb طَلَعَ meaning \"he rose\" or \"he emerged.\" طَلْعٌ refers to the \"spadix\" or \"blossom\" of the date-palm, representing the initial emergence of fruit. The connection lies in the first appearance of growth, directly reflecting the root's concept of emergence. This term symbolizes potential and the beginnings of fruition in nature, capturing the early stages of development and the promise of what is to come. It emphasizes the moment of first growth, marking the onset of a natural process that will eventually lead to full maturation.",
  "4710": "عَالِيًا and related words stem from the root ع-ل-و, with the root verb عَلا meaning \"he rose,\" \"he ascended,\" or \"he became elevated.\" عَالِيًا means \"high,\" \"elevated,\" or \"lofty,\" often describing something that is physically or metaphorically above others. The root embodies the concept of height or prominence, symbolizing distinction or superiority. عَالِيًا can refer to physical elevation, such as a high structure, or metaphorical greatness, highlighting how height is often associated with power, prestige, or distinction.",
  "4711": "عَدٌّ and related words stem from the root ع-د-د, with the root verb عَدَّ meaning \"he counted\" or \"he enumerated.\" عَدٌّ means \"counting\" or \"enumeration.\" The connection is straightforward, embodying the action of counting itself, directly reflecting the root's fundamental meaning.",
  "4712": "عَلانِيَةٌ and related words stem from the root ع-ل-ن, with the root verb عَلَنَ meaning \"it became manifest\" or \"it became known.\" عَلانِيَةٌ means \"openness,\" \"publicness,\" or \"in the open.\" The connection lies in the state of being public or manifest, directly relating to the root's emphasis on visibility and openness in actions or information.",
  "4713": "The particle عَنْ means \"from,\" \"about,\" or \"concerning\" and is essential for indicating separation, origin, or the subject of discussion. It conveys both literal meanings, such as movement away from a source, and abstract meanings, such as focusing on a topic or exchanging information. In the Qur'an, عَنْ highlights relationships between actions and their sources, emphasizing themes of guidance, accountability, and communication. Its usage highlights the importance of turning away from harm, focusing on beneficial matters, and conveying knowledge with clarity and precision.",
  "4714": "عَنِتُّمْ and related words stem from the root ع-ن-ت, with the root verb عَنَتَ meaning \"he suffered hardship,\" \"he was distressed,\" or \"he was brought to ruin.\" عَنِتُّمْ means \"you suffered hardship\" or \"you were distressed.\" Broader root concepts include subjugation, breaking under pressure, and falling into difficulty, often tied to physical or emotional suffering. The connection lies in the root’s emphasis on the overwhelming strain or burden one endures, reflecting the fragility of the human condition under trials.",
  "4715": "فَارَ and related words stem from the root ف-و-ر, with the root verb فَارَ meaning \"it boiled,\" \"it bubbled up,\" or \"it overflowed.\" The connection lies in the action of boiling over or erupting, symbolizing sudden outburst or emergence. This term reflects intense activity or emotion coming to the surface, emphasizing a dynamic and powerful release.",
  "4716": "فَرَقَ and related words stem from the root ف-ر-ق, and as the root verb, it means \"he separated\" or \"he divided,\" emphasizing a distinct act of making a clear distinction between entities. The root encompasses broader dimensions, including notions of differentiation, parting, or dispersing, often involving clarity. Metaphorically, it may also signify setting boundaries or establishing order by distinguishing aspects. These themes highlight physical separation and intellectual or abstract differentiation, such as distinguishing truth from falsehood. The word فَرَقَ and its derivatives carry profound implications of creating clarity or demarcation, making separation purposeful and significant in application.",
  "4717": "فَوْجٌ and related words stem from the root ف-و-ج, with the root verb فَاجَ meaning \"he came in a group\" or \"he surged.\" فَوْجٌ means \"group,\" \"company,\" or \"multitude.\" The connection lies in the movement of people en masse, reflecting the gathering or surging of a crowd. This term emphasizes collective movement or arrival, often used in contexts of groups entering or exiting together.",
  "4718": "قَبَضَ and related words stem from the root ق-ب-ض, with the root verb قَبَضَ meaning \"he grasped\" or \"he seized.\" The root conveys the action of taking hold, reflecting control, possession, or withholding. الْقَابِضُ, one of Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect names, means \"The Withholder\" or \"The Restrainer,\" signifying His authority to withhold sustenance, mercy, or blessings wisely. This name highlights Allah’s (ﷻ) ultimate control over resources and ability to withhold as a test or for a greater purpose. The connection to the root verb emphasizes the act of grasping or restraining, reminding us to trust Allah’s (ﷻ) wisdom, practice patience, and find contentment in His decree.",
  "4719": "The particle قَدْ is used to add emphasis, indicate approximation, or show that an action is complete. It is often translated as \"indeed,\" \"already,\" or \"perhaps,\" depending on the context. When placed before a verb, it adds nuances of certainty or timing, such as confirming that something has already happened or highlighting its likelihood. In the Qur'an, قَدْ reinforces the meaning of statements, affirming truths or emphasizing that events have occurred, thereby strengthening the clarity and impact of the message being conveyed.",
  "4720": "قَدِمْنَا and related words stem from the root ق-د-م, with the root verb قَدُمَ meaning \"he was ancient\" or \"he preceded.\" قَدِمْنَا means \"we came forward,\" \"we advanced,\" or \"we approached,\" emphasizing the act of moving forward or presenting oneself. The root conveys themes of precedence, advancement, and being at the forefront, whether in terms of time, position, or action. This term reflects the deliberate action of stepping forward or taking initiative, often with the intent of addressing a matter or achieving a goal. It emphasizes themes of purposeful progress and readiness, highlighting the importance of advancing with intention and foresight.",
  "4721": "قَفَّيْنَا and related words stem from the root ق-ف-و, with the root verb قَفَا meaning \"he followed\" or \"he came after.\" قَفَّيْنَا means \"We sent following\" or \"We caused to follow.\" The connection lies in the deliberate act of sending one after another in succession, reflecting the root's emphasis on orderly following or tracing. This root highlights continuity and progression, often signifying a sequence of actions or individuals aligned with a specific purpose or goal, emphasizing the importance of succession and continuity in maintaining guidance or purpose.",
  "4722": "قَلائِدُ and related words stem from the root ق-ل-د, with the root verb قَلَدَ meaning \"he hung a necklace or collar,\" \"he adorned,\" or \"he imitated.\" قَلائِدُ (plural of قِلادَةٌ) means \"garlands\" or \"collars.\" The connection lies in the act of encircling or adorning with a necklace, symbolizing dedication and marking. In the Qur'an, it refers to garlands or collars hung around the necks of sacrificial animals to designate them as offerings in the path of Allah (ﷻ). The root’s concept of encircling emphasizes commitment, identification, and the binding nature of vows or traditions.",
  "4723": "قَيَّضْنَا and related words stem from the root ق-ي-ض, with the root verb قَاضَ meaning \"he clave,\" \"he broke,\" or \"he hollowed out,\" signifying the act of carving or shaping something specific. قَيَّضَ means \"he appointed\" or \"he destined,\" while قَيَّضْنَا means \"We have appointed\" or \"We have destined.\" The connection lies in the root's focus on the act of shaping or preparing something with purpose, whether it’s a physical object or an event. This highlights the precision and care involved in the preparation and arrangement of a particular outcome, reflecting divine orchestration and the unfolding of events according to a higher plan.",
  "4724": "قُتِلُوا and related words stem from the root ق-ت-ل, with the root verb قَتَلَ meaning \"he killed.\" قُتِلُوا is a passive form meaning \"they were killed repeatedly\" or \"they were massacred.\" This form emphasizes the action of killing experienced by the subject, particularly in a recurring or intensified manner. The root concept is fully realized here in the context of severe suffering and brutality inflicted upon a group.",
  "4725": "قِطْعٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ط-ع, with the root verb قَطَعَ meaning \"he cut,\" \"he severed,\" or \"he separated.\" قِطْعٌ refers to a \"portion,\" \"piece,\" or \"segment,\" emphasizing a part that has been cut or separated from a whole. The connection lies in the deliberate act of dividing or isolating something into smaller parts, reflecting themes of separation, distinction, and fragmentation. This root highlights the idea of dividing to create manageable or distinct portions, whether in a physical, metaphorical, or conceptual sense, emphasizing the transformative power of division.",
  "4726": "The particle كَأَنَّ combines كَ (like) and أَنَّ (that), meaning \"as if\" or \"as though.\" It introduces a comparative clause, describing one situation as resembling another. In the Qur'an, كَأَنَّ is used to create vivid imagery and emphasize the intensity of experiences or conditions, allowing readers to visualize and emotionally connect with the message. Its frequent usage in classical and modern Arabic makes it a primary tool for crafting expressive comparisons.",
  "4727": "The particle كَأَنْ combines كَ (like) and أَنْ (that) and is an alternative form of كَأَنَّ, both translating to \"as if\" or \"as though.\" While both introduce comparative scenarios, كَأَنْ is less common and predominantly found in older classical texts. It is often used in formal or poetic contexts, lending an elevated tone to the narrative. Though rarer than كَأَنَّ, the particle كَأَنْ enriches the language by offering stylistic variation and subtle nuance, making it a distinctive feature in classical Arabic literature.",
  "4728": "كَسَوْا and related words stem from the root ك-س-و, with the root verb كَسَا meaning \"he clothed\" or \"he covered.\" كَسَوْا means \"they clothed\" or \"they covered,\" signifying the act of providing garments or coverings. The root emphasizes the concept of concealment and adornment, not only in a physical sense but also as an act of care and provision. Clothing is symbolically tied to notions of modesty, dignity, and protection, reflecting a deeper moral and social responsibility. In classical Arabic, the act of clothing others is often associated with generosity, nurturing, and fulfilling a basic human need, highlighting its importance in fostering compassion and community bonds.",
  "4729": "The particle كَلَّا is a strong expression of negation and admonition, meaning \"never,\" \"not at all,\" or \"by no means.\" In the Qur'an, it is used to emphatically reject false notions, reprimand wrongdoing, or assert undeniable truths. كَلَّا serves as a powerful tool to correct misconceptions, redirect attention to reality, and compel the listener to reflect and align with the truth. Its forceful tone underscores the seriousness of the message, urging a reconsideration of one’s actions or beliefs.",
  "4730": "The particle كَيْ means \"so that\" or \"in order that\" and is used to indicate purpose or result. It introduces clauses that explain the reasoning or objective behind an action, connecting actions to their intended outcomes. In the Qur'an, كَيْ is used to clarify the wisdom behind Allah’s (ﷻ) commands, highlighting the divine purpose and the benefits intended for humanity. By linking actions to their results, كَيْ deepens understanding and appreciation of Allah’s (ﷻ) guidance, encouraging reflection on the deliberate and purposeful nature of His decrees.",
  "4731": "الْكُبْرَىٰ and related words stem from the root ك-ب-ر, with the root verb كَبُرَ meaning \"he became great\" or \"he grew,\" encompassing growth, magnitude, and prominence. الْكُبْرَىٰ means \"the greatest\" or \"the supreme,\" representing the pinnacle of greatness or significance. This form highlights unmatched prominence, surpassing others in importance. It is used in contexts like الطَّامَّةُ الْكُبْرَىٰ (the Greatest Catastrophe), referring to the Day of Judgment and its unparalleled magnitude in deciding creation’s fate, and الْبَطْشَةَ الْكُبْرَىٰ (the Greatest Seizure), emphasizing the ultimate act of justice. These examples illustrate how الْكُبْرَىٰ conveys unparalleled greatness and impact, reflecting the root’s grandeur.",
  "4732": "كُرْسِيٌّ and related words stem from the root ك-ر-س, with the root verb كَـرَسَ meaning \"he accumulated\" or \"he collected.\" كُرْسِيٌّ means \"throne,\" symbolizing authority, dominion, and centrality. The connection to the root lies in the idea of accumulation, as a throne represents the gathered power, control, or knowledge of its occupant. In its most exalted sense, it signifies unparalleled authority and a manifestation of vast dominion, emphasizing the sovereignty and encompassing rule associated with it.",
  "4733": "كِلَا and related words stem from the root ك-ل-و, which conveys meanings of entirety, completeness, and inclusion. كِلَا means \"both\" or \"each of the two,\" specifically referring to two masculine entities. The connection lies in encompassing two items or individuals as a whole, directly aligning with the root's concept of totality. This term emphasizes the inclusion and consideration of both elements together in their entirety, highlighting the balance and duality inherent in the pair.",
  "4734": "The particle لَدَى means \"with,\" \"at,\" or \"in the presence of\" and is used to denote close proximity or immediate association. It often conveys a sense of nearness in physical, relational, or abstract terms. In contrast, the prepositional form لَدَيَّ adds a possessive nuance, meaning \"with me\" or \"in my presence,\" personalizing the relationship or association. In the Qur'an, لَدَى emphasizes the closeness of Allah’s (ﷻ) knowledge, authority, or presence, reinforcing the immediacy and intimacy of divine oversight and support. This distinction between لَدَى and its possessive form enhances the richness of Arabic expression, allowing for precise descriptions of relationships and proximity.",
  "4735": "The particle لَعَلَّ means \"perhaps\" or \"in hopes that,\" conveying hope, possibility, or uncertainty about a future event. It carries a sense of expectation and suggests a desired outcome. In the Qur'an, لَعَلَّ often appears in the context of giving signs, with the hope that people may be guided. This reflects Allah's (ﷻ) infinite mercy and patience, showing that He created humanity for Paradise and not for suffering. Through لَعَلَّ, Allah (ﷻ) offers opportunities for repentance and success, emphasizing His boundless mercy and His want for us to attain everlasting success.",
  "4736": "The particle لَمَّا has two primary meanings: \"when\" and \"not yet,\" depending on the context. As \"when,\" it introduces a temporal clause to specify the timing or sequence of events. As \"not yet,\" it negates a past-tense verb, indicating that an action has not occurred up to the present moment but is expected to happen. In the Qur'an, لَمَّا is used to highlight precise timing, unfolding events, or pending matters, emphasizing Allah’s (ﷻ) control over time and outcomes. Its dual functionality adds depth and clarity to the message, encouraging reflection on Allah’s (ﷻ) wisdom and the timing of events.",
  "4737": "The particle لَنْ is a negation used with the \"subjunctive\" form of the verb to indicate future tense negative, meaning \"will never.\" The subjunctive form refers to a specific way the verb is conjugated, often used to express possibility, intention, or expectation. When combined with لَنْ, it negates actions that are expected or intended to happen in the future. In the Qur'an, لَنْ emphasizes the certainty that certain events will not occur, reinforcing definitive statements about Allah's (ﷻ) decrees or human actions.",
  "4738": "The conditional particle لَوْ means \"if\" and is often used to introduce hypothetical or contrary-to-fact statements. In the Qur'an, لَوْ is employed to set up hypothetical or unreal conditions, translating to \"if,\" \"even if,\" or \"if only.\" It is used in clauses describing conditions that are contrary to reality or imagining scenarios that did not or cannot happen. Additionally, لَوْ can be used to imply a wish or desire for something that is not attainable.",
  "4739": "The particle لَوْلَا is formed from لَوْ (\"if\") and لَا (\"not\") and is used to express conditionality and negation. It means \"if not,\" \"were it not for,\" or \"why not,\" serving as a linguistic bridge between possibility and reality. لَوْلَا invites reflection on crucial factors that prevent or enable specific outcomes, often emphasizing the significance of divine intervention or human action. In the Qur'an, it introduces hypothetical scenarios to inspire self-examination, gratitude, and awareness, urging individuals to contemplate their choices and recognize Allah’s (ﷻ) blessings and warnings.",
  "4740": "The particle لَيْسَ functions as a defective verb meaning \"is not\" or \"does not exist,\" used to negate nominal sentences in Arabic, serving as a linking word for negation. It expresses non-existence or absence, making it fundamental in Arabic grammar for forming negative statements about being or existence. This highlights the concept of negation, emphasizing the absence of a state or quality. لَيْسَ plays a crucial role in communication by defining contrasts, clarifying realities, and acknowledging what does not exist, thereby shaping the understanding of existence through its negation.",
  "4741": "The particle لَٰكِنْ means \"but\" or \"however,\" used to introduce a contrast or exception to a previous statement. It serves to shift the direction of thought by highlighting differences or contradictions, creating a nuanced distinction between two ideas. In the Qur'an, لَٰكِنْ is often employed to emphasize a clarification or correction, marking a turning point in the narrative that guides the reader toward a deeper understanding of the message being conveyed.",
  "4742": "The particle لَٰكِنَّ means \"but\" or \"however,\" used to introduce a strong contrast or exception to a previous statement with added emphasis. It provides a more emphatic contrast compared to لَٰكِنْ. Here, لَٰكِنَّ connects two clauses, where the second clause sharply contrasts with or highlights an exception to the first. In the Qur'an, لَٰكِنَّ reinforces key distinctions or clarifications, emphasizing important shifts in meaning and guiding the reader toward a deeper understanding of Allah's (ﷻ) message, especially when correcting misunderstandings or presenting divine wisdom.",
  "4743": "The suffix م in ٱللَّٰهُمَّ transforms the word \"Allah\" into a form specifically used for supplication. This term directly addresses Allah (ﷻ), translating to \"O Allah.\" Traditional Islamic scholarship and linguistic analysis emphasize that ٱللَّٰهُمَّ is a profound and comprehensive way to call upon Allah (ﷻ), encompassing all His majestic and beautiful names and attributes. Its unique structure makes it a powerful and eloquent expression of direct supplication to Allah (ﷻ).",
  "4744": "The interrogative particle ماذا combines مَا (\"what\") and ذَا (\"this\"), translating to \"what?\" or \"what is that?\" It is used to introduce questions that seek to understand or inquire about something specific. In the Qur'an and classical Arabic, ماذا often appears to ask about actions, objects, or explanations. Its usage reflects a desire for clarity or further elaboration, allowing for a more focused inquiry than the standalone مَا. The particle can also be used for rhetorical questions, emphasizing curiosity or surprise in a given context.",
  "4745": "مَالِئُونَ and related words stem from the root م-ل-أ, with the root verb مَلَأَ meaning \"he filled.\" مَالِئُونَ means \"one who fills\" or \"filler,\" directly embodying the role of someone or something that provides fullness or completion. The root also implies the act of supplying or fulfilling, whether in tangible or intangible ways, such as filling a need or satisfying a requirement. This connection highlights the root’s broader dimensions of providing abundance or completeness, emphasizing the active role in creating fullness in various contexts.",
  "4746": "The interrogative particle مَتَى is used to ask questions about time, meaning \"when.\" It inquires about the timing of events, whether past, present, or future. In the Qur'an, مَتَى is often used in questions that reflect curiosity, impatience, or even skepticism, particularly regarding the Day of Judgment. Its usage highlights mankind's preoccupation with divine timing and serves as a powerful reminder of Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect wisdom in determining the precise moment for all events, encouraging both reflection and sincere preparation for what is to come.",
  "4747": "مَسْكَنَةٌ and related words stem from the root س-ك-ن, with the root verb سَكَنَ meaning \"he dwelt,\" \"he resided,\" or \"he became still.\" مَسْكَنَةٌ means \"poverty,\" \"humility,\" or \"abasement.\" The connection lies in the state of being subdued or rendered still by poverty, where one's ability to move or act is limited due to lack of resources. It reflects a sense of helplessness and vulnerability, aligning with the root's concept of stillness but highlighting the compassionate response required towards those in such a state.",
  "4748": "مَضَىٰ and related words stem from the root م-ض-ي, with the root verb meaning \"he proceeded,\" \"he passed on,\" or \"he departed.\" مَضَىٰ specifically means \"he passed\" or \"he went forth,\" emphasizing movement or transition. The root encapsulates concepts of progression, continuity, and transience, highlighting the natural flow of events or time. This sense of passage extends metaphorically to signify the completion of an era, the conclusion of a task, or the fleeting nature of existence. It also conveys determination and decisiveness, as proceeding often requires the resolve to leave something behind in pursuit of what lies ahead.",
  "4749": "مَعَاذٌ and related words stem from the root ع-و-ذ, with the root verb عَاذَ meaning \"he sought refuge.\" مَعَاذٌ means \"refuge\" or \"protection,\" and is also used as an exclamation meaning \"God forbid!\" The connection lies in the concept of seeking or being in a place of safety, reflecting the root's emphasis on refuge. It expresses the desire to be protected from undesirable actions or outcomes, emphasizing reliance on Allah's (ﷻ) protection and a rejection of wrongdoing.",
  "4750": "مَعْذِرَةٌ and related words stem from the root ع-ذ-ر, with the root verb عَذَرَ meaning \"he excused,\" \"he pardoned,\" or \"he provided justification.\" مَعْذِرَةٌ means \"an excuse\" or \"an apology.\" It represents the act of presenting a justification or seeking forgiveness for a fault or mistake, directly connected to the root's concept of excusing and pardoning. This term highlights the importance of acknowledging errors and the humility involved in seeking pardon, emphasizing moral responsibility and the value of forgiveness in interpersonal relationships.",
  "4751": "مَفَاتِحُ and related words stem from the root ف-ت-ح, with the root verb فَتَحَ meaning \"he opened.\" مَفَاتِحُ (plural of مِفْتَاحٌ) means \"keys,\" referring to instruments that unlock or provide access. The connection lies in tools that facilitate opening, reflecting the root's concept of unlocking. This emphasizes the idea of gaining access or opening opportunities, whether in a literal or metaphorical sense, representing means to attain knowledge, resources, or solutions.",
  "4752": "مَقالِيدُ and related words stem from the root ق-ل-د, with the root verb قَلَدَ meaning \"he entrusted,\" \"he imitated,\" or \"he hung something around the neck.\" مَقالِيدُ refers to \"keys,\" symbolizing instruments of access, authority, and control. The connection lies in the act of entrusting someone with keys, which represents conferring responsibility or power, much like placing a necklace around the neck symbolizes honor, obligation, or commitment. This aligns with the root’s broader emphasis on entrusting and delegation, making keys a powerful metaphor for authority and responsibility.",
  "4753": "مُتَحَيِّزٌ and related words stem from the root ح-و-ز, with the root verb حازَ meaning \"he collected,\" \"he gathered,\" or \"he took possession.\" تَحَيَّزَ means \"he took a stance or position,\" \"he withdrew to a place,\" or \"he distinguished himself from others.\" مُتَحَيِّزٌ means \"one who takes a particular position.\" In this context, it refers to one who moves toward a group or aligns with a faction. It conveys the idea of shifting to a defined place or side with intent, whether as a strategic maneuver or a conscious decision to join a force. This emphasizes the deliberate act of taking refuge or positioning oneself, reinforcing the structured nature of movement in battle.",
  "4754": "مُتَصَدِّقِينَ and related words stem from the root ص-د-ق, with the root verb صَدَّقَ meaning \"he confirmed\" or \"he believed.\" تَصَدَّقَ means \"he gave charity\" or \"he voluntarily gave in support of others.\" مُتَصَدِّقِينَ means \"men who give charity,\" emphasizing the voluntary and deliberate nature of their giving. The root conveys themes of truthfulness, sincerity, and integrity, reflecting the honest intention behind charitable acts. مُتَصَدِّقِينَ highlights the individual’s willingness and initiative to contribute, portraying charity as a conscious and virtuous choice that embodies moral responsibility and compassion.",
  "4755": "مُحِيطَةٌ and related words stem from the root ح-و-ط, with the root verb حَاطَ meaning \"he surrounded or encompassed,\" \"he protected,\" or \"he comprehended or had full knowledge.\" مُحِيطَةٌ means \"encompassing\" or \"surrounding,\" often referring to calamities or divine retribution that completely encircle individuals. The root conveys the idea of complete enclosure, full understanding, or total control, often implying authority or preservation. This word emphasizes totality and inescapability, portraying how such circumstances envelop those targeted, leaving them without recourse.",
  "4756": "مُرْسَى and related words stem from the root ر-س-و, with the root verb رَسَا meaning \"it was firm,\" \"it was fixed,\" or \"it was anchored.\" مُرْسَى means \"anchorage\" or \"place of anchoring.\" The connection reflects the location or means by which something is made firm, embodying the root's essence of stability. It can symbolize points of security and grounding, emphasizing the need for firm foundations in life.",
  "4757": "مُقْوِينَ and related words stem from the root ق-و-ي, with the verb قَوِيَ meaning \"he was strong\" or \"he became strong.\" مُقْوِينَ refers to \"those who travel through barren lands,\" emphasizing the resilience and fortitude required to endure harsh and desolate conditions. This meaning directly ties to the root’s connotation of strength, highlighting the physical and mental endurance needed for survival and progress in such environments. The term reflects the broader root dimension of providing strength and support, as travelers often rely on both their own resilience and communal cooperation, highlighting themes of self-reliance and mutual assistance.",
  "4758": "مُنْتَهَىٰ and related words stem from the root ن-ه-ى, with the root verb نَهَى meaning \"he forbade\" or \"he prohibited.\" مُنْتَهَىٰ means \"ultimate\" or \"final.\" The connection lies in the concept of an end or boundary, directly relating to the root's idea of prohibition and setting limits. This term emphasizes the conclusion or the final boundary in a process, highlighting the moral lesson of recognizing limits and respecting final decisions.",
  "4759": "مُنْكِرُونَ and related words stem from the root ن-ك-ر, with the root verb نَكِرَ meaning \"he did not know,\" \"he found strange,\" or \"he disowned.\" The root conveys themes of unfamiliarity, rejection, and denial. مُنْكِرُونَ means \"those who deny\" or \"those not recognizing,\" describing individuals who reject, disown, or fail to acknowledge something, often because it is perceived as strange or unacceptable. The connection lies in the response of denial or rejection toward what is unfamiliar or contrary to one’s understanding or beliefs, reflecting the root’s emphasis on disapproval and estrangement.",
  "4760": "مِثْلُ and related words stem from the root م-ث-ل, with the root verb مَثَلَ meaning \"he resembled,\" \"he was like,\" or \"he set forth an example.\" مِثْلُ means \"like,\" or \"similar.\" The connection lies in denoting similarity or equivalence between entities, directly relating to the root's concept of resemblance. It emphasizes the idea of parity and the ability to compare or relate things based on shared characteristics.",
  "4761": "نَأَىٰ and related words stem from the root ن-أ-ي, with the root verb meaning \"he was distant,\" \"he withdrew,\" or \"he moved far away.\" This concept encompasses both physical distancing and metaphorical withdrawal, often implying separation from guidance or righteous deeds. The root also carries connotations of avoidance or turning away, reflecting actions that distance one from beneficial or virtuous paths. A related word from the same root, نُؤْيٌ, refers to a trench or protective barrier, symbolizing deliberate separation or isolation. This imagery reinforces the idea of distancing, whether as a protective measure or a sign of separation from what one seeks to avoid.",
  "4762": "The pronoun نَحْنُ is the first-person plural pronoun, meaning \"we\" or \"us.\" It signifies unity and collective identity, used when the speaker includes themselves with others. In the Qur'an, نَحْنُ is used as a plural of majesty by Allah (ﷻ), emphasizing His greatness and authority, not plurality. This royal usage reflects divine power, highlighting that all actions and decrees stem from His supreme will. Understanding this enhances the appreciation of the nuance behind the pronoun in Arabic, especially in its divine context.",
  "4763": "نَفَرٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ف-ر, with the root verb نَفَرَ meaning \"he departed,\" \"he set out,\" or \"he fled.\" نَفَرٌ means \"a group of men,\" \"a company,\" or \"people,\" often implying a collective that has mobilized or departed together. The connection lies in the root’s theme of purposeful movement or departure, highlighting the dynamic nature of a group acting as a unit, often with urgency or intention. This term reflects the root's emphasis on action and unity in collective effort or journey.",
  "4764": "نَقَمُوا and related words stem from the root ن-ق-م, with the root verb نَقَمَ meaning \"he resented,\" \"he avenged,\" or \"he was indignant.\" نَقَمُوا means \"they resented\" or \"they were indignant,\" signifying collective dissatisfaction or anger. The root conveys themes of grievance, indignation, and retaliation, often stemming from a sense of perceived injustice. نَقَمُوا reflects a shared emotional response of resentment or dissatisfaction that may lead to acts of reprisal or opposition.",
  "4765": "نَقْصٌ and related words stem from the root ن-ق-ص, with the root verb نَقَصَ meaning \"he diminished\" or \"he decreased.\" نَقْصٌ means \"decrease,\" \"deficiency,\" or \"shortcoming.\" The connection lies in the concept of reduction or the absence of completeness, directly relating to the root's meaning. It highlights the notion of imperfection or insufficiency in something.",
  "4766": "نُسِفَتْ and related words stem from the root ن-س-ف, with the root verb نَسَفَ meaning \"he scattered,\" \"he winnowed,\" or \"he pulverized.\" نُسِفَتْ is a passive form meaning \"it was scattered\" or \"it was pulverized,\" describing an object being broken apart and dispersed by an external force. The root emphasizes the thoroughness of disintegration and the subsequent dispersal of fragments. نُسِفَتْ conveys an image of complete obliteration, such as mountains or objects reduced to dust and scattered widely, highlighting the power and intensity of the act. This term reflects the root’s broader themes of destruction, dispersion, and the unstoppable nature of certain forces.",
  "4767": "نُنَكِّسْ and related words stem from the root ن-ك-س, with the root verb نَكَسَ meaning \"he inverted\" or \"reversed.\" نُنَكِّسْ means \"We reverse\" or \"We cause to decline.\" The usage signifies actively causing something to regress or turn back, connecting to the root's idea of inversion and degradation. This conveys the concept of deliberate alteration of a state, leading to decline or deterioration, reflecting the transformative power inherent in the root meaning.",
  "4768": "نِدَاءٌ and related words stem from the root ن-د-ي, with the root verb نَدَا meaning \"he called,\" \"he proclaimed,\" or \"he invited.\" نِدَاءٌ means \"a call,\" \"proclamation,\" or \"announcement,\" referring to the act of calling out loudly to convey a message. The root centers on summoning and drawing attention, with نِدَاءٌ encapsulating the essence of vocal communication, emphasizing the importance of the message and the act of delivering it.",
  "4769": "هَيْئَةٌ and related words stem from the root ه-ي-أ, with the root verb هَآءَ meaning \"he was of good form or appearance,\" and هَيَّأَ meaning \"he prepared\" or \"he arranged.\" هَيْئَةٌ means \"form,\" \"shape,\" or \"appearance,\" referring to the outward configuration or condition of something. The root conveys themes of preparation, arrangement, and readiness, emphasizing the intentional effort that results in an organized state. هَيْئَةٌ highlights how deliberate preparation leads to an observable form or structure, symbolizing the relationship between internal planning and external manifestation. This term highlights the harmony between purpose and appearance.",
  "4770": "The pronoun هُمْ is the third-person masculine plural pronoun, meaning \"they\" or \"them.\" It refers to a group of males or a mixed-gender group and can function as both a subject or object pronoun in sentences. In the Qur'an, هُمْ often appears to indicate collective responsibility or action, highlighting the shared nature of deeds, whether good or bad. Its usage also helps emphasize communal or collective identities in contexts of moral guidance or divine address, highlighting that actions and consequences often extend beyond the individual.",
  "4771": "The pronoun هُنَّ is the third-person feminine plural pronoun, meaning \"they\" or \"them\" when referring to a group of females. It serves as both a subject and object pronoun in sentences. In the Qur'an, هُنَّ is used to refer to female groups, such as in narratives about women or collective feminine entities. Its usage highlights the distinct identity and agency of female groups, ensuring precision in gender-specific references.",
  "4772": "The pronoun هُوَ is the third-person masculine singular pronoun, meaning \"he\" or \"him,\" used to refer to a single male. It functions as both a subject and object pronoun in sentences. In the Qur'an, هُوَ frequently refers to Allah (ﷻ), emphasizing His singularity and transcendence. In Arabic, it is important to note that هُوَ is the default pronoun for singular forms and is not tied to gender in the human sense when referring to Allah (ﷻ). The usage reflects His absolute oneness without implying any male or female characteristics, as Allah (ﷻ) transcends all human attributes.",
  "4773": "The pronoun هِىَ is the third-person feminine singular pronoun, meaning \"she\" or \"her,\" used to refer to a single female. It serves as both a subject and object pronoun, depending on the sentence structure. In the Qur'an, هِىَ is used to refer to individual female figures, highlighting their actions or attributes. Its usage ensures clarity when referring to feminine subjects, distinguishing them from masculine or plural pronouns.",
  "4774": "الْوَاقِعَةُ and related words stem from the root و-ق-ع, with the root verb وَقَعَ meaning \"he fell\" or \"it occurred.\" الْوَاقِعَةُ translates as \"the Occurrence\" or \"the Event,\" emphasizing an inevitable and impactful happening. The connection lies in the certainty and profound effect of an event that is destined to \"fall upon\" people. In the Qur'anic context, الْوَاقِعَةُ specifically refers to the Day of Resurrection, highlighting its inevitability and transformative consequences, which align with the root's core concept of unavoidable and momentous occurrences.",
  "4775": "وُثْقَى and related words stem from the root و-ث-ق, with the root verb وَثَقَ meaning \"he trusted\" or \"he was firm.\" وُثْقَى means \"firmest,\" \"most secure,\" or \"strongest bond.\" The connection lies in the utmost degree of firmness and security, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on strength and reliability. This term highlights the strongest forms of commitment or trust, often used to describe an unbreakable bond or the firmest handhold in faith.",
  "4776": "يَجْرِمَنَّكُمْ and related words stem from the root ج-ر-م, with the root verb جَرَمَ meaning \"he cut off,\" \"he committed a crime,\" or \"he induced or incited,\" particularly towards sin or wrongdoing. يَجْرِمَنَّكُمْ means \"to incite you,\" emphasizing the act of provoking or pressuring others into transgression. The root conveys themes of severance and forceful movement, reflecting the dangers of being driven toward moral or ethical violations. يَجْرِمَنَّكُمْ connects to the broader root concept of actions that cause separation from righteousness or upright behavior.",
  "4777": "يَطَئُونَ and related words stem from the root و-ط-أ, with the root verb وَطِئَ meaning \"he trod upon\" or \"he stepped.\" يَطَئُونَ means \"they tread,\" \"they step upon,\" or \"they walk on.\" The connection to the root emphasizes the ongoing action of stepping or treading, highlighting movement, progress, and the paths one takes. It can also metaphorically signify engaging in actions or ventures that leave a mark or have significant consequences. This highlights the root's broader dimensions of motion, interaction, and the transformative effects of deliberate action.",
  "4778": "يَغِيظُ and related words stem from the root غ-ي-ظ, with the root verb غَاظَ meaning \"he provoked anger\" or \"he caused rage.\" يَغِيظُ means \"he enrages,\" \"he provokes anger,\" or \"he causes intense irritation,\" emphasizing the act of actively stirring strong emotions in others. Broader root meanings highlight boiling agitation and overwhelming feelings caused by provocation. The connection lies in the root’s focus on causing internal agitation, reflecting the powerful impact actions can have on others' emotional states.",
  "4779": "يَفْجُرَ and related words stem from the root ف-ج-ر, with the root verb فَجَرَ meaning \"he acted immorally\" or \"he broke the bounds.\" يَفْجُرَ means \"he transgresses\" or \"he commits wickedness.\" The connection lies in the ongoing action of exceeding moral limits, directly relating to the root's concept of breaking forth beyond acceptable boundaries. This term emphasizes the active and perhaps habitual engagement in immoral behavior, highlighting the persistence of transgression.",
  "4780": "يَمٌّ and related words stem from the root ي-م-م, with the root verb يَمَّمَ meaning \"he aimed for\" or \"he directed himself towards.\" يَمٌّ means \"sea\" or \"vast expanse of water.\" The connection lies in the idea of direction and journey, as the sea represents a vast path one undertakes. It symbolizes life's journey and the pursuit of destinations, aligning with the root's emphasis on intention and movement.",
  "4781": "يَنۢبَغِي and related words stem from the root ب-غ-ى, with the root verb بَغَىٰ meaning \"he sought, desired, or exceeded beyond limits.\" يَنۢبَغِي means \"it is befitting,\" often used to indicate what is appropriate or morally justified. The root conveys themes of pursuit and boundaries, connecting يَنۢبَغِي to the idea of maintaining actions within proper limits. In the Qur'an, it is frequently negated to stress what is not justified or fitting, serving as guidance to prevent behaviors that could devolve into excess or transgression (بَغْيٌ), reinforcing the importance of restraint and propriety.",
  "4782": "يُحْمَىٰ and related words stem from the root ح-م-ي, with the root verb حَمَى meaning \"he protected from harm,\" or \"he made forbidden,\" and حَمِيَ meaning \"it was hot,\" or \"he was enraged,\" or \"it was forbidden.\" يُحْمَىٰ is a passive form meaning \"it is heated.\" The root reflects themes of heat, intensity, and protection, often signifying barriers that shield or separate. The connection to يُحْمَىٰ lies in the act of subjecting something to intense heat while confining it within, shielding the outside from the effects of the heat. This term captures the transformative and punishing aspects of intense heat, illustrating its role in both refining and containing as part of divine justice.",
  "4783": "يَدَّبَّرُوا and related words stem from the root د-ب-ر, with the root verb دَبَرَ meaning \"it came after or followed\" or \"he turned his back or went away.\" دَبَّرَ means \"he planned\" or \"he managed,\" while يَدَّبَّرُوا means \"they contemplate,\" emphasizing deep, deliberate reflection and careful evaluation. The root revolves around sequence, planning, and consequence, conveying the idea of looking beyond the immediate, understanding outcomes, and engaging in thoughtful deliberation. The connection highlights how contemplation involves foresight, assessing what follows, and making sense of matters with wisdom and depth.",
  "4784": "يُمَحِّصُ and related words stem from the root م-ح-ص, with the root verb مَحَصَ meaning \"he purified,\" \"he tested,\" or \"he examined thoroughly.\" يُمَحِّصُ means \"he purifies\" or \"he tests thoroughly.\" The connection lies in the process of refining by removing impurities or weaknesses, reflecting the root's concept of purification and thorough examination. It emphasizes the transformative power of trials in revealing true character and strengthening one's qualities.",
  "4785": "يُوَفِّقُ and related words stem from the root و-ف-ق, with the root verb وَفَقَ meaning \"he agreed\" or \"he was suitable,\" and the verb وَفَّقَ meaning \"he made successful\" or \"he guided rightly.\" يُوَفِّقُ means \"He grants success,\" \"He guides rightly,\" or \"He facilitates harmony.\" The connection lies in seeking Allah's (ﷻ) assistance to achieve success, make correct choices, or bring about accord, reflecting the root's focus on alignment with righteousness. This highlights the reliance on Allah's (ﷻ) grace for guidance, reminding us that true success and harmony come from His support and blessings."
};
